<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Rises Against Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar shoved the euro to within a whisper  
of its lowest level ever Friday as investors continued to support 
the bullish U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar slipped from its seven-month high against the  
Japanese yen as traders took profits and repositioned their bets. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0568, falling from $1.0623 Thursday.  
On April 30, the euro reached $1.0540, its lowest level since its 
January launch. The dollar slumped to 124.01 yen from 124.40 yen 
Thursday, the second day the U.S. currency rose to a seven-month 
high against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Without fresh economic data or political commentary for  
guidance, traders simply looked at the economic realities: The U.S. 
economy remains strongest with a bull market still occupying Wall 
Street, Japan is mired in recession and Europe hasn't harnessed its 
energies to recover from its doldrums. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. economy is so healthy, the Federal Reserve issued an  
alert Tuesday that it is considering raising interest rates to 
lasso the unharnessed economy and tame inflation before it can 
surface and create damage. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think basically it's the fundamentals that are in play,''  
said Elena Shperling, chief currency trader at Banco di Sicilia. 
``The U.S. economy is strong. As a result, the dollar is 
stronger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, outgoing Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and  
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan assured Congress Thursday 
that the world economy is on track for full recovery from the 
turmoil that began nearly two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin also said that the United States was not going to use  
foreign exchange policy to fix the widening trade deficit. The 
Commerce Department announced Thursday that the trade deficit broke 
a record for the third straight month in March. 
</P>
<P>
	Once markets opened in Asia and Europe Friday, ``a lot of people  
took a look at that and took the dollar up,'' Shperling said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading, the dollar was quoted at 1.5166 Swiss Francs,  
up from 1.5090; and 1.4610 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4662. The 
British pound fell to $1.6013 from $1.6075. 
</P>
<P>
	The currencies of the 11 countries that have switched to the  
euro are no longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a 
fixed rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on the euro's latest exchange rate, the dollar was worth:  
1.8508 German marks, up from 1.8413; 6.2073 French francs, up from 
6.1767; and 1,831.50 Italian lire, up from 1,821.49. 
</P>
</TEXT>
