<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reds OK Lease for New Ballpark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- In one of her last acts as the Cincinnati Reds  
owner, Marge Schott signed up her team for a new ballpark. 
</P>
<P>
	Schott attended a news conference at Cinergy Field today to  
announce that she has signed a 30-year lease for a new ballpark 
along the Ohio River that will open in 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	The news conference near the pitchers' mound amounted to a  
passing of the torch. Cincinnati financier Carl Lindner, who will 
take over for Schott once major league baseball approves the team's 
sale, stood behind Schott during the 20-minute session. 
</P>
<P>
	Reds managing executive John Allen, who has been running the  
team since 1996 while Schott serves her latest punishments from 
baseball, said revenues from the stadium will allow the club to 
become competitive again. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds are located in one of baseball's smallest markets and  
have not been to the playoffs since 1995, the last year before they 
started slashing their payroll. 
</P>
<P>
	``What this signifies with the signing of this lease is we now  
have the capabilities to go to the next level,'' Allen said. 
</P>
<P>
	The lease agreement removes the last major hurdle to getting the  
project underway. Architects are working on a design for the 
45,000-seat ballpark, which will overlap the left field seats at 
Cinergy. A preliminary rendering is expected in July. 
</P>
<P>
	A $403 million stadium project for the Cincinnati Bengals is  
under construction just west of the stadium and is expected to be 
finished for the 2000 NFL season. Voters approved a sales tax hike 
to build both stadiums in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Signing the stadium lease was one of Schott's final acts as the  
Reds' controlling partner. She agreed to sell all but one of her 6 1/2 
shares to Lindner and two other limited partners for $67 million on 
April 20, ending her 15-year reign. 
</P>
<P>
	Major league baseball has to approve the sale before the team  
switches hands. Lindner declined to answer questions about the 
team's future today because the sale is pending. 
</P>
<P>
	Lindner and Schott walked onto the field side-by-side. Schott  
used a cane -- she's still hampered by a broken hip suffered a year 
ago -- and leaned on a table for support throughout the 20-minute 
session. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Schott's first public appearance since she agreed to sell  
the team. She's been back to the stadium only a few times since 
then. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if it was a bittersweet moment, Schott said, ``Kind of,  
yeah. But you've got to do things that baseball wants you to do. 
It's a boys' club.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
