<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amazon.com Backs Off Book Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Responding to e-mail complaints, Amazon.com says  
it will restore a book critical of the Scientology movement to its 
online catalog. 
</P>
<P>
	The book, ``A Piece of Blue Sky,'' by British writer Jon Atack,  
was banned by a British court following a successful 1995 
defamation lawsuit against Atack. 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon pulled the book in February, but said Thursday it would  
reinstate it. 
</P>
<P>
	``While the decision in February seemed the right thing to do at  
the time, we thought we could do better by blocking (sale of) it in 
(Britain) rather than everywhere,'' Amazon spokesman Bill Curry 
said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Amazon's policy is to offer every book from every  
publisher, and still remain in compliance with the laws where it 
does business. 
</P>
<P>
	Curry said the book would be able to be shipped in a matter of  
days, after coding is put in place to make sure copies aren't 
shipped to British addresses. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Amazon worked to find a way to restore the book to its  
site after its absence was noted by Wired News, and complaints 
began arriving on Amazon e-mail. 
</P>
<P>
	Atack was sued in 1995 by a woman named in a single paragraph of  
the book. The court decided that paragraph was defamatory and ruled 
that copies of the book containing the offending material could not 
be distributed in Great Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	``A Piece of Blue Sky'' is about the Scientology movement from  
its creation in 1959 to the death of its founder, L. Ron Hubbard, 
in 1986. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
