<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Italy Fears New Political Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- A briefcase lying on a bloodied sidewalk. A grieving  
widow. A commando communique. 
</P>
<P>
	The killing of a labor official, claimed by the militant Red  
Brigades, terrifies Italians, who worried Friday about a possible 
return to the political violence that marked the 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	The question is, why now?  
</P>
<P>
	Italy's economy and government are remarkably stable after years  
of turmoil. But government attempts to bolster the economy by 
winning concessions from labor and its backing of NATO's air 
campaign in Yugoslavia have been denounced by the far left. 
</P>
<P>
	Both issues figured in the 28-page manifesto left by the Red  
Brigades in a trash bin in Rome claiming Thursday's slaying of 
Massimo D'Antona, who was shot repeatedly in the heart as he walked 
to work. 
</P>
<P>
	At D'Antona's funeral Friday, Italian leaders vowed there would  
be no replay of the ``years of lead,'' when assassinations and 
bombings by terrorists from the far left and right terrified the 
country in the 1970s and early '80s. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whoever did the shooting shouldn't fool themselves,''  
D'Antona's boss, Labor Minister Antonio Bassolino, told the funeral 
congregation. ``We haven't gone back 20 years. Italy wants to go 
ahead with new social and labor rules.'' 
</P>
<P>
	D'Antona, he said, was a man ``ready for dialogue, a leftist and  
a reformist. That's why he was struck down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Italy's Cabinet approved an employment package that  
D'Antona had finished just hours before his death. 
</P>
<P>
	A university professor in labor law, D'Antona was a chief  
architect of labor reforms that included an agreement by industry 
and unions to create more jobs by encouraging part-time work. 
</P>
<P>
	Italy has also been enjoying a rare show of cooperation between  
the center-left government and the center-right opposition, 
including on electoral reforms aimed at bringing Rome more in line 
with the rest of Western Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides were also cooperating in Italy's participation in the  
NATO air campaign in Yugoslavia, which has made extensive use of 
Italian air bases. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Brigades' most notorious attack, in 1978, struck at  
another figure of cooperation -- former Premier Aldo Moro, who, just 
before his kidnapping and killing, brokered the ``historic 
compromise'' in which Communists pledged to work together in 
Parliament with the Christian Democrat-dominated coalition. 
</P>
<P>
	Two decades later, that accord helped pave the way for the  
appointment of the country's first former Communist premier, 
Massimo D'Alema. 
</P>
<P>
	The militants' goal during their bloody campaign in the 1970s  
was nothing short of destruction of the Italian state and anarchy. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the latest attack, D'Alema said: ``We don't want to  
underestimate their message and intent to destabilize our country 
in this delicate moment. But this is a country that will not let 
itself be sent backward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	D'Antona's killing came 11 years after the Red Brigades' last  
claimed assassination, that of a senator, and six years after its 
last claimed act of violence, a bombing at the U.S. air base at 
Aviano, Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	In Parliament on Wednesday, the opposition helped D'Alema beat  
back an attempt by some in his government to urge a unilateral 
cease-fire in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	And last week, the center-left and the opposition pulled  
together to elect the nation's president in a first-round vote -- 
only the third time in Italy's postwar history that has happened. 
The new head of state, Carlo Azeglio Ciampi, a political 
independent, is a staunch backer of political reform. 
</P>
<P>
	In its manifesto claiming D'Antona's killing, the Red Brigades  
vowed to ``attack and dismantle ... the imperialist state'' and 
target NATO for its ``imperialist war.'' 
</P>
<P>
	D'Antona had been targeted as a shaper of ``neo-corporate  
politics,'' the manifesto said, using the Marxist language of 
decades ago. 
</P>
<P>
	A crackdown after Moro's death and the end of the Cold War  
helped cool the guns and passions of the old Red Brigades. The last 
imprisoned major leader, Renato Curcio, a Brigades founder, won 
release last October after 24 years behind bars. 
</P>
<P>
	However, many Red Brigades members were never captured, with  
many believed to be living abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
