<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Greg Maddux Is a Master in a Slump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Greg Maddux has only himself to blame.  
</P>
<P>
	He's the one who set the bar so high by winning four straight Cy  
Young awards. He's the one who pushed expectations to the limit 
with two of the greatest seasons in pitching history. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, with his ERA hovering above 5.00, everyone wants to know  
what's wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	``I realize that I'm probably under a different standard than  
most pitchers, but that's something I live with,'' the Atlanta 
right-hander said after Braves lost to the Chicago Cubs 6-5 
Thursday night in 12 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Maddux got off to a 4-0 start for the first time in his career,  
but he hasn't won in more than three weeks while his ERA soared to 
5.02 and his record dropped to 4-3. 
</P>
<P>
	In his last four starts, covering 24 1-3 innings, he's given up  
22 earned runs -- a staggering 8.14 ERA. In his latest start, he 
surrendered nine hits and five runs to the Cubs in seven innings, 
avoiding his fourth straight loss only because Gerald Williams hit 
a ninth-inning home run to tie the score. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel good,'' Maddux insisted. ``I feel capable and I feel  
like I'm concentrating. I feel like I'm doing the things I need to 
do to throw that last pitch. But when I have thrown it, it's gotten 
fouled off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Or worse.  
</P>
<P>
	In the first inning Thursday night, Maddux got two strikes on  
Sammy Sosa, missed badly on the next pitch, then ``made a bad pitch 
and give up a home run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not like it's the first year it's happened,'' Maddux  
said. ``It's been that way for a while.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's true. Maddux was 18-9 and won his fourth ERA title (2.22)  
last season, but he was a mortal 3-3 with a 3.93 ERA the final two 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	Maddux, who turned 33 last month, is probably the top pitcher of  
this generation along with Roger Clemens. He won the NL Cy Young 
Award every season from 1992-95, setting landmark standards the 
final two seasons by going 16-6 with a 1.56 ERA, followed by 19-2 
and 1.63. 
</P>
<P>
	He hasn't had an ERA over 3.00 since 1991 and his 146 wins are  
the most in the majors over the last nine years. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, suddenly, he's just another pitcher -- or worse. Maddux has  
given up 88 hits in 57 1-3 innings and opponents are batting .351 
against him, the highest average allowed by any National League 
starter. 
</P>
<P>
	Maddux said he's failing to put away hitters after he gets ahead  
in the count. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've just got to regroup, get it together, get it going  
again,'' he said. ``There's still a lot of time left.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubs chuckled at the suggestion that Maddux is on the  
downside. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a joke that they're (the media) trying to find  
something wrong with him,'' said Chicago pitcher Steve Trachsel, 
who beat Maddux 5-1 on a six-hitter last week. ``He's just not 
hitting his spots. I wish I had that kind of problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the same guy I've seen. Nothing's changed,'' Sosa added.  
``He'll be all right. He'll be OK. He'll probably win the Cy Young 
again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Maddux, it's just a matter of making fewer bad pitches.  
</P>
<P>
	``I just feel like I'm making 20 mistakes a game instead of 12  
or 14,'' he said. ``I'm just not getting away with as many 
mistakes.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
