<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airlines Want Hong Kong Fees Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Hong Kong is losing its role as Asia's leading  
international aviation hub because of exorbitant airport fees, a 
report by airline representatives said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong's nearly year-old Chek Lap Kok airport has lost 82  
weekly flights, resulting in estimated losses of $1.5 billion since 
Chek Lap Kok airport's opening last July, a report by the Board of 
Airline Representatives said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The suspension of such a large number of services is  
unprecedented in the history of Hong Kong's aviation industry,'' it 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Higher charges are encouraging international tour operators to  
use other cheaper hubs in the region as springboards for regional 
travel itineraries,'' said the report prepared for the 
legislature's economic services committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Airlines have been pressuring the airport to cut its charges.  
</P>
<P>
	Airport charges jumped 34.1 percent for large planes and 14.7  
percent for smaller planes since the new airport opened last July 
at the height of Asia's financial crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Many other leading airports have even higher charges, including  
Japan's Kansai, Narita and Osaka airports, London's Heathrow 
airport, and airports in mainland China. 
</P>
<P>
	But the charges to use Hong Kong airport are nearly twice as  
much as Singapore's Changi Airport, Hong Kong's key rival as Asia's 
aviation hub. Singapore slashed charges by 10 percent last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Since its July opening, Scandinavian Airlines Systems, Varig  
Brazilian Airlines and Russia's Transaero have suspended services 
in Chek Lap Kok airport because the routes had become unprofitable. 
</P>
<P>
	``International airlines do have a choice. The high prices would  
deter airlines from launching new flights and cut existing 
flights,'' said Quince Chong, the corporate communications manager 
at Hong Kong-based Cathay Pacific Airways. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Donnelley, a spokesman for the Airport Authority, the  
public body running the airport, called the allegations unfair. 
</P>
<P>
	He argued that airport fees contribute to an average of just 4.3  
percent of airline's operating costs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Airlines won't sway their decision to come here or not because  
of that 1 percent saving,'' said Donnelley. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
