<HEADLINE> Earnhardt Not Considering Retirement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- Dale Earnhardt doesn't want anyone to think  
he's pondering retirement just because his contract to drive for 
Richard Childress expires after next season. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnhardt, 48, said Friday that Childress already has begun  
discussions about keeping the team together, including primary 
sponsor GM Goodwrench Service, through the 2003 Winston Cup season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Things are going to start happening here soon as far as which  
direction we're going to go,'' Earnhardt said. ``If I can race good 
and win and feel good about myself, about my driving, I think I can 
still do it. I'm there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earnhardt won the last of his seven Winston Cup championships in  
1994, and just two of his 72 career race victories have come in the 
past three seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``I pretty much feel like I'm a top-five driver,'' said  
Earnhardt, who won at Talladega, Ala., last month and is ninth in 
this year's points standings. ``I can get in there and do it with 
them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One bonus for Earnhardt staying around in Winston Cup racing  
would be getting to compete against Dale Jr., 24, the reigning 
Busch Series champion who is scheduled to move up to the top 
circuit full time next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's unbelievable the way your kids grow up and the way things  
change over the years,'' the elder Earnhardt said. ``I'm having fun 
with it, enjoying seeing him do what he's doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WINSTON OPEN: Tony Stewart and Mike Skinner won 25-lap heat  
races Friday night to determine the starting order for the Winston 
Open, a qualifying race for The Winston, Saturday night's all-star 
event at Lowe's Motor Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner of the 50-lap Winston Open earns the 21st and final  
spot on the starting grid for The Winston, a 70-lap affair that has 
a purse of more than $1.3 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart started on the pole and led the whole way in his heat,  
finishing about 700 yards ahead of Wally Dallenbach. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after the race, Stewart was driven to a nearby airport  
and flown to Indiana, where he was scheduled to try to qualify for 
the Indianapolis 500 on Saturday morning. Immediately after Indy 
time trials, he planned to fly back to Charlotte in time for the 
Winston Open. 
</P>
<P>
	Skinner led the final 23 laps of the opening heat and finished  
about 1,000 yards ahead of Jimmy Spencer on the 1.5-mile, 
high-banked trioval. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no cautions in either race.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	NEW LOOK: Continuing a trend that is becoming increasingly  
popular at the all-star weekend, 10 teams have adorned their cars 
with special paint schemes or sponsor logos for The Winston and its 
related activities. 
</P>
<P>
	Sporting different looks this weekend are the cars of Brett  
Bodine, Dale Earnhardt, Jeff Gordon, Dale Jarrett, Terry Labonte, 
Sterling Marlin, Mark Martin, Jimmy Spencer, Darrell Waltrip and 
Michael Waltrip. 
</P>
<P>
	Probably the most recognizable of the paint schemes was on the  
Chevrolet of Earnhardt, who was sporting the yellow and blue 
Wrangler jeans colors that were on his cars from 1981-87. 
</P>
