<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arrest Unrelated to Fugitive Hunt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCK SPRINGS, Wyo. (AP) -- Two brothers arrested Friday in a  
Wyoming robbery are not the fugitives authorities have been 
searching for in connection with the killing of a Colorado police 
officer nearly a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The men, arrested in western Kansas, matched the description of  
two survivalists who have eluded authorities since last year. Hours 
after their arrest, the FBI confirmed their identities and said 
they were not the fugitives, Alan ``Monte'' Pilon and Jason McVean. 
</P>
<P>
	Brendon James Johnson, 21, and Raymond Kendall Johnson, 31, both  
of Hillsdale, Mich., were being held in a Colby, Kan., jail and 
will be charged Saturday, the Fremont County attorney's office 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The robbery on Wednesday fueled speculation about a link to  
Pilon and McVean. 
</P>
<P>
	For the better part of a year, authorities have been frustrated  
in their search for Pilon and McVean, accused of killing officer 
Dale Claxton during a traffic stop in Cortez, Colo., on May 29, 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Claxton died after he tried to stop three men in a stolen water  
truck. They opened fire with automatic weapons, hitting Claxton and 
his cruiser 26 times before he could even unbuckle his seat belt. 
</P>
<P>
	One suspect died of a self-inflicted gunshot days later in Utah.  
The other two were chased by more than 500 officers at one point 
into the desert country of Four Corners, where New Mexico, 
Colorado, Utah and Arizona meet. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, two men robbed the Rock Shop in Wyoming, a  
combination store, bar and restaurant about four miles east of 
South Pass City and some 300 miles north of Cortez. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspects, who were wearing military boots and ski masks,  
took about $500 and escaped in a stolen white truck, which was 
crashed into a ditch near Rock Springs. Sheriff's deputies believe 
the two fled on foot and then jumped an eastbound Union Pacific 
train early Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheriff Dave King said authorities found evidence the two men  
had been camping in the area for several days. In the truck, they 
seized parts of night vision equipment, sleeping bags, body armor 
and ammunition. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said a caretaker at a plant near where the truck was  
ditched identified the two men who fled the truck as Pilon and 
McVean based on photographs. 
</P>
<P>
	Cortez Police Chief Roy Lane said he was disappointed by the  
false report. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've said all along, and I still continue to say that they are  
not too far away from the Four Corners area,'' he said. ``I think 
they are close by.'' 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
