<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Finish Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks closed slightly higher today as  
investors fetched bargains following a sharp downturn in share 
prices. The dollar dropped against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 92.99  
points, or 0.57 percent, to finish the day at 16,292.98. On 
Thursday, the average closed up 71.81 points, or 0.44 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
exchange's first section was up 7.80 points, or 0.60 percent, to 
1,309.67. The TOPIX closed up 1.26 points, or 0.10 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar slipped against the yen after early gains, falling to  
123.76, 0.72 yen below its level late Thursday in Tokyo and also 
below its late New York level of 124.40 overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The greenback had gained early today following remarks from U.S.  
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin that the United States had no 
intention to use its currency as a trade policy tool. The remark 
indicated the government had no plans to make American exports 
cheaper by undermining the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	But the dollar quickly met stiff selling by U.S. banks, some  
large Asian players and large Japanese brokerages seeking to lock 
in profits, dealers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar ranged between 123.63 yen and 124.60 yen in today's  
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, the Nikkei 225 briefly dropped below 16,000  
for the first time since April 1. But with the index down more than 
6 percent from a high set on May 6, further downside risk was 
limited, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The 16,000 level provides a very good opportunity for domestic  
institutional investors to start new investment for this fiscal 
year,'' said Tsuyoshi Nomaguchi, a strategist at Daiwa Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, players don't expect a quick rebound in share  
prices either, especially since the U.S. Federal Reserve's hint at 
an interest rate hike has cooled off the action on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the First Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange was  
estimated at 565.65 million shares, up from 550.36 million shares 
Thursday. Advancing issues outnumbered retreaters 613 to 585, while 
114 issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	Some investors bought shares on dips after the Nikkei average  
closed below 17,000 points Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Blue chips were mixed. TDK, Tokyo Electron, Kyocera, Honda,  
Nippon Telegraph and Telephone and Fuji Photo were weaker, while 
Sony, NEC, Toyota and Bridgestone were up. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares in banks and brokerages are generally higher after recent  
declines. Major commercial banks will announce earnings results 
later today. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 131.17 yen, down  
from 132.44 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 212 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.345 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.295 percent, 
driving its price down to 101.37 yen from 101.82 yen. 


</P>
</TEXT>
