<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Told To Review Phone-Fee Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A battle over fees that make up a big part of  
long-distance bills is headed back to federal regulators. A federal 
appeals court said the way the fees were calculated wasn't 
adequately explained. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia on Friday  
ordered the Federal Communications Commission to review part of a 
1997 decision that resulted in lower phone bills for millions of 
Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	A ``very pleased'' United States Telephone Association, which  
represents local phone companies, had contested the FCC's decision 
in court saying the agency's calculations made unjustified cuts to 
the fees. AT&AMP;T and MCI also challenged the 1997 calculations in 
court but for opposite reasons, arguing the agency should have 
adjusted the formula to result in deeper cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said the FCC did not adequately explain certain  
changes to a complex formula that affects the so-called access 
payments that long-distance companies pay local phone companies to 
connect calls. 
</P>
<P>
	The access fees, which are typically passed along to  
long-distance customers, have been going down and now make up about 
30 cents of every $1 of long-distance charges. 
</P>
<P>
	When the FCC periodically orders these fees to be reduced, the  
savings are supposed to be passed along to long-distance customers. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, the FCC made adjustments that caused the access fees to  
be reduced by $1.7 billion to better reflect local phone companies' 
costs to connect long-distance calls. 
</P>
<P>
	Specifically, the court today disagreed with the FCC's rationale  
for making those changes to the so-called ``X Factor.'' Expressed 
as a percentage, the factor aims at ensuring that as a local phone 
company's productivity improves, the company would receive less 
from these access payments. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years, the factor has forced an automatic annual  
reduction in the fees. 
</P>
<P>
	Local phone companies ``argue that the FCC did not give a  
rational explanation ... and we agree,'' the court said in its 
opinion. 
</P>
<P>
	The court didn't say whether the FCC should have made specific  
adjustments that would have resulted in either lower or higher 
access fees, just that some FCC calculations needed to be further 
explained. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC will ask the court to suspend its ruling, a commission  
spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision -- assuming it stands -- could affect how the FCC  
adjusts access fees later this year, telecommunications attorneys 
said. The fees are still expected to be reduced, but now it's 
unclear by how much. 
</P>
<P>
	The court's decision also could have implications for how the  
FCC compensates for the cost of cheap Internet hookups for schools 
and libraries. The FCC is supposed to approve $2.25 billion in new 
money for the Internet program on Thursday. Payment for this 
program is also passed on to consumers in their phone bills. But a 
new round of expected access fee reductions are supposed to offset 
any potential phone bill increases caused by the Internet program. 
</P>
<P>
	FCC Commissioner Harold Furchtgott-Roth, who disagrees with the  
way the FCC pays for the Internet program, said phone bills will go 
up to pay for the Internet subsidies if the court's action delays 
this new round of access reductions. Senior FCC officials 
disagreed. 
</P>
<P>
	The access issue has pitted local phone companies, such as the  
Baby Bells and GTE, against long-distance companies, such as AT&AMP;T 
and consumer groups, which want deep cuts in access fees. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling is likely to be used by both sides to advocate their  
position before the FCC. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will use this as an opening to go back and argue for much  
deeper cuts in pricing,'' said Gene Kimmelman, co-director of the 
Consumers Union's Washington office. AT&AMP;T agreed. 
</P>
<P>
	Local phone company BellSouth believes the ruling ``cries out  
for the FCC to use it as an opportunity to address both access 
charge reform and universal service subsidies in a comprehensive 
way,'' said attorney Robert Sutherland. 
</P>
<P>
	A portion of access fees -- there's debate over the exact amount  
-- helps make local phone service more affordable. The FCC is in the 
process of trying to determine how much as part of an overhaul of 
phone subsidies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
