<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senators Push Rural Internet Access </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Farm-state Senate Democrats are asking federal  
regulators to consider subsidizing high-speed Internet access in 
rural areas, saying better telecommunications are critical to 
economic survival. 
</P>
<P>
	The money would come from fees that are imposed on  
telecommunications companies and typically passed on to their 
customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are determined not to end up with a country of haves and  
have-nots with respect to advanced telecommunications,'' Sen. Byron 
Dorgan, D-N.D., said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a 1996 law, rural areas are supposed to have  
telecommunications services that are ``reasonably comparable'' to 
those in cities, but it was left up to the FCC to decide how to do 
that. 
</P>
<P>
	FCC officials said they were already studying ways to improve  
rural service. ``We're looking at how we can bridge the digital 
divide,'' said spokeswoman Joy Howell. 
</P>
<P>
	The government is handing out nearly $1.7 billion in subsidies  
to schools and libraries, including those in rural areas and inner 
cities, for a variety of telecommunications needs, including 
Internet access. 
</P>
<P>
	FCC Chairman Bill Kennard recently called for $2.25 billion to  
fund the program in its second year. That is generating criticism 
mostly from Republicans on Capitol Hill, because of fears that it 
could raise phone bills. 
</P>
<P>
	The senators say farmers, rural businesses and small-town  
health-care facilities need access to high-speed Internet services 
for transmitting graphics and large amounts of data. Farmers, for 
example, often use satellite imaging to decide how much fertilizer 
and pesticide to use in their fields. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to Kennard, the senators said the FCC should  
consider subsidizing high-speed Internet and data services via 
satellite services, raise the technical requirements for phone 
lines, and encourage cellular companies to serve remote areas and 
Indian reservations where there is little existing phone service. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the senators are introducing legislation to set up  
an office of rural advocacy at the FCC. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rural communities need the economic and social benefits that  
high-speed Internet access provides. For some of them, it's a 
matter of basic economic survival,'' said Senate Minority Leader 
Tom Daschle, D-S.D. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecommunications companies have been racing each other to  
provide high-speed Internet access. 
</P>
<P>
	An alliance of computer makers and big telephone companies,  
including US West, wants the FCC to ease regulations they say 
discourage modernization. Rival long-distance companies, including 
AT&AMP;T, oppose the move. AT&AMP;T is seeking to become a major provider 
of Internet service over cable TV lines. 
</P>
<P>
	The letter was signed by Daschle and Dorgan and Sens. Tom Harkin  
of Iowa, Tim Johnson of South Dakota, Ron Wyden of Oregon, Kent 
Conrad of North Dakota, Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, Paul Wellstone of 
Minnesota, Patty Murray of Washington, and Max Baucus of Montana. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 12:11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gingrich Urges GOP To Cut Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans should set their sights on  
lowering the total tax burden on Americans to 25 percent and not 
waste time campaigning for a fundamental overhaul of the system, 
former House Speaker Newt Gingrich said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gingrich, now a senior fellow at the American Enterprise  
Institute think tank, said at a tax seminar that he will write to 
GOP leaders across the country this fall urging that the 25 percent 
goal in the next 15 years become a ``a moral principle'' in 
national and local Republican Party platforms. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tax reform is a dead end,'' Gingrich said. ``The real goal  
should be to shrink the total government tax.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On average, Americans pay about 40 percent of their earnings in  
all types of federal, state and local taxes each year, Gingrich 
said. Taxes should be reduced by shrinking the size of government, 
he said, which would give people more money to spend on their own 
priorities. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you have huge governments, they have their own  
interests,'' Gingrich said. ``Taxes in the end are about power. Who 
has the ability to spend what you earn?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gingrich, a Republican from Georgia, resigned as House speaker  
after Republicans lost seats in the 1998 elections. He said he will 
not run for any office in 2000. But he has not ruled out a future 
presidential bid and said Friday that his tax message would be 
financed with his new Friends of Newt Gingrich political action 
committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans ranging from House Majority Leader Dick Armey,  
R-Texas, to presidential contender Steve Forbes have championed a 
flat income tax to replace the current graduated code. Others favor 
consumption taxes on purchases to replace income taxes, such as a 
national sales tax, while some want a constitutional amendment 
limiting tax increases. 
</P>
<P>
	Gingrich, however, said such efforts frequently amount to an  
``enormous black hole into which you pour energy but nothing ever 
comes out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tax reforms that would broaden the tax base, such as a national  
sales tax, run into political thickets because ``you're hitting 
somebody'' with new taxes no matter which road is taken, Gingrich 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It took 26 years to get welfare reform,'' Gingrich said of the  
laws passed by Congress in 1996. ``Our goal should be to lessen all 
taxes to 25 percent. You could do something every year.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
