<HEADLINE> Kids Fuel 'Phantom Menace' Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- This weekend's anticipated flood of younger  
viewers to movie theaters to see ``Star Wars: Episode I -- The 
Phantom Menace'' is expected help the movie trounce previous box 
office records. 
</P>
<P>
	In its first two days, the ``Star Wars'' prequel earned nearly  
$41 million, including a record $28.5 million in its debut 
Wednesday, according to 20th Century Fox. 
</P>
<P>
	Historical precedent suggested there would be a significant drop  
on Thursday before a weekend rebound to opening day levels. 
</P>
<P>
	The kid factor should push today's grosses beyond Wednesday,  
setting a new one-day record. Receipts totaling $28,542,349 on 
Wednesday beat the $26.1 million earned in 1997 by previous title 
holder ``Lost World: Jurassic Park.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Box office comparisons are not adjusted for inflation.  
</P>
<P>
	Youngsters could be the key to the movie's longevity. Some  
critics harped that the film's 8-year-old central character and 
sidekick Jar Jar Binks target little tykes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Show me the kids!'' 20th Century Fox distribution chief Tom  
Sherak said Friday, refusing to predict how much the George Lucas 
film would rake in by Sunday's final showings. 
</P>
<P>
	Movie analysts expect ``The Phantom Menace,'' a $125 million  
film that Lucas financed himself, to gross $120 million to $140 
million by the end of its five-day opening frame. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all have our fingers crossed. We've said it's like a  
shooting star and we're holding on to see what it does,'' Sherak 
said. ``Monday will show you the direction we're going, then the 
next weekend is the holiday weekend and, who knows?'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
