<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poll Finds Support for Gun Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican women have shifted dramatically in  
recent years toward the belief that controlling gun ownership is 
more important than the rights of gun owners, a poll says. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll results were released Thursday as the Senate approved a  
proposal to slap fresh restrictions on gun purchases at gun shows 
and pawn shops, a move pushed by Senate Democrats and opposed by 
most Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll by the Pew Research Center for the People &AMP; the Press  
was taken before Thursday's school shootings in Conyers, Ga., and 
was released as President Clinton traveled to Littleton, Colo., to 
observe the one-month anniversary of the nation's worst school 
shooting. That attack claimed 15 lives, including the two 
assailants who committed suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	Just over half of all Republicans, 53 percent, said gun control  
was more important, while 42 percent said protecting the gun 
owners' rights took priority. Six years ago, 47 percent of 
Republicans picked gun control and 45 percent picked protecting gun 
owners' rights, a statistical tie. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican women were key to the shift in overall GOP sentiment  
in the poll. 
</P>
<P>
	Almost three-fourths of GOP women said in the poll that  
controlling gun ownership was more important, about the same 
percentage as all women who felt that way. In 1993, about half of 
GOP women said controlling guns was more important, while just over 
four-in-10 said it was important to protect the rights of gun 
owners. 
</P>
<P>
	Three-quarters of Democrats in the poll said gun control is more  
important than protecting the rights of gun owners, an increase 
from the two-thirds who felt that way six years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	About two-thirds of all those questioned in the poll thought gun  
control was more important, slightly higher than in a Pew poll in 
December 1993. The percentage of people who feel television news 
contains too much violence also grew. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll indicated that almost two-thirds of Americans think  
television news contains too much violence, compared with half who 
felt that way in 1993. Seven-of-10 said TV entertainment programs 
have too much violence, the same level as the 1993 Pew poll and a 
1971 Harris poll. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pew poll showed an 8-point increase in support for gun  
control since December 1993. An ABC-Washington Post poll released 
earlier this week showed two-thirds supported tougher gun controls, 
about the same as the percentage when ABC asked that question in 
March 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Associated Press polls taken just before and after the Littleton  
shooting showed a 9-point increase in the percentage of people who 
believe tougher gun controls are a better deterrent than stricter 
enforcement of current laws. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Pew poll, almost all demographic groups showed increased  
support for giving priority to gun controls, with a shift of more 
than 10 percentage points among women, people over age 65 and those 
with some college education. Men were more evenly divided, with 53 
percent saying restrictions were more important and 42 percent 
saying protection of gun rights was more important. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest school shooting in Georgia highlighted the copycat  
threats that have plagued the nation's schools since the Colorado 
school shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	In another survey released Thursday, the George H. Gallup  
International Institute reported that 46 percent of high school 
students said their school has groups of students who are violent 
or capable of violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether they ever fear for their personal safety at  
school, 20 percent in the Gallup poll said they did. That's higher 
than the 13 percent who said that a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The Gallup telephone poll of 403 teens, ages 13-17, was  
conducted May 5 to May 17. It has a margin of error of plus or 
minus 5 percentage points. The Pew telephone poll of 1,179 adults 
was taken May 12-16 and has an error margin of plus or minus 3.5 
percentage points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
