<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sunken Cruise Ship Passengers Saved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- More than 1,100 passengers aboard  
a luxury cruise liner scrambled overboard as the ship caught fire 
and sank off the western coast of Malaysia early Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Marine Rescue and Coordination Center in Port Klang said  
officials believed all passengers and crew aboard the ship had been 
brought to safety. 
</P>
<P>
	The passengers -- including Australians, Americans, Britons and  
Japanese -- were rescued from the Bahamian-registered Sun Vista, 
said center spokesman Raja Malik. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are no reports of fatalities,'' Raja said.  
</P>
<P>
	A total of 1,104 passengers and crew members of 26 nationalities  
were picked up by a dozen ferries and naval vessels and at least 
one cargo ship. All arrived safely on Penang island in northwestern 
Malaysia, according a statement from Sun Cruises, the operators of 
the ship. 
</P>
<P>
	The statement said a power failure resulted from a fire in the  
main engine room, but that an investigation was under way as to why 
the ship sank. 
</P>
<P>
	Sun Cruises said all passengers would be accommodated at hotels  
until they could be flown home. They would be given full refunds 
``for the inconvenience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rescued passengers in Penang spoke of panic and chaos, others of  
how they kept up their spirits by singing the song from the movie, 
``Titanic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``What actually happened is lack of information because the  
captain did not tell us about the fire. All the crew members looked 
panicky,'' passenger Thomas Bonnard, 62, of England, told the 
Malaysian news agency Bernama. 
</P>
<P>
	Indian businessman Ram Yalamanchi, 32, said he would never  
forget the screams of his fellow passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a true nightmare, I thought we all were going to die,''  
Yalamanchi told the Australian Associated Press from his hotel room 
in Penang. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were on one of the last lifeboats, we watched her just slip  
under the water,'' he said. ``People were screaming, praying, it 
was awful, the most terrifying experience of my life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first distress signal went out at about 6:30 p.m. Thursday.  
Marine police said the ship sank about seven hours later, at 1:20 
a.m., in the Strait of Malacca, about 27 miles off the central 
state of Perak. 
</P>
<P>
	The passengers were moved onto 18 lifeboats and four lift rafts.  
</P>
<P>
	Some Australians faced the trauma by singing the theme song from  
the movie, ``Titanic,'' according to Australian passenger Greg 
Haywood, 30. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were singing the Celine Dion song, `My Heart Will Go On,'  
trying to keep everyone's spirits up,'' said Haywood, adding that 
people mostly remained calm. 
</P>
<P>
	``A few people were crying and panicking, but everyone behaved  
themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ten passengers were sent to Penang Hospital for treatment. A  
hospital spokesman said the conditions were not yet known. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bernama news agency reported that the ship's captain was  
taken to a local police station to lodge a report on the incident. 
</P>
<P>
	Sun Cruises Sydney-based spokesman David Baker said most of the  
Australian and New Zealand passengers were expected to depart 
Singapore Friday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker said the company, with a head office in Singapore and one  
Australian branch in Perth, had been in operation about 18 months. 
</P>
<P>
	Sun Cruises in its statement said there were 472 passengers and  
632 crew members on board. Other passengers included Americans, 
Britons, Germans, Belgians, French, Indonesians, Japanese, 
Mexicans, Russians, Spanish and Swiss. 
</P>
<P>
	The 700-foot-long Sun Vista can hold more than 1,600 passengers  
and crew in its 547 cabins. It has eight decks, five whirlpool 
baths, a swimming pool, beauty salon, bars and casinos. 
</P>
<P>
	The ship's journey originated in Singapore, stopped to pick up  
more passengers in the Malaysian city of Malacca and then sailed on 
to the resort island of Phuket off the southern coast of Thailand. 
The Sun Vista was on its way back to its base in Singapore when it 
sank on the last leg of its six-day cruise. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman of the Kampung Acheh Marine Police in Lumut said the  
incident occurred in international waters. 
</P>
<P>
	``When our boat arrived at the scene at 12:15 a.m., the cruise  
liner was still on fire,'' said the spokesman. ``Some said that it 
looked like a scene from the film `Titanic.''' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
