<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House OKs Land Treaty Restrictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Future U.N. designations of protected lands in  
the United States would need congressional approval under 
legislation approved by the House. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters said the bill, passed by voice vote Thursday,  
reconfirms that under the Constitution Congress has the sole 
authority to manage federal lands. Democratic opponents said the 
bill was unneeded and reflected anti-U.N. paranoia. 
</P>
<P>
	It is opposed by the Clinton administration and faces an uphill  
battle in the Senate. ``I am sure we can expect the Senate again to 
ignore it, which is all it deserves,'' Interior Secretary Bruce 
Babbitt said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation, which Republicans unsuccessfully offered in the  
last two Congresses, would require congressional consent before any 
federal land could be included in an international land reserve. 
</P>
<P>
	It is aimed specifically at the World Heritage program, which  
since 1972 has identified world sites of exceptional interest and 
universal value, and U.N. biosphere reserves, founded in 1968 to 
foster studies of environments around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	There are 47 biosphere reserves in the United States, including  
the six-state Southern Appalachian Biosphere Reserve, and 20 World 
Heritage sites, mostly in national parks such as Yellowstone, the 
Statue of Liberty and Independence Hall. Sixteen sites under a U.N. 
wetlands program would also be affected by the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation, sponsored by House Resources Committee Chairman  
Don Young, R-Alaska, would terminate all existing biosphere 
reserves unless they are specifically authorized by Congress by the 
end of 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	But Democratic opponents said the land designations give the  
United Nations no control over local lands or American laws. 
</P>
<P>
	----	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 883.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
