<DOCNO> APW19990521.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 16:12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Administrator Disarms Ga. Gunman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- Assistant principal Cecil Brinkley was  
enjoying his last day of classes before retirement when he saw 
students dashing from Heritage High School, trying to escape 
another student with a gun. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas Solomon Jr., 15, had just shot and wounded six students  
Thursday, and Brinkley, 60, saw him run out near the football field 
with a .357 Magnum handgun. 
</P>
<P>
	Knowing a shortcut from 23 years of patrolling the halls,  
Brinkley came out a door about 10 feet away from Solomon to find 
him shaking and on his knees. 
</P>
<P>
	The boy put the gun in his own mouth, then pointed it at  
Brinkley as he approached. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was a little nervous, a little shaky,'' the soft-spoken  
administrator with graying red hair said Friday. ``From looking at 
him, I really thought that if I kept talking to him, he would give 
it to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brinkley stayed calm.  
</P>
<P>
	``I stepped back a couple of steps and I turned to him again and  
I said, `Give me the gun,' and I said again, `Give me the gun,''' 
Brinkley said. ``I saw him lower the barrel of the gun and I kept 
getting closer and closer to him. Then I held out my hands and he 
laid the gun in my hands. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then he gave me a real big bear hug and said `I'm so scared,  
I'm so scared,'' Brinkley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Solomon was being held in an undisclosed juvenile detention  
center Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Brinkley has been working at Heritage High since it opened in  
1976, and Thursday was to be his last full class day before his 
retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	His role in the surrender was no surprise to students or  
co-workers. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a great guy -- strict but understanding,'' said senior  
Kent Cason, 19. ``He's by the book, but human about it too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He is like a great umpire,'' Rockdale County school  
superintendent Donald Peccia said. ``He's doing a great job, and 
keeping things fair and disciplined, but you don't ever see him. He 
doesn't become the story.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
