<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 14:44:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Record Tax Surplus Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawmakers won't have another record-breaking  
``April surprise'' tax surplus to make their budgeting job easier 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The government's $113.5 billion surplus last month was 8.9  
percent lower than the $124.6 billion posted in April 1998, the 
Treasury Department said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997 and 1998, record surpluses for April -- the month that  
government coffers swell as Americans face the deadline to pay 
their income taxes -- provided lawmakers with an unexpected 
windfall. 
</P>
<P>
	That so-called April surprise helped congressional and White  
House negotiators reach agreement in 1997 on a five-year plan to 
balance the federal budget. Last year's surprise helped them 
achieve, ahead of schedule, the first annual budget surplus since 
1969 -- $69.2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	In spite of the lack of an April surprise this year, Clinton  
administration and congressional accountants are still predicting a 
bigger surplus -- between $79 billion and $111 billion -- overall for 
the government's fiscal year 1999, which began Oct. 1. For the 
first seven months of the fiscal year, through April, the surplus 
has totaled $64.7 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are on track to reach the largest annual budget surplus  
ever,'' said President Clinton in a statement. But he added, 
``Despite the good news, this is not a time for complacency.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's clear now, analysts say, that there won't be extra wiggle  
room for lawmakers struggling to make difficult choices among 
competing priorities for how to spend the surplus -- including 
shoring up Social Security, tax cuts Republicans want, domestic 
spending requested by Clinton and the conflict in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anybody who was hoping for a sudden boost, a much bigger  
surplus that would provide them a little room to do something, it's 
just not going to be there,'' said Stanley Collender, senior vice 
president of the consulting firm Fleishman Hillard. ``Revenues are 
still growing substantially, they're just not growing as fast.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One reason for the lower April surplus this year as compared to  
last April was a nearly 59 percent increase in tax refunds, to 
$36.6 billion. That reflects the new $400 per child credit and new 
credits for higher education as well as the increasing popularity 
of electronic filing and direct deposit, which offer speedier 
refunds than paper tax returns and paper checks. Year to date, tax 
refunds are up nearly 33 percent compared to the same period in 
fiscal 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
