<HEADLINE> Tobacco Companies Suing Mass. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Cigarette makers are challenging Massachusetts'  
attempt to curtail tobacco marketing, arguing the multistate 
tobacco settlement already addresses concerns about advertising to 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	Two companies filed federal lawsuits Friday against the  
first-in-the-nation effort by the state attorney general's office 
that would restrict tobacco advertising under the office's consumer 
protection powers. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Porter, an assistant attorney general, said Philip Morris  
and Lorillard filed the suits, and he said R.J. Reynolds and Brown 
&AMP; Williamson planned on filing similar actions. 
</P>
<P>
	Porter said the Philip Morris complaint claimed that the  
restrictions on cigarette advertising violated the First Amendment 
and were pre-empted by federal law. 
</P>
<P>
	``The attorney general intends vigorously to defend these cases  
and is firmly of the view that these regulations are lawful,'' 
Porter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Morris spokesman Brendan McCormick said the company had  
challenged sections of the consumer regulations ``which we feel 
unduly restrict our right to market our products to adults who 
choose to smoke.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A message left for Lorillard attorney Richard Zielinski wasn't  
immediately returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Massachusetts was a participant in the nationwide settlement of  
states' lawsuits against the tobacco industry. That settlement of 
claims for the costs of smoking-related illnesses is to bring the 
state $7.6 billion over 25 years. 
</P>
<P>
	But the settlement didn't guarantee a truce from the industry,  
said Richard Daynard, a law professor at Northeastern University 
who is chairman of the Tobacco Products Liability Project. 
</P>
<P>
	``This may be the first truly nasty move since the settlement,''  
Daynard said. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Connolly, director of the state's tobacco control program,  
said the rules that were challenged restricted advertising near 
schools. 


</P>
</TEXT>
