<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kevorkian Lawyer Asks For New Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Saying Dr. Jack Kevorkian's former attorney was  
more interested in talking to the media than performing his duties, 
his current lawyer has asked a judge to throw out Kevorkian's 
murder conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevorkian attorney Mayer Morganroth filed a motion late Friday  
afternoon, asking Judge Jessica Cooper to throw out Kevorkian's 
conviction on charges of second-degree murder and delivery of a 
controlled substance. 
</P>
<P>
	David Gorosh and Lisa Dwyer filed motions and argued for  
Kevorkian during his preliminary hearing. But the night before the 
trial began, Kevorkian decided to represent himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Morganroth alleged that Kevorkian acted as his own attorney out  
of frustration over the way Gorosh was handling the defense. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think he totally represented himself,'' Morganroth  
said. ``There's much more to it than meets the eye.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his motion, Morganroth wrote that Gorosh ``left his client  
without the legal information necessary to present a competent 
defense. ... Gorosh was more interested in talking to the media 
than the defense team and his client, Dr. Kevorkian.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gorosh said there was no basis for Morganroth to make his claim.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to see Dr. Kevorkian get a new trial, but not through  
a method that is untrue,'' Gorosh said. ``It was his own choice to 
defend himself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kevorkian, who turns 71 next week, is in the Oaks Correctional  
Facility in Manistee, serving a 10- to 25-year sentence. He was 
found guilty March 26 of second-degree murder and delivery of a 
controlled substance in the injection death of Thomas Youk, a Lou 
Gehrig's disease patient. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevorkian taped Youk's death on Sept. 17 and gave the video to  
CBS' ``60 Minutes.'' The tape and interview with Kevorkian the show 
later aired were the prosecution's key evidence. Kevorkian defended 
himself, making opening and closing arguments to the jury, but 
calling no witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Morganroth, who had helped defend Kevorkian in two previous  
trials, dropped in on the last day of the criminal trial. Kevorkian 
asked for his help, and let Morganroth represent him during his 
sentencing. April 14. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's unfortunate that he (Morganroth) has apparently tried to  
manipulate what happened in this case without contacting me,'' 
Gorosh said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
