<HEADLINE> Gore Hopes Gun Vote Boosts Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore hopes to turn his  
tie-breaking vote on gun control into a momentum-building moment 
that energizes his 2000 presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Senate deadlocked, Gore twice asked the clerk to  
announce a tie Thursday before casting the decisive vote to expand 
a system of background checks on firearms purchases so they would 
cover all such buys at gun shows and pawnshops. 
</P>
<P>
	``This could be a turning point for Gore in that he has finally  
shown some leadership on an issue and for once he stands apart from 
President Clinton,'' said Republican strategist Scott Reed. 
</P>
<P>
	``That vote says, `This is a guy who calls a tough shot,''' said  
Democratic Party chairman Roy Romer, former governor of Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	Polls suggest he wasn't taking a major risk. An overwhelming  
number of Americans -- and a slight majority of all Republicans -- 
are telling pollsters they favor some forms of gun control. And 
large majorities of Democratic and Republican women, a key voting 
bloc in the 2000 elections, say gun control is important. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thursday's vote was not about politics, it was about  
protecting America's kids,'' Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said. 
``We'll continue to work to find solutions and answers in the 
aftermath of the school shootings to help give parents the tools 
they need to protect their children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's upcoming schedule affords him a chance to build on the  
gun vote. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, he'll attend a school safety event in New  
Hampshire, the state that holds the nation's first presidential 
primaries in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, Gore plans to address a major labor union and a  
Jewish political action committee -- hitting two key constituencies 
in one day. 
</P>
<P>
	He will be in Atlanta on Monday, near the high school where a  
teen-ager opened fire Thursday and wounded six classmates. The 
topic of his address, the second major speech in eight days, will 
be the importance of faith-based institutions in helping government 
provide services to Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	Later in the week, he is scheduled to be in Texas, the home of  
GOP front-runner Gov. George W. Bush. 
</P>
</TEXT>
