<DOCNO> APW19990521.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 13:21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> City Schools Escape Shooting Sprees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Every morning, Maria Marino passes gang turf on  
her way to Clemente High School. There she walks through a metal 
detector. There she passes five security guards. There she feels 
safe. 
</P>
<P>
	A shooting in her school? The 17-year-old senior thinks not.  
</P>
<P>
	``It could happen anywhere,'' she conceded Friday, ``but I just  
don't imagine it happening here. I feel comfortable here. I think 
there's more possibilities for it to happen in the neighborhood.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the mass school shootings that have horrified the nation  
since 1997, a striking similarity has emerged: The tragedies have 
occurred in quiet and mostly white suburban or rural communities -- 
Littleton, Colo., Jonesboro, Ark., Conyers, Ga. -- not big cities 
typically associated with teen violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Some experts say urban schools, while struggling with gangs and  
drugs, have so far escaped random shooting sprees for some basic 
reasons: 
</P>
<P>
	-- In the city, a teen-ager with a gun is automatically thought  
to be up to no good. That's not always the case in rural or 
suburban areas where people go hunting or take target practice. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Violence in the city tends to be aimed at individuals more  
often than it is unleashed indiscriminately. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Perhaps most important, security is tighter.  
</P>
<P>
	``Urban schools have had to deal with the issue of violence for  
a longer period of time,'' said Joanne McDaniel, research director 
of the Center for the Prevention of School Violence in Raleigh, 
N.C. ``They may not be able to make a safe neighborhood, but at 
least they can make school a safe haven.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many city schools have conflict and anger management programs,  
mentoring and metal detectors. 
</P>
<P>
	At Clemente, on Chicago's near West Side, security officials say  
they have not found a gun since metal detectors were installed two 
years ago. ``Mostly it's knives and pagers and lighters,'' said 
Steve Garcia, the school's security supervisor. 
</P>
<P>
	Only about a quarter of the nation's largest 55 to 60 districts  
used metal detectors in the early 1990s; more than 95 percent do 
now, according to Ronald Stephens, director of the National School 
Safety Center in Westlake Village, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Stephens cited a recent government study showing that  
only 4 percent of all school districts nationwide had metal 
detectors. 
</P>
<P>
	The cramped urban setting may itself serve as a deterrent. The  
Jonesboro school, for example, had a wooded area from which the 
attack was launched. Columbine High School in Littleton had a large 
parking lot. 
</P>
<P>
	``Imagine trying to bring in 30 bombs and all that weaponry in a  
Chicago high school,'' as was done in Columbine, said Laurence 
Steinberg, a psychology professor at Temple University and director 
of the MacArthur Foundation Research Network on Adolescent 
Development and Juvenile Justice. 
</P>
<P>
	School safety experts note that while big-city schools still are  
more violent than rural or suburban ones, urban gangs tend to 
target rivals or other specific victims, rather than launching 
random assaults. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, ``gangs in urban areas typically do not see the  
schoolhouse as the place to carry out their turf war,'' Mrs. 
McDaniel said. ``They're going to do that in the streets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some experts also say city kids obtain guns usually to commit  
crimes, while suburban and rural teens frequently own weapons for 
hunting and recreation. 
</P>
<P>
	``The gun culture is different'' outside the cities, said Paul  
Gray, a professor of sociology at Boston College. ``It normalizes 
the possession and use of a gun.'' He added: ``My kids never see me 
doing target practice. I don't belong to a gun club. I don't 
identify weapons with self-protection or leisure activity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All the gunmen in the school shootings have been white boys or  
young men, leading some sociologists to speculate about a growing 
sense of isolation and alienation among suburban teens who may 
enjoy material comforts but have troubled relationships with their 
peers and parents. 
</P>
<P>
	Though urban schools have been spared mass shootings, many  
experts caution against assuming that such tragedies can't -- or 
won't -- happen there. And some also say inner-city violence is 
often overlooked. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Columbine High massacre happened in the inner city, ``I'm  
not sure it would have gotten the same media attention,'' said Ron 
Astor, professor of social work and education at the University of 
Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	And, he added, ``If it happens at 3:30, after the bell rings,  
then it's called community violence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Chicago's Clemente High, 16-year-old Darnell Ivy shook his  
head Friday when he heard the recent reports about the Georgia 
shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought, `Just more crazy kids.' There's some of those  
here,'' he said. Then he paused and added: ``They're not so 
different from us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- AP reporter Martha Irvine also contributed to  
this report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 06:38:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AOL Chief Faces Microsoft Questions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Steve Case, America Online's billionaire  
chairman and one of the few executives to succeed in the shadow of 
Microsoft, was facing questions under oath today from the software 
giant about his nearly $10 billion purchase of Netscape. 
</P>
<P>
	Case, who was being questioned by lawyers at a hotel in downtown  
Washington, has already said he doesn't expect to offer any new 
information relevant to the government's antitrust case against 
Microsoft Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nothing there (involving Netscape) has anything to do with  
operating systems, which, as best I can tell, is the focus of that 
trial,'' said Case, who also is chief executive officer of America 
Online Inc., the world's largest Internet provider, with nearly 18 
million customers. 
</P>
<P>
	But the judge who will deliver the trial's verdict has already  
expressed interest in hearing from Case about his plans for 
Netscape Communications Corp., the Internet pioneer that saw its 
business wane after Microsoft started giving away its own browser 
software free with its dominant Windows operating system. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft contends that the purchase of Netscape illustrates  
that competition is healthy in the high-tech industry, and that a 
judge's intervention is unnecessary. It claims the sale undermines 
allegations that Netscape could be prevented from distributing its 
software, saying it expects AOL eventually to ship the Netscape 
browser to all its subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
	In earlier deposition testimony, AOL's Barry Schuler  
acknowledged that a senior executive privately warned a top 
government lawyer weeks before the trial's start that AOL was 
actively involved in sensitive negotiations with Netscape. 
</P>
<P>
	But Schuler, president of AOL's Interactive Services Group,  
denied AOL gave the Justice Department full details of its plans. 
The government said previously that it didn't know about the merger 
until November, after witnesses for both AOL and Netscape had 
testified against Microsoft. 
</P>
<P>
	Reporters were being allowed to attend at least part of Case's  
questioning because of an obscure 1913 law covering antitrust 
depositions, which are normally conducted in private. 
</P>
<P>
	In the midst of the trial in January, weeks after the AOL  
purchase of Netscape was announced, U.S. District Judge Thomas 
Penfield Jackson surprised the courtroom when he introduced a 
newspaper interview with Case as Court Exhibit No. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge even hinted to lawyers from both sides they might  
consider calling Case as one of the final witnesses in the trial, 
although neither side ultimately agreed. The trial resumes June 1. 
</P>
<P>
	In that interview with The Washington Post, Case denied that AOL  
intends to compete with Microsoft in the market for computer 
operating systems. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no flight of fancy that we can dent in any way, shape  
or form what is a monopoly in the operating system business,'' Case 
told the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Like some other major companies, such as IBM Corp., AOL  
maintains a schizophrenic relationship with Microsoft -- partners in 
some areas but bitter rivals in others. 
</P>
<P>
	AOL's software requires Windows, making the company somewhat  
reliant on Microsoft. And under a March 1996 deal, AOL agreed to 
distribute Microsoft's browser to all its subscribers in exchange 
for having its own software made available with Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	But AOL has roundly trumped Microsoft in the popularity of its  
MSN online service, which stagnates with about 2 million 
subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
	The success of AOL has always been an aggravation to Microsoft  
Chairman Bill Gates, who warned Case in the early 1990s: ``I can 
buy 20 percent of you or I can buy all of you. Or I can go into 
this business myself and bury you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And with its purchase of Netscape, AOL now owns Microsoft's  
chief browser rival and the popular Netcenter Web site. The latest 
figures from Media Metrix Inc., which tracks Internet visitors, 
showed AOL's site was the second-most popular on the Web, and 
Netscape's was sixth. MSN's site was third, and Microsoft's 
corporate page was seventh. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
