<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olivetti Telecom Takeover Nearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Olivetti narrowly clinched a majority stake in  
Telecom Italia today, clearing the way for completion of the 
hostile $64 billion takeover of Italy's No. 1 phone company. 
</P>
<P>
	By garnering 51 percent of Telecom's shares, Olivetti apparently  
avoids having to battle Telecom's current management for control -- 
a contentious outcome that industry analyst Dwayne Taylor of Robert 
Fleming Securities described as a ``lawyers' dream.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Italian stock market officials said late Friday in Milan that  
Olivetti had secured an unspecified majority stake in Telecom. The 
announcement came after officials toted up the results from the 
last day of the offer by Olivetti, a diversified communications and 
office products business. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Olivetti had less than 20 percent of Telecom's  
shares. But on the final day for securing shareholder backing for 
its upstart effort, most of Telecom Italia's strongest supporters 
jumped ship. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a dramatic climax to the largest unfriendly corporate  
takeover ever launched in Europe, in which Olivetti took aim at a 
target five times its size. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am proud of the market response to our offer. This confirms  
the seriousness and the transparency of Olivetti's industrial 
project,'' Olivetti's chief executive, Roberto Colaninno, said in a 
statement. ``The positive conclusion ... signals the beginning of a 
new, great industrial history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The result surpassed the 35 percent threshold Olivetti said it  
needed to press ahead with its plan to acquire Italy's former 
government-run telephone monopoly for 11.5 euros per share, or 
$12.15 at current exchange rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Colaninno had said he might call off the bid if his company  
failed to gain 67 percent of Telecom's shares. Now, with a majority 
stake in Telecom, he is almost certain to push ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	``Colaninno has put a lot into this, and he's not going to back  
out,'' said Taylor of the London-based brokerage. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti will hold a board meeting Saturday to assess the  
outcome of the takeover bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Franco Bernabe, the Telecom chief executive, said it is now up  
to the company's shareholders to determine its future. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is my hope that they can give the company another push in  
the short term, to surpass the goals already reached and to create 
value from the many human and technological resources at their 
disposal,'' he said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	But another Telecom Italia official held out the possibility  
that Franco Bernabe, the Telecom chief executive, might be willing 
to negotiate a power-sharing arrangement with Colaninno. The 
official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said that Bernabe had 
refused until now to negotiate because Colaninno had not made any 
overtures. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the day's biggest disappointments for Telecom were the  
defections of almost all of its core shareholders, an investor 
group organized when Telecom was privatized in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Assicurazioni Generali, Italy's largest insurer, said it  
tendered all its Telecom shares, equal to 1 percent of the total 
number outstanding, while San Paulo IMI, a bank, turned over 0.8 
percent. Another bank, Unicredito, tendered 0.7 percent of 
Telecom's shares, and IFIL, the holding company of Italy's Agnelli 
industrial dynasty, gave up 0.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Only one core shareholder, Credit Suisse Group, said it would  
stick with Telecom's current management. 
</P>
<P>
	In another blow to Telecom, Olivetti said Friday that the  
European Union Commission had approved the sale of its stake in 
Italian mobile phone operator Omnitel. Olivetti is counting on the 
sale to Germany's Mannesmann to generate much of the cash it needs 
to finance its takeover of Telecom. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's result also appears to doom Telecom Italia's proposed  
defensive merger with its German counterpart, Deutsche Telekom. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies announced plans for a friendly merger in  
April, but since then the deal has met with resistance from Italian 
leaders, who fear that the German government might try to influence 
the merged companies through its majority ownership of Deutsche 
Telekom. 
</P>
<P>
	A Deutsche Telekom official, speaking on condition of anonymity,  
said Friday the company still hopes to merge with Telecom Italia 
despite Olivetti's successful offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Many investors also have reacted skeptically to the union,  
saying it lacks commercial logic. 
</P>
<P>
	But some analysts have raised similar questions about Olivetti's  
own effort. Like the proposed German-Italian merger, Olivetti's bid 
was a deal ``done on the run'' that depended more on personal and 
corporate politics than on economic fundamentals, said Mark Horn of 
the London-based stock brokerage T. Hoare Canaccord. 
</P>
<P>
	``Where along the line here does anyone talk about earnings,  
about value? You need political analysts for this one, not 
financial analysts.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
