<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Excerpts From Secrets Book </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Excerpts from classified documents that appear in the appendix  
of ``Betrayal,'' an account of Clinton administration national 
security policy by Bill Gertz, a reporter for The Washington Times. 
The book is published by Regnery Publishing Inc. of Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	--A Dec. 10, 1996, report by the Air Force National Air  
Intelligence Center stamped ``Secret'' describes how China, under a 
contract with U.S. communications company Motorola, developed a 
space launcher to send satellites into Earth orbit. But the Air 
Force analysis called these satellite launchers a ``technology 
bridge'' to launchers for multiple-warhead missiles. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no data, however, that the Chinese have embarked on  
the development of'' such a missile launcher, the report said. 
``The Chinese have expressed an interest in developing'' such 
technology, the report also noted, ``however, no known testing of 
such a system has occurred.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--From a March 1996 document marked ``Confidential,'' a  
memorandum of a conversation between President Clinton and Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin that took place during a conference on 
international terrorism held in Egypt. Clinton gives Yeltsin a 
draft communique: 
</P>
<P>
	``The president gave Yeltsin a copy and apologized that it was  
only in English. Foreign Minister (Yevgeny) Primakov said that he 
could read it, and Yeltsin joked that since Primakov knew English, 
Secretary (of State Warren) Christopher should now learn Russian. 
The Russians would be glad to provide the secretary with a young 
attractive instructress who would work with the secretary night and 
day. The president joked that this would change the secretary's 
image in the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--A 1997 CIA report labeled ``Top Secret'' describes how in  
Russia ``work has progressed on extending a deep subway for rapid 
evacuation of leaders during wartime from Moscow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--A top secret U.S. intelligence report from 1996 discloses,  
``Incidents of cannibalism have begun to punctuate reporting on 
North Korea's deepening food shortage. Reported occurrences so far 
have been limited to the far northeast, a remote and chronic 
food-deficit region.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
