<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sabres Try to Savor Playoffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Winning the Stanley Cup is the first  
priority for Joe Juneau. Enjoying the experience of the playoffs is 
also important to the Buffalo Sabres center. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some games you're not going to win, but you still have to  
catch the moment and be able to look back at it,'' Juneau said. 
``There's always good moments in a hockey game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Juneau hopes there will be more good moments than bad for the  
Sabres when they open the Eastern Conference final Sunday at 
Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	Juneau stored away a few highlights last season, when he made it  
to the Stanley Cup final with the Washington Capitals. One was an 
overtime goal in Game 6 that gave the Capitals the Eastern 
Conference title, and ended the season for his current team. 
</P>
<P>
	The center was dealt to Buffalo in March and has nine points --  
two goals, seven assists -- in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Juneau recalled a chat he had a few years back with buddy  
Patrick Roy, the Colorado goalie getting ready to lead the 
Avalanche against Dallas in the Western Conference final. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said it was not to win the Cup ... the more fun he had was  
actually during the time -- the good times he had getting there,'' 
Juneau said of Roy, who has played for three Stanley Cup winners. 
``And it's just the truth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's a philosophy shared by coach Lindy Ruff, who encourages his  
team to appreciate its accomplishments while working hard to 
advance. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's one of the requirements. You've got to have fun,'' Ruff  
said after Thursday's practice. ``It's work hard, have fun and 
enjoy it. We want them to enjoy it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the players know the difference between work and play,  
captain Michael Peca says. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Ruff) gives us the days off to do whatever we want, whether  
it's play some golf or something like that,'' he said, ``but the 
day before the series starts, it's back to business and focus on 
our jobs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Peca said that concentration has been stronger during this  
playoff run than last year's. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year, we thought we accomplished something getting to the  
conference finals. This year we're not satisfied with anything 
we've done,'' he said. ``We're happy with the progress we've made 
over the course of the postseason, but we want to go all the way. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody's being very, very businesslike about it and it's  
good to see that attitude.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres, looking for their first Stanley Cup, play the first  
two games of the best-of-7 series at Toronto, which hasn't won the 
cup since 1967. 
</P>
<P>
	In five regular-season meetings, Buffalo won the first three and  
Toronto the next two. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
