<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 16:05:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lackluster Baseball Crop in Draft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The search is on for the next Mark McGwire and Randy Johnson.  
</P>
<P>
	And they might be found at the high school level, according to  
major league scouts. 
</P>
<P>
	While the last five No. 1 picks of the amateur draft have been  
college players, the names mentioned most often this year are those 
of high school players. 
</P>
<P>
	Josh Beckett, a right-hander from Spring (Texas) H.S., and Josh  
Hamilton, a 6-foot-4, 200-pound outfielder from Athens Drive (N.C.) 
H.S., are pre-draft favorites to be selected first on June 2. B.J. 
Garbe, an outfielder/right-hander from Moses Lake (Wash.) H.S. is 
expected to be a top-five pick. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's college crop lacks position players, scouts say.  
</P>
<P>
	``From a college standpoint, it's a very below-average field,''  
said Dan Jennings, scouting director for the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, 
who pick first. ``There are some decent college arms in the mix, 
though.'' 
</P>
<P>
	College players expected to be chosen early include: Southern  
California catcher Eric Munson, Northeast Louisiana right-hander 
Ben Sheets, North Carolina righty Kyle Snyder, Mississippi State 
right-hander Matt Ginter and Washington righty Jeff Heaverlo. 
</P>
<P>
	Munson, who missed 21 games with a broken hand, is the top  
college position player available. However, scouts are undecided 
whether he will be a catcher or move elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheets has an outstanding curveball, and his fastball hits 93-94  
mph. Heaverlo is a strikeout artist who has good genes -- his dad, 
Dave, was a major league pitcher. 
</P>
<P>
	Snyder, a 6-8, 215-pounder, lost some velocity because of  
tendinitis. Ginter has a terrific sinker and is projected to be a 
closer. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami shortstop Bobby Hill, Providence outfielder Keith Reed and  
North Carolina shortstop Brian Roberts are other college position 
players mentioned as possible first-round selections. 
</P>
<P>
	Baylor's Jason Jennings, the nation's premier two-way college  
player, is expected to be a first-round pick, but as a pitcher. 
</P>
<P>
	Some scouts predict that up to 20 of the 30 first-round  
selections may be high school players. 
</P>
<P>
	``Probably talentwise, it could very well shape up that way,''  
Jennings said. ``It really comes down to organizational 
philosophies. With us picking first, we just want to get the best 
player in the country, whether it's a high school player or a 
college player.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ABSENT EAST:* The expansion of the Division I tournament to 64  
teams this year was aimed at garnering interest in areas that 
traditionally lacked large fan bases. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the Division I baseball committee announced the sites  
of the 16 four-team regionals that begin May 28 -- and the Northeast 
was missing from the list. 
</P>
<P>
	The regional hosts are Alabama, Arkansas, Auburn, Baylor,  
Florida State, Houston, Louisiana State, Miami, Notre Dame, Ohio 
State, Southern California, Stanford, Texas A&AMP;M, Texas Tech, Wake 
Forest, and Wichita State. 
</P>
<P>
	Committee chairman Dick Rockwell said 29 schools placed regional  
bids -- none from the Northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	``We set up some things basically to help the Northeast and  
nobody stepped forward,'' said Rockwell, athletic director at Le 
Moyne College in Syracuse, N.Y. The bid amount was lowered from 
$50,000 to $35,000, and fields are no longer required to have 
lights. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think sooner or later, those of us in the Northeast have to  
realize that we've been given an opportunity to step up to the 
plate, and didn't get it done,'' Rockwell said. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BATTLE OF THE BATS:* The crack of the bat is being heard at the  
NCAA Division III tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	The six teams in the Mid-Atlantic regional -- Rowan, Montclair  
St., William Paterson and the College of New Jersey, all members of 
the New Jersey Athletic Conference, as well as Widener (Pa.) and 
Ursinus (Pa.) -- agreed to use wooden bats in the double-elimination 
tournament, which began Thursday. The regional will be the only one 
using wood exclusively. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision comes amid controversy. The NJAC banned aluminum  
bats this season and conference athletic directors voted 6-4 to 
boycott the Division III tournament because of the use of aluminum. 
The four schools chosen for the regional decided to participate 
anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	The schools may ultimately face penalties by the conference  
because the winner of the regional advances to the Division III 
World Series in Salem, Va., beginning May 28, and will have to play 
with aluminum bats. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other schools, Wisconsin-Oshkosh and Wisconsin-Stevens Point  
in the Midwest regional, are also using wooden bats. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SEMINOLE SLUGGER:* Marshall McDougall's stock may have risen a  
bit. 
</P>
<P>
	The Florida State second baseman, who hit six consecutive homers  
and drove in 16 runs -- both NCAA records -- in a 26-2 rout of 
Maryland on May 10, has already been drafted twice. He is projected 
to be selected in the first few rounds this year. 
</P>
<P>
	McDougall was drafted out of Buchholz (Fla.) High School in the  
33rd round by the Chicago White Sox in 1996. The following year, he 
was drafted out of Santa Fe Community College by the New York 
Yankees in the 37th round. 
</P>
<P>
	McDougall, who hit just 12 homers in his first two college  
seasons at Sante Fe, was hitting .441 with an Atlantic Coast 
Conference-leading 24 homers and 92 RBIs going into the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *AROUND THE HORN:* The Citadel's Rodney Hancock had a Southern  
Conference tournament-record 20 strikeouts in a 3-0 victory over 
Furman on Wednesday. ... California coach Bob Milano retired Monday 
after compiling a 679-629-4 record over 29 years. ... Temple's 4-2 
victory over Rhode Island on May 15 was coach James ``Skip'' 
Wilson's 900th career win. 
</P>
<P>
	 *End Adv for May 22-23    	
</P>
