<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Susan B. Anthony Dollar Is Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Eighteen years after the U.S. Mint stopped  
churning out the Susan B. Anthony dollar -- and just months before a 
gussied-up younger cousin makes its debut -- the once-unloved coin 
is making a comeback. 
</P>
<P>
	Heavy demand for the Susan B in snack machines and subways has  
exhausted the supply, prompting the Mint to decide Thursday to 
produce a final ``1999'' encore run. 
</P>
<P>
	The government struck 857 million coins with the 19th century  
suffragette on the face from 1979 to 1981, but found itself stuck 
with 550 million of them when production ended. Many people 
complained the Susan B dollar was too easily mistaken for a quarter 
because of its look and feel. 
</P>
<P>
	But now, with many vending machines, Postal Service stamp  
dispensers and city subway systems accepting the dollar coin, Mint 
officials are vowing to keep them in supply until the debut early 
next year of the new Sacagawea dollar coin, which also can be used 
in vending machines. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're committed to providing an uninterrupted supply of dollar  
coins through this transition,'' Mint Director Philip N. Diehl 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new dollar coin, graced with an image of Shoshone Indian  
woman who helped the Lewis and Clark Expedition, also can be used 
in vending machines. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sacagawea dollar coin will be the same size as the Susan B,  
but have a gold-colored surface and a smooth rim. The ridge-edged, 
silver-colored Susan B was considered too quarter-like. 
</P>
<P>
	And while the Susan B depicts the women's rights leader in stern  
profile, the Sacagawea coin shows the teen-ager who helped the 
Lewis &AMP; Clark expedition glancing back over her shoulder, her 
infant son asleep in a carrier on her back. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mint has not yet determined how many new Susan Bs to strike  
or when the process will begin, and spokesman Michael White wasn't 
sure if officials had estimated how much it would cost. 
</P>
<P>
	Some coin collectors were quick to hail the Susan B's return.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of good news,'' said Ed Rochette, executive director  
of the American Numismatic Association, a 108-year-old society of 
coin collectors. ``It will make it easier for the Sacagawea 
dollar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rochette, reciting a common collector's prejudice against the $1  
bill, said coins don't stand much chance of wide usage as long as 
the bill remains in circulation. 
</P>
<P>
	Many coin collectors and some members of Congress long have  
campaigned for an end to the dollar bill, claiming that while paper 
money is cheaper to produce than coins, it wears out more quickly 
and thus costs the government more in the long run. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
