<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Panel OKs `Sweepstakes' Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sweepstakes companies would be required to  
assure consumers that they need not purchase mail-order merchandise 
in order to win big prizes under legislation pending before the 
Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate Governmental Affairs Committee approved the bill by  
voice vote Thursday, sending it to the full Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation is aimed at stopping deceptive sweepstakes  
offers designed to induce consumers to spend money on products they 
don't want or need in the mistaken belief the purchases will 
improve their chances of winning, said the bill's sponsor, Sen. 
Susan Collins, R-Maine. Sweepstakes sponsors who fail to comply 
would face stiff fines. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sweepstakes in this country for many Americans have become a  
cruel joke,'' Collins said. ``Many Americans are overwhelmed with 
sweepstakes solicitations that promise large winnings and deliver 
only empty entreaties for more purchases of unneeded products and 
entries into even more sweepstakes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During hearings in March, elderly people told the Senate  
Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations how they sometimes spent 
thousands of dollars buying magazines and merchandise in pursuit of 
multimillion-dollar cash prizes, cars and exotic vacations. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee also heard from representatives of Publishers  
Clearing House, Reader's Digest, American Family Enterprises and 
Time who defended their practices, contending they have voluntarily 
changed their mailings and are making efforts to identify the small 
segment of Americans who don't understand the rules. 
</P>
<P>
	``The deception here is disgraceful. It happens too  
frequently,'' bill co-sponsor Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., said 
Thursday. ``This will be very protective of people, especially 
senior citizens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would require sweepstakes companies to include language  
in their mailings that ``clearly and conspicuously'' state that no 
purchase is necessary to win and making a purchase will not 
increase the chances of winning. 
</P>
<P>
	It also would require sweepstakes sponsors to include rules and  
entry procedures in language that is easy to read, understand and 
locate. Consumers also must be told the odds of winning each prize. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar requirements would be imposed on sponsors of contests --  
puzzles, games or other competitions that require skill to solve 
and may require an entry fee. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweepstakes sponsors would have to establish a system allowing  
consumers to call a toll-free number to learn how to be removed 
from their mailing lists. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also takes aim at mailed advertisements that look like  
checks or mail from a government agency. The bill would require 
those mailings to include statements that the ``checks'' have no 
cash value and are not negotiable or that the mailings have no 
connection the government. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is S. 335.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
