<HEADLINE> GE Recalls 9,100 Light Fixtures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- General Electric is recalling about 9,100  
fluorescent light fixtures because they were improperly assembled 
and could give consumers electrical shocks, the Consumer Product 
Safety Commission said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 12- and 24-inch models of GE ``Ultra Thin Line'' products  
fit beneath cabinets and are wired directly into the electrical 
system of the home. No injuries resulting from the use of the 
lights have been reported, CPSC said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The fixtures being recalled are white and have ``GE Lighting''  
and a model number written on a sticker beneath the plastic bulb 
guard. The models subject to the recall are 23039, 27278, 23045 and 
27281. Fixtures plugged into wall sockets are not included in the 
recall. 
</P>
<P>
	The lights were sold from February 1998 through April 1999 for  
about $35 at Home Depot, Hechingers, Payless Cashways and other 
home center and hardware stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers are advised to turn power off at the breaker switch  
before examining the product. They should also call GE Home 
Electric Products to have an electrician replace the fixture. For 
more information, they may call GE at (800) 517-9602 weekdays 
between 7 a.m. and 11 p.m. CDT. 

</P>
</TEXT>
