<HEADLINE> Lemieux Pushing Ahead on Penguins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Mario Lemieux stuck to his decision not to  
work for SMG and Fox Sports Pittsburgh when he met with the 
companies regarding their proposals to save the bankrupt Pittsburgh 
Penguins, his attorney said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux, the former center who led the team to two Stanley Cups,  
and the two companies have released rival plans for reorganizing 
the team and keeping it in Pittsburgh. The SMG-Fox plan would have 
Lemieux work for the companies, but Lemieux is still pushing for 
his own plan, said attorney Chuck Greenberg. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mario made clear to them that he intends to pursue the Lemieux  
plan but that he intends to resolve issues with SMG and Fox so that 
the Lemieux plan can go,'' Greenberg said. ``He discussed with them 
ways of working out issues within the context of the Lemieux 
plan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Tom Murphy urged Lemieux and the companies this week to  
somehow combine their two plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``SMG won't comment publicly on negotiations but we are  
cooperating fully with Mayor Murphy and will talk with any group 
that shares our goal of saving the Penguins for Pittsburgh,'' SMG 
spokesman Steve Halvonik said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	A Fox spokesman did not immediately return a call for comment.  
</P>
<P>
	A plan from the NHL calls for breaking up the team and moving it  
from Pittsburgh if neither of the other plans are approved. 
</P>
<P>
	SMG's $24 million lease and the Penguins' broadcasting deal with  
Fox have been cited as reasons the team filed for protection from 
its creditors last October. 
</P>
<P>
	In his plan, submitted to U.S. Bankruptcy Court in March,  
Lemieux anticipates new agreements between the team and the 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	In their plan, submitted Tuesday, SMG and Fox say they would  
make concessions that would mean an extra $5 million a year for the 
team above the already signed deals. 
</P>
<P>
	It also calls for Lemieux to be chairman of the team's  
management committee for $3 million up front, a 5 percent equity 
stake in the team with the possibility of another 5 percent in 
three years, and a salary of $200,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux, however, issued a statement after the plan was  
submitted saying he would not work for the companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
