<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Media General Cuts Denver Post Stake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Media General is selling half of its 40  
percent stake in The Denver Post to MediaNews Group, which owns the 
rest of the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Media General plans to use the proceeds of the sale to reduce  
its debt and expand its presence in the Southeast, where it already 
owns 21 daily newspapers and 13 television stations. 
</P>
<P>
	Together with a previously scheduled redemption of preferred  
stock in Denver Newspapers Inc., which runs the Post, the 
transaction will net Media General about $92 million. After the 
deal closes, Media General will own 20 percent of the Post and 
MediaNews will have the remaining 80 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	J. Stewart Bryan III, chairman and chief executive officer of  
Media General, said that combined with the $1.4 billion sale of the 
company's cable television division to Cox Communications announced 
last month, the Post transaction will give Media General 
``significant financial flexibility for future growth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Media General is an independent, publicly owned communications  
company based in Richmond, Va. It has interests in newspapers, 
broadcast television, recycled newsprint production and diversified 
information services. 
</P>
<P>
	MediaNews Group, a private, Denver-based company formed by W.  
Dean Singleton and Richard B. Scudder, owns clusters of newspapers 
in several states, including California, New Jersey and 
Pennsylvania. Last month, Singleton was elected to the board of 
directors of The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale is subject to regulatory approval, but company  
officials said they expect the deal to close by end of June. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
