<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 22:41:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Border Patrol Agents Combat Boredom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- George McCubbin, a 14-year veteran of the  
Border Patrol, started work at 4 p.m. and ended at midnight. In 
between, he sat in his Chevy Tahoe high on a hill, listened to a 
baseball game, reread an old Joseph Wambaugh novel, and waited for 
something to happen. 
</P>
<P>
	Nothing did.  
</P>
<P>
	``They tell us, this 'X' is your location. Now, stay there until  
we say you can leave,'' said McCubbin, head of the agents' local 
union. ``After a while it wears on you mentally. At the end of the 
day you don't feel like you've accomplished anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A crackdown on illegal immigration has brought much more calm to  
what was once the busiest sector of the 2000-mile border. But some 
agents say the boredom of working ``X'' shifts is taking a toll -- 
339 agents out of nearly 2,300 in the San Diego sector quit last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	During a typical ``X'' shift, an agent parks somewhere with a  
panoramic view along the U.S. side of the border, hoping their mere 
presence will discourage Mexican migrants from risking the 
crossing. 
</P>
<P>
	Border Patrol officials acknowledge that the ``X's'' --  
officially known as ``visual deterrent positions'' -- are not 
popular with the rank-and-file. But they maintain that the strategy 
has had only a minor effect on the agents' decision to leave the 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	``Agents have complained about the (``X's'') but the policy is  
very effective,'' said Border Patrol spokesman Robert Smith. ``It's 
a necessary evil.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both the union and the agency agree the strategy behind the  
``X's'' is a marked change for the Border Patrol. Agents sit for as 
many as nine hours, usually alone and with only a few breaks. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem for the agents is that fewer migrants risk an  
illegal crossing in San Diego County. Operation Gatekeeper, which 
more than doubled the number of agents in the 66-mile-long zone, 
has pushed most of the illegal traffic further east to inland 
California and Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	Arrests plummeted last year to 248,000, an 18-year low.  
</P>
<P>
	Agents are reluctant to voice their frustrations publicly for  
fear of endangering their jobs. But many complain of the tedium, as 
one agent put it, from having to ``stare at a fence all day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sector officials agree that attrition is a problem. But  
Villareal said economics is probably the real reason, not the 
``Xs.'' He supports the union's effort to win raises for the agents 
-- something that would be accomplished by a pending U.S. Senate 
bill. 
</P>
<P>
	An agent with a year's experience earns roughly $33,000 a year,  
plus an average of 10 percent to 15 percent more in overtime pay. 
</P>
<P>
	A third of agents who left last year were forced out because  
they failed tests in Spanish and law, said agency spokesman Roy 
Villareal. Another 31 percent received transfers or promotions to 
other sectors in the United States, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of agents on an ``X'' at any given moment varies by  
zone and shift. In the Imperial Beach Station, the westernmost part 
of the San Diego sector, between 20 and 28 agents work on ``X's'' 
out of about 225 officers on duty, Villareal said. 
</P>
<P>
	Others may find themselves on horse patrol, bike duty or  
training -- the kinds of work they expected on joining the patrol, 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the union wants more rotation of those who do find  
themselves on the ``X's'' and more opportunities in investigations. 
</P>
<P>
	``They really paint this exciting picture of the job but the job  
is anything but exciting,'' said Daryl Schermerhorn of the National 
Border Patrol Council. ``A guy with half a brain doesn't want to go 
sit around for nine hours.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 21:31:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cubs Get Closer Aguilera From Twins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Chicago Cubs, in need of a closer with  
struggling Rod Beck on the disabled list and considering elbow 
surgery, acquired Rick Aguilera from the Minnesota Twins on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubs sent minor league right-handers Kyle Lohse and Jason  
Ryan to the Twins in exchange for the 37-year-old Aguilera -- the 
Twins' all-time saves leader -- and minor league left-hander Scott 
Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's some mixed emotions,'' Aguilera said. ``My heart's  
kind of hurt, knowing I'm leaving. But on the other hand, I'm 
excited about what lies ahead. It was a tough day saying goodbye to 
my teammates and (manager) Tom Kelly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aguilera should fill the Cubs' gaping hole at closer. Beck saved  
51 games last season but has struggled all season. The burly 
right-hander was 2-4 with four blown saves and a 10.54 ERA before 
he went on the DL. 
</P>
<P>
	Beck flew to San Francisco for a second opinion Thursday on  
whether to have surgery on two bone spurs and bone chips in his 
right elbow. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to shore up the bullpen. Hopefully, Rick Aguilera can  
do that for us,'' Cubs manager Jim Riggleman said. ``We just didn't 
feel we could go forward without some experience in the bullpen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to Friday's game against the Atlanta Braves, the Cubs had  
converted only 11 of 21 save opportunities, and no reliever other 
than Beck had more than one save. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday night, Scott Sanders gave up a ninth-inning homer to  
Gerald Williams to squander a 5-4 lead. The Cubs eventually won 6-5 
in 12 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Aguilera was 3-1 with a 1.27 ERA and six saves in 17 games for  
the Twins this season. He came to Minnesota from the New York Mets 
in 1989 as a starter, but converted to the role of closer in 1990, 
compiling 254 saves. He also ranks first in club history in games 
pitched with 490. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just think he's an improvement over some of the pieces in  
our bullpen,'' Riggleman said. ``He's a good pitcher who can get 
outs in the ninth inning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aguilera was the last link to the Twins' World Series  
championship team in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a shame,'' Kelly said. ``It seems like a long time ago,  
I guess. I think everyone hates to see him go. He's been an 
outstanding player and he's represented the organization very well 
on and off the field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, Aguilera was traded to the Boston Red Sox for pitcher  
Frank Rodriguez. He was re-signed by the Twins in December 1995 to 
a three-year contract as a starting pitcher after spending the 
previous six seasons exclusively as a closer. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite three stints on the disabled list in 1996, he made 19  
starts, posting an 8-6 record while pitching 111 1-3 innings. 
Aguilera returned to the closer role in 1997 and has 70 saves over 
the past two-plus seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	He will join the Cubs in Atlanta on Saturday.  
</P>
<P>
	Lohse, 20, comes to the Twins from the Cubs Class A team in  
Daytona, and will report to Fort Myers in the Class A Florida State 
League. Ryan, 23, has been playing for West Tenn in the Double A 
Southern League and will report to Double A New Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	Downs, 23, returns to the Cubs organization after being traded  
to the Twins in November for Mike Morgan. After pitching for Fort 
Myers and New Britain, Downs will report to Daytona. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, Aguilera waived the no-trade clause in his contract  
so the Twins could keep cutting their payroll. Aguilera's salary 
for this year is $3.25 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been talking about getting Aguilera for a long time,''  
Riggleman said. ``We'd like to have him and Rod out there 
eventually. Hopefully, we will before the season is over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Twins, who began Friday with the worst record (13-27) in the  
AL, felt they had no choice other than trading their top reliever. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's going to be sorely missed here, but under the  
circumstances, we just couldn't get to him down there in our 
bullpen,'' general manager Terry Ryan said. ``I'd much rather have 
it turn out this way with us getting something than have him walk 
away and get nothing.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 17:41:24 </DATE_TIME>
