<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 00:21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  A Loud Pop, Then Chaos -- Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- The bell for the first class of the day was  
still 20 minutes away, leaving plenty of time for students at 
Heritage High School to mill about the common area next to the 
cafeteria. 
</P>
<P>
	Some nibbled on cinnamon rolls and sipped juice or milk while  
others just conversed with friends. For seniors, it was a time to 
revel in their last full day of school before graduation. 
</P>
<P>
	They were looking forward to getting their yearbooks signed and  
were braced for senior pranks. The previous day, jokesters let 
loose a large bag of crickets, and firecrackers had become almost 
an annual tradition. 
</P>
<P>
	Then suddenly, the chatter and laughter was interrupted by a  
loud popping sound. A 15-year-old sophomore wielding a .22-caliber 
rifle was standing in front of the girls' bathroom in the common 
area firing at his schoolmates. He was identified by students as 
Thomas Solomon. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was sitting in the common area when I heard something that  
sounded like fireworks. I turned around and saw him and I just ran 
out of the school and across the street to my friend's house,'' 
said Brittanie Berry, 15. ``I saw everybody yelling and running.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nathaniel Deeter, 15, was a friend of the gunman.  
</P>
<P>
	``I yelled to him, `Hey, what're you doing?' But he just kept  
shooting. And then the kid next to me got shot in the foot. Then I 
started to run,'' Deeter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Students took cover under benches and behind planters while  
others raced outside the one-story red brick building into the 
parking lot of the 1,300-student school. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody started throwing their book bags down and trying to  
get out, running as fast as they could,'' said Lee Merritt, 17. 
</P>
<P>
	Teachers and administrators in other parts of the building  
ushered students into classrooms, telling them to lock the doors. 
At least one teacher took her students into a closet, where she 
recited Bible verses. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were screaming at us over the intercom to get to our  
homerooms as fast as we could,'' said Jessie McCumber, 15. 
</P>
<P>
	After wounding six students, the gunman dropped the rifle and  
fled outdoors. He dropped to his knees, pulled out a .22-caliber 
revolver and stuck it in his mouth. But before he could shoot, 
assistant principal Cecil Brinkley talked him into dropping the 
weapon. The suspect broke down sobbing and was arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	Inside, cafeteria worker Teresa Kumar was preparing lunch and  
had walked into the cooler to get fruits and vegetables. When she 
emerged, everybody was gone and there were plates of grits, 
biscuits, and bowls of cereal left sitting on the tables. In the 
common area, she saw a wounded girl lying on the floor bleeding and 
screaming. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was hollering she wanted her mother and she was hollering  
that she was shot,'' Ms. Kumar said. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, small groups of students stood outside waiting for rides  
home and trading versions of how the event unfolded. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just crazy and chaos,'' said Alaina Mitchell, 16,  
hugging her brother, who had come to school to pick her up. 
</P>
<P>
	When the news first carried reports of the shooting, Janice Pugh  
waited at home for a while, hoping for a phone call from her only 
child, William. Finally she decided she couldn't wait any longer, 
so she went to Heritage. 
</P>
<P>
	Her voice cracking and her eyes red, she kept one arm wrapped  
around William while her other hand gripped a balled-up tissue. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not knowing what exactly had happened, not knowing what I  
would find, I just prayed that he would be all right,'' she said. 
``I'm just happy that he's OK and I pray for the others.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 16:10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. OKs Some Assistance to Iraqis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The U.N. Security Council agreed Friday to  
extend for six months a humanitarian program financed by oil 
exports aimed at helping ordinary Iraqis cope with economic 
sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
	The council unanimously adopted a resolution continuing the  
oil-for-food program. Its current mandate expires at midnight 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Security Council launched the program in 1996 to provide  
food, medicine and other humanitarian aid for Iraqis suffering 
under sanctions imposed after Baghdad's 1990 invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
<P>
	The program currently allows Iraq to export $5.26 billion in oil  
over six months to buy humanitarian supplies, as well as compensate 
Gulf War victims and fund U.N. operations in Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	The resolution adopted Friday would renew the oil-for-food  
program under the same terms, but promises to review the $5.26 
billion limit on oil exports should Iraq reach the ceiling. 
</P>
<P>
	Iraq is expected to sell a record $3.9 billion worth of oil in  
the current six-month phase, about $900 million over the previous 
high. 
</P>
<P>
	Although oil prices were at a 12-year low six months ago, a  
strong recovery coupled with Iraq's ability to export close to 2 
million barrels a day enabled Baghdad to set a revenue record. 
</P>
<P>
	But Benon V. Sevan, executive director of the U.N.'s Iraq  
Program, noted that oil prices dropped in the past week and 
stressed that the previous increase had still not enabled Baghdad 
to reach the $5.26 billion ceiling. 
</P>
<P>
	In a briefing to the council, he reiterated Secretary-General  
Kofi Annan's recent report, which concluded that oil-for-food 
``cannot -- and was never meant to -- meet all the humanitarian needs 
of the Iraqi people, nor can it restore Iraq's economic and social 
infrastructure to pre-1990 levels.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Echoing these concerns, Russia's U.N. Ambassador Sergey Lavrov  
said even if the oil-for-food program was improved, ``it would not 
be enough to solve the humanitarian crisis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Agreement on extending the program comes as the council is  
considering ways to improve the humanitarian program as part of a 
new overall policy towards Iraq in the aftermath of the 
U.S.-British airstrikes in December. 
</P>
<P>
	France had wanted to incorporate some of those suggested  
improvements into the resolution for the new six-month phase -- 
including eliminating the ceiling on Iraqi oil exports, an idea 
first raised by the United States in January. 
</P>
<P>
	However, with the recovery in world oil prices, Iraqi oil  
revenue has gone up, prompting the United States to rethink its 
proposal. U.S. officials are now talking about raising the ceiling 
instead. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, France settled for a promise from the council to  
review the $5.26 billion limit should Iraq reach the ceiling over 
the next six months. 
</P>
<P>
	The council remains divided on a long-term policy toward Iraq  
and reaching agreement is expected to take weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 18:51:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yankees Activate Clemens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Roger Clemens was activated from the 15-day  
disabled list tonight before his start against the Chicago White 
Sox. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens was placed on the DL on April 29, retroactive to the  
previous day, because of a strained left hamstring. He hurt the 
hamstring and had to leave after two innings of his previous start 
April 27. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens, shooting for an AL-record 18th straight victory, had to  
wait to make his first appearance in nearly a month when the start 
of Friday's game was delayed by rain. 
</P>
<P>
	To make room for Clemens, the Yankees optioned right-hander Todd  
Erdos to Triple-A Columbus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
