<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 11:11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Exhibit Features World of Microbes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An invisible world that can bring disease and  
death or health and pleasure can finally be seen -- at once 
beautiful and yucky -- at the Smithsonian Institution. 
</P>
<P>
	Welcoming the visitor to ``Microbes: Invisible Invaders, Amazing  
Allies,'' is a Medieval mask, its long, birdlike beak curving 
downward and providing space for pleasant-smelling flowers to 
protect the wearer from the bad smells and poisoned air thought to 
cause the plague. 
</P>
<P>
	The departing viewer gets a last treat, a glimpse of part of the  
original notebooks of Scottish scientist Alexander Fleming and a 
sample of the mold that he discovered contained penicillin. 
</P>
<P>
	In between, child and adult alike enters the world of microbes,  
sees the toll of death and illness they have inflicted on the world 
and meets their good uses too, from drugs to tasty mushrooms to 
blue cheese and yogurt. 
</P>
<P>
	``They think they're having fun, but they're also learning,''  
Dr. Randall E. Kaye of Pfizer Inc., the exhibit's sponsor, said 
Friday as visiting school children raced from exhibit to exhibit 
pressing buttons, playing video games, laughing and asking 
questions. 
</P>
<P>
	Officially opening Saturday, the exhibit is to remain in  
Washington through Sept. 6. It then travels to Chicago, Buffalo, 
N.Y., Cleveland, Fort Lauderdale, Fla., and Indianapolis, with more 
stops still being booked. It premiered in Toronto and visited 
Jersey City, N.J., Los Angeles, San Francisco and Dallas before 
arriving in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	On the exhibit's dark side, a photo of the face of an Egyptian  
mummy clearly shows the scars of smallpox. 
</P>
<P>
	Around a corner is a tiny, baby-size iron lung, a remembrance of  
before the advent of polio vaccines, when thousands of victims were 
confined to those steel drums to help them breathe. 
</P>
<P>
	A highlight is a large room where the viewer can see the world  
from the point of view of a microbe. The surroundings are other 
bacteria and germs and even a giant white blood cell looking for 
invading viruses. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearby, a series of hologram screens project 3-D images of the  
virus that causes AIDS, e. coli germs, streptococcus, salmonella 
and several other microbes. 
</P>
<P>
	In its own little room a world map invites visitors to press  
buttons marked with diseases such as tuberculosis, dengue fever, 
AIDS and others. The map lights to show where that disease is most 
prevalent. 
</P>
<P>
	But not all microbes are bad. The show notes that some help  
return nitrogen to the soil to help plants grow, others clean up 
oil and pesticides in the environment, billions of microbes in the 
intestines help digest food, and yeasts even help make bread rise 
and ferment beer and wine. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 12:41:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dana Plato's Death Ruled a Suicide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Former child actress Dana Plato's  
drug-overdose death was ruled a suicide Friday, not an accident as 
initially believed. 
</P>
<P>
	The 34-year-old former star of the NBC sitcom ``Diff'rent  
Strokes'' died May 8 while visiting her fiance's parents in Moore. 
Police initially said she died of an accidental overdose of a 
painkiller and Valium. 
</P>
<P>
	But Dr. Larry E. Balding, deputy state medical examiner, said  
Friday that she had fatal concentrations of the muscle relaxant 
Soma and a generic form of the painkiller Lortab in her body. She 
also had the equivalent of seven tablets of the muscle relaxant in 
her stomach. 
</P>
<P>
	Balding said the death was ruled a suicide because of the high  
level of drugs and her history of suicidal tendencies. She did not 
leave a suicide note. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Plato had been prescribed both drugs -- according to her  
fiance, for back injuries she suffered in a car accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Plato's life went into a tailspin after the sitcom's  
cancellation in 1984. In 1991, she was arrested for robbing a Las 
Vegas video store and placed on five years' probation. A year 
later, she was given another five years' probation for forging 
prescriptions for Valium. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I hadn't gotten caught, it could have been the worst thing  
that happened to me because I could have died of a drug overdose,'' 
she said then. 
</P>
<P>
	The day before her death, Ms. Plato went on Howard Stern's radio  
show in New York to deny a former roommate's claims that she was on 
drugs. Ms. Plato insisted she had been sober for about 10 years but 
said she had taken painkillers when her wisdom teeth were removed 
four months ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 19:05:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Sentenced for Role in Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) -- The girlfriend of a man who pleaded guilty  
to killing gay college student Matthew Shepard was sentenced Friday 
to up to two years in prison for helping to cover up evidence in 
the killing. 
</P>
<P>
	Chasity Vera Pasley, 20, cried repeatedly as she was sentenced  
to 15 months to two years in prison for being an accessory after 
the fact to first-degree murder. 
</P>
<P>
	Pasley said she was sorry for helping to dispose of bloody  
clothing her boyfriend, Russell Henderson, wore during the Oct. 7 
attack on Shepard, 21. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said Henderson and Aaron McKinney, both 21, posed as  
homosexuals and lured Shepard out of a bar before taking him to a 
remote area, pistol-whipping him and leaving him tied to a fence in 
the cold. He died five days later. 
</P>
<P>
	Pasley faced up to three years in prison.  
</P>
<P>
	``I needed to face up to what I did,'' Pasley said during her  
sentencing hearing. ``I can't bring him back. I'm sorry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pasley was one of two women accused of helping McKinney and  
Henderson dispose of Henderson' bloody clothes. 
</P>
<P>
	Henderson pleaded guilty last month to kidnapping and felony  
murder and was sentenced to consecutive life prison terms. McKinney 
has pleaded innocent and is scheduled to stand trial in August. He 
faces the death penalty if convicted of murder. 
</P>
<P>
	Kristen LeAnn Price, 19, was McKinney's girlfriend. She also was  
charged with being an accessory after the fact to first-degree 
murder, but her trial has been delayed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 14:22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Police: Teen Brought Guns From Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- The arrest of a quiet, churchgoing Boy Scout  
accused of shooting up his high school with weapons stolen from his 
stepfather's locked gun cabinet was a sharp reminder that it's not 
always the surly, trenchcoat-wearing outcasts who commit violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas Solomon Jr., 15, is charged with aggravated assault for  
wounding six fellow Heritage High School students. As more details 
about the sophomore emerged Friday, it became clear that he has 
little in common with the killers in last month's Colorado school 
shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	Writings by Dylan Klebold and Eric Harris -- outsiders ostracized  
at Columbine High School -- indicated that they wanted to kill as 
many people as possible and go down in a blaze of gore. 
</P>
<P>
	Solomon was a marksman with two deadly weapons -- a .357 Magnum  
revolver and a sawed-off rifle hidden in the legs of his baggy 
jeans -- and could have easily killed many students. But he 
apparently aimed at them below the waist so as only to wound them. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was just trying to be heard and not trying to kill  
anybody,'' said Kent Cason, 19. ``Two of my friends saw him walking 
into the cafeteria and he was loading a gun. He told them to stay 
there so they wouldn't get hurt, and then walked into the 
building.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And if Solomon really wanted to leave a trail of bodies behind,  
he could have stolen several more powerful weapons from his 
stepfather, according to Sheriff Jeff Wigington. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a lot more firepower available to him,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Experts said Solomon -- described as a typical teen who grew  
sullen after his girlfriend dumped him this week -- was making a 
desperate cry for attention. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly he had the option and the weapon to do more damage,  
and in not doing that, what he was doing was a way of getting 
attention,'' said Richard Gelles, professor of child welfare and 
family violence at the University of Pennsylvania. ``He knew he 
would get it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike Klebold and Harris, who killed 12 students and a teacher  
before taking their own lives, Solomon wasn't ostracized by the 
more popular students and didn't dress differently from his peers. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was just an average kid,'' said Joe Watts, a student.  
</P>
<P>
	``This case is a reminder that just because a particular child  
isn't in some group of alienated teens or doesn't have two nose 
rings or 15 tattoos doesn't mean that there's not a possibility 
that something tragic could happen,'' said Dr. Tom Cummins, a child 
and adolescent psychiatrist at Emory University Hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	The attack was the sixth mass shooting at an American high  
school or middle school since October 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Few, if any, of the other school killers wore their outcast  
status as clearly and boldly as the trenchcoat-clad Klebold and 
Harris did. 
</P>
<P>
	Luke Woodham, convicted of killing his mother and then two  
classmates in Pearl, Miss., in 1997, was in a cult-like group, but 
it held secretive meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he didn't stand out for the way he dressed, Kip Kinkel,  
who allegedly killed his parents and two fellow high school 
students last year in Springfield, Ore., had tortured animals, was 
fascinated with guns and had a quick temper. In middle school he 
was voted ``Most Likely to Start World War III.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Solomon, called T.J., is described as a clean-cut student with  
average grades that had slipped recently. He went to church with 
his family every week, and the night before the shooting he 
attended a Catholic youth group meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Friends said he became angry after the breakup and talked of  
ending his life or bringing a gun to school. But no one took him 
seriously. 
</P>
<P>
	With about 300 students crowded into the school's common area  
Thursday morning, Solomon fired 14 times -- 11 shots with the rifle 
and three times with the revolver. 
</P>
<P>
	Jason Cheek, a junior who was shot once in the buttocks and once  
in the leg, said students began chasing Solomon -- who was running 
and smiling as he fired from the hip -- after the rifle ran out of 
bullets. Solomon then fired with the revolver and fled outside. 
</P>
<P>
	There, he fell to his knees and put the gun in his mouth.  
</P>
<P>
	When Assistant Principal Cecil Brinkley followed him outside,  
Solomon raised the gun toward Brinkley. 
</P>
<P>
	``I stepped back a couple of steps and I turned to him again and  
I said, `Give me the gun,' and I said again, `Give me the gun,''' 
Brinkley said Friday. ``I saw him lower the barrel of the gun and I 
kept getting closer and closer to him. Then I held out my hands and 
he laid the gun in my hands. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then he gave me a real big bear hug and he said, `I'm scared,  
I'm scared,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Solomon must appear in juvenile court before he can be charged  
as an adult, something not expected before Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Students were expected to return to Heritage High on Monday, and  
graduation is to go on as scheduled May 28. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday morning, students streamed into Heritage Hills Baptist  
Church to meet with counselors and ministers. Some teens hugged in 
the parking lot before going inside the church. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're just all trying to get our lives back,'' said  
senior Brian Skelton, 18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
