<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Top Dole Adviser Quits Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Consultant Kieran Mahoney left Elizabeth  
Dole's campaign Friday, costing her a top adviser just as her GOP 
presidential effort appeared to be gaining steam. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole aides and Mahoney said the parting was amicable, although  
sources close to the candidate suggested it resulted partly from a 
power struggle. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wants to spend more time with his family,'' said Dole  
spokesman Ari Fleischer, calling the departure ``mutually agreed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to go home, and I will get to see my son awake  
tomorrow for the first time in a week,'' Mahoney said in a 
telephone interview. 
</P>
<P>
	The move was announced after a meeting between Mrs. Dole and  
Mahoney, who had assumed an unusual amount of control for a 
consultant. His departure leaves campaign manager Tom Daffron as 
Mrs. Dole's top adviser, eventually able to hire consultants who 
will report to him, an official close to Mrs. Dole said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wish Mrs. Dole the best. She's had a substantial last month  
and a half on the campaign trail, and I believe she's articulating 
issues that need to be heard and doing it better than any other 
candidate in that regard,'' Mahoney said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other officials close to Mrs. Dole said Mahoney's family  
concerns were complicated by growing disenchantment over his role 
in the campaign. He had expected to have more control, said the 
officials, whose assessment was not disputed by a Mahoney backer. 
</P>
<P>
	The sources spoke on condition of anonymity.  
</P>
<P>
	As Daffron and Fleischer assumed more authority in shaping Mrs.  
Dole's message, Mahoney's role decreased, said the two sources 
close to Mrs. Dole. One said Mahoney had little to do with the 
campaign in the past couple of weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Though speaking highly of Mrs. Dole, Mahoney seemed to suggest  
the fledgling campaign was more difficult to run than it should 
have been. Discussing the difficulty of balancing his family life 
with his job, he said, ``I had expected this to be more manageable 
in that regard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mahoney's hiring was questioned by Republican strategists who  
predicted he would clash with Mrs. Dole's small circle of longtime 
allies. Though no dispute ever spilled into the open, officials say 
there was friction from the beginning. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole had trouble raising money and finding her voice in the  
early days of her campaign, but a visit to Kosovo and an aggressive 
move to the political center on gun control gained her much-needed 
attention. 
</P>
<P>
	She hoped to add momentum to her campaign Saturday in a speech  
to Georgia Republicans. Two days after a school shooting near 
Atlanta, Mrs. Dole was expected to portray herself as a courageous 
advocate of some gun restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some in our party may not have liked what I said, but that's  
who I am and what I believe,'' Mrs. Dole said in a draft of her 
Saturday speech provided to The Associated Press. She was suffering 
from laryngitis on Friday, leaving some doubt that she would 
deliver the speech. 
</P>
<P>
	Praising the Senate for approving measures requiring background  
checks at gun shows and the sale of safety locks with guns, Mrs. 
Dole said in the prepared remarks, ``The House of Representatives 
should do the same.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an apparent reference to Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the GOP  
front-runner, Mrs. Dole suggested her rival must speak up on gun 
control. ``Leadership requires more than sitting on a front porch 
measuring which direction the gunsmoke is blowing,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	In response, Mindy Tucker, a spokeswoman for Bush, said: ``Gov.  
Bush has a record in office of enacting tough laws on those who 
commit crimes with a gun. In fact, this coming week he will sign a 
bill that will require automatic detention for juveniles caught 
with illegal possession of a gun.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
