<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers Mystify Glen Rice  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- As well as San Antonio has played  
defense, Glen Rice believes the Spurs have had some help. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're making their job a lot easier than we should,'' the Los  
Angeles Lakers forward said. ``I'm just standing out buried on the 
wing or buried deep in the corner and guys are getting their rest. 
They're able to save a lot of energy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs brought a 2-0 lead into Game 3 today at the Forum,  
where Game 4 in the best-of-7 Western Conference semifinal series 
is Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in a tough spot, but we don't feel that the emergency  
lights have to go on,'' Lakers point guard Derek Fisher said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Fisher agrees that Rice isn't being utilized in a way that  
makes him as effective as he was in the first round against 
Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	``We get stagnated trying to give the ball to Shaq or maybe Kobe  
tries to make a play,'' he said. ``We're allowing those guys to 
make the play for us. What happens is everybody ends up standing 
around. 
</P>
<P>
	``Shaq and Kobe are our stars and our main two weapons, but  
we've got Glen. We have to figure out ways to keep him involved in 
the game at all times,'' Fisher said. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite a 34-14 all-time record at home against the Spurs,  
history suggests the Lakers are in trouble. They haven't recovered 
from a 2-0 deficit to win a best-of-7 series since the trio of 
Elgin Baylor, Wilt Chamberlain and Jerry West did so in 1968-69. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, the Lakers are 0-9 in playoff series in which they  
lost the first two games, including losses to Utah each of the last 
two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a difficult task for us, but I just think the way we  
played in the first two games isn't the best that we can play,'' 
Lakers backup guard Derek Harper said. ``We have to go into 
tomorrow's game with a very aggressive approach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs have lost four straight at the Forum, including twice  
in the regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a big hurdle for us,'' Spurs forward Tim Duncan said.  
``The Lakers are a very confident team. They're going to come in 
here with some great emotion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Lakers say they beat themselves in losing Game 1 87-81 and  
Game 2 by three points Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our biggest problem in game one is that we weren't aggressive  
enough,'' Fisher said. ``In game two, we came out a little 
aggressive but we made too many mistakes, so we have to find that 
good mix right in the middle with being aggressive but still play 
smart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs expect Shaquille O'Neal to take more than the 11 shots  
he had in Game 2, and they want to challenge each one. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been very aggressive going down there,'' said Spurs  
center David Robinson, who along with fellow 7-footer Duncan, has 
frustrated O'Neal. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he wants to take tough shots with guys on him, then that's  
a good thing for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just because O'Neal has averaged 18.5 points in the series --  
well below his season average -- doesn't mean the Spurs are 
overconfident. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the reasons why we've played him pretty good thus far  
is because we fear him so much,'' Avery Johnson said. ``He can come 
in the next game, in our minds, playing like he's going to get 38. 
The minute you start to relax and don't fear him as much, then 
you're going to really be killed.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
