<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 03:34:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Teammates to Face Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- They were younger then and didn't know better.  
</P>
<P>
	Joe Nieuwendyk was a second-year center and Theo Fleury a rookie  
right wing when the Calgary Flames won the Stanley Cup in 1989. 
With long careers ahead, both hoped to have their names engraved a 
few more times. 
</P>
<P>
	A decade later, they're still waiting.  
</P>
<P>
	For one of them, that moment may be only a few weeks away. Both  
are in the Western Conference finals -- Nieuwendyk for the Dallas 
Stars and Fleury for the Colorado Avalanche -- which means one of 
them will advance to the NHL finals. 
</P>
<P>
	The series between top-seeded Dallas and second-seeded Colorado  
begins Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were the regular-season champions and were far and above  
the best team,'' Fleury said of the Stars. ``We're going to have 
our work cut out for us, but it's going to be fun. It's going to be 
exciting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fleury remained with Calgary until he was traded to Colorado on  
Feb. 28. He would've been an unrestricted free agent this summer 
and the Flames dealt him because they knew he wasn't likely to 
re-sign. 
</P>
<P>
	The 5-foot-6, 160-pounder with the laser shot and quick skates  
scored in his first game for the Avalanche but also sprained his 
right knee. He missed seven games, then scored again in his first 
game back. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's really an opportunistic kind of guy,'' Nieuwendyk said.  
``He won't be overly aggressive on the forecheck, but he'll be the 
guy coming in late who seems to get the goal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fleury has done a good job of it in the playoffs, scoring five  
goals and assisting on nine others. His 14 points tie teammate Joe 
Sakic for third in the playoffs. Another teammate, Peter Forsberg, 
leads the list with 17 points. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fleury is another threat for them, but he's not asked to carry  
the load like he was in Calgary the last few years,'' Nieuwendyk 
said. ``I think he's a real good fit for that team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because Fleury is on a team loaded with scorers, opponents are  
hesitant to target him for fear of being hurt by someone else. 
Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock said his team's biggest challenge will 
be finding a way to handle Colorado's depth. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you know you have more firepower, you can almost play  
cocky at times,'' Hitchcock said. ``Fleury brings that cocky 
attitude that says, `We're going to beat you with the puck and beat 
you bad.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Nieuwendyk decided he didn't want to play for Calgary any more  
in 1995. He held out at the beginning of the season until being 
traded to Dallas in February. 
</P>
<P>
	He was the Stars' MVP last season, when he picked up the slack  
following an injury to Mike Modano and led the team in points and 
goals. But midway through the first period of the first postseason 
game, he blew out his right knee on a vicious hit from San Jose's 
Bryan Marchment. Dallas reached the Western Conference finals, but 
Nieuwendyk could only cheer them on. 
</P>
<P>
	This postseason, Nieuwendyk is making up for the lost time. His  
three game-winning goals are tied for the playoff lead, as are his 
two overtime goals. Over 10 games, he has six goals and three 
assists. 
</P>
<P>
	Avalanche coach Bob Hartley said Nieuwendyk is one of several  
players his team must contain. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have lots of speed, especially at center with Joe  
Nieuwendyk and Mike Modano,'' Hartley said. ``They have speed, size 
and a lot of great two-way players.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
