<DOCNO> APW19990521.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 06:11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Salt Lake Panel Gets Tech Nod </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Cash-hungry organizers of Salt Lake City's  
Olympics got one thing they wanted from the International Olympic 
Committee this week: the nod to go after technology sponsors. 
</P>
<P>
	The Salt Lake Organizing Committee and OPUS, the marketing  
company it runs jointly with the U.S. Olympic Committee, have 
hesitated to recruit those corporate sponsors because technology 
has been the IOC's purview in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	No more, said Mitt Romney, chief executive of the SLOC, speaking  
Thursday at the end of four days of meetings between the IOC 
Coordination Commission and Salt Lake City executives. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're taking the blinders off,'' Romney said. ``There is a  
huge virgin territory in the information technology marketplace. We 
need to get after it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tentative agreements forged this week ``open to us  
potentially millions of dollars,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Those millions are badly needed by a committee scarred by  
scandal this winter and still $300 million short of meeting its 
$1.45 billion budget. 
</P>
<P>
	Vows of cooperation, such as on the technology sponsor front,  
were the byword of the meetings here this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission, comprised of IOC members and international  
sports officials, offered suggestions ranging from opening the beer 
and wine spigots at the press center to setting aside an 
athletes-only traffic lane between the Olympic Village in Salt Lake 
City and the ski venues in Park City. 
</P>
<P>
	Marc Hodler, the Swiss IOC member who is chairman of the  
commission, suggested Salt Lake City hope for no snow since the 
artificial variety is preferable from an athletic and logistical 
standpoint. ``That is the only thing man does better than God,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a gesture to show the IOC does not demand luxury, it decided  
to stay at the existing Little America hotel, not in the more 
opulent Little America Tower being built across the street. The 
tower will have suites, but IOC members need only double-bed rooms, 
Hodler said. 
</P>
<P>
	That will mean SLOC can erase a $1.2 million contingency it  
built into its budget in case room rates exceeded $200 per night 
the IOC was obligated to pay. 
</P>
<P>
	The deputy chairman of the commission, Jean-Claude Killy of  
France, assured that ``the IOC will pay for its rooms,'' Romney 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission also endorsed keeping figure skating in the Delta  
Center by adding seats close to the ice so athletes see spectators' 
faces and by using two jumbo screens at the end of the arena to 
give all fans good views. Both athletes and spectators grumbled 
after the U.S. Figure Skating Championships in February. 
</P>
<P>
	And the IOC welcomed the SLOC announcement it wants to add five  
events to the games, bringing the total to 75, the most ever for a 
Winter Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Romney said he's confident the SLOC board and IOC will approve  
adding women's bobsled, men's and women's skeleton (a headfirst 
plunge on a small sled down an ice chute at 70 mph) and men's and 
women's cross-country sprints. The events will use the track 
already build for luge and bobsled as well as the biathlon trail to 
be built this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The cost of adding the events, after figuring in ticket sales,  
is $650,000, said Cathy Priestner-Allinger, director of sport for 
the committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Jen Davidson, a 26-year-old exercise physiologist at  
Intermountain Health Care and women's bobsledder, said she was 
elated by the decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been working long and hard on this,'' Davidson said.  
``I'm pretty happy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davidson, who lives in Layton, Utah, was the brakeman on the  
bobsled team that won three gold and five silver medals during the 
recent World Cup season. 
</P>
<P>
	Fraser Bullock, the chief operating officer, said the organizing  
committee and the U.S. Olympic Committee are close to finding $5 
million to pay for operating the Utah Winter Sports Park, including 
its bobsled luge track, until the games. 
</P>
<P>
	The SLOC has been threatening to close down the park at times to  
save $5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Romney said details of the new technology sponsor approach  
remain to be worked out, but Salt Lake and OPUS are free to go 
after sponsors that could help it sell tickets and merchandise on 
the Internet, a $30 million category, as well as other types of 
sponsors. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC will continue negotiating for the computer hardware  
itself, and it has not been decided who will pursue systems 
analysis companies, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Romney said the agreements will be finalized when the IOC  
executive board meets in Seoul, South Korea, next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
