<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> RaytSaid Dropping Chat Board Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- Raytheon has reportedly dropped a  
lawsuit against 21 people it had accused of revealing the company's 
financial secrets on an Internet chat site. 
</P>
<P>
	Raytheon filed papers yesterday in Middlesex Superior Courtto  
dismiss the suit that had claimed the postings cost it $25,000 and 
hurt its business reputation, according to a report in today's 
editions of The Boston Globe. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lexington-based defense contractor said the move had  
protected its financial information. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think it brings the matter to a close,'' Raytheon spokesman  
David Polk told the Globe. ``Our internal activities are over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The defendants, at least some of whom were Raytheon employees,  
discussed corporate business on a World Wide Web site run by Yahoo! 
Topics included the company's stock price and gripes about the 
chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	The defendants used aliases like ``Rayman-mass'' and  
``RaytheonVeteran,'' which they believed would protect their 
identities. 
</P>
<P>
	But the defense contractor obtained their names after filing  
discovery motions against Yahoo! and other Internet providers, 
drawing attention to how easy it is to learn the identities behind 
supposedly anonymous Internet screen names. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet free speech groups were critical of the Internet  
providers, saying they caved in to Raytheon after giving the 
impression they'd do more to protect users' privacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Four of the employees named in the suit have since left  
Raytheon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
