<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blijlevens Takes Italy's 7th Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LANCIANO, Italy (AP) -- Jeroen Blijlevens of the Netherlands  
earned his second stage victory in the Tour of Italy cycling race 
Friday, outsprinting Latvian Romans Vainsteins and Italy's Fabrizio 
Guidi. 
</P>
<P>
	French champion Laurent Jalabert retained the pink jersey as  
overall leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Blijlevens, winner of the third stage at Messina and a former  
race leader, rushed ahead with 200 meters left in the seventh stage 
and won easily. 
</P>
<P>
	Vainsteins, winner of Thursday's stage, finished second and  
Guidi was third in the 94.8-mile stage. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner was timed in 4 hours, 12 minutes, 6 seconds.  
</P>
<P>
	Overall, Jalabert led Italy's Danilo Di Luca by seven seconds.  
Defending champion Marco Pantani was fifth, 22 seconds behind. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the start of Friday's stage, Pantani, Jalabert and world  
road champion Oscar Camenzind led a strong protest against blood 
tests carried out by doctors of the Italian Olympic Committee. 
Cyclists considered the new tests an unneeded duplication of blood 
controls made by the International Cycling Union (UIC) at the start 
of last Saturday's race. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not against random anti-doping tests by UIC, but we  
don't want duplicated controls ... If CONI tests are renewed in the 
next days, we are ready to stop the race and return home,'' said 
Pantani, who represented most of the 156 cyclists in the Giro. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's eighth stage of 156.8 miles in the 22-leg event  
includes three climbs and a tough finish at Gran Sasso d'Italia, at 
2,130 meters of altitude in the Apennines mountains. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
