<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Disney Execs Plan Web Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) -- Two former Walt Disney Co.  
executives are joining forces to create an entertainment Internet 
site that will be able to personalize its presentation to meet the 
interests of users. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Ovitz, who served a brief tenure as president of Disney,  
and former Disney Online president Richard Wolpert hope to 
distinguish their site, CheckOut.com, from dozens of other 
e-commerce portals by offering fans more than just an opportunity 
to buy products. 
</P>
<P>
	Users will be able to listen to music, watch videos and read the  
latest news and archived stories about actors, musicians and 
digital game designers. 
</P>
<P>
	But the selling point stressed by Wolpert and Ovitz during a  
brief demonstration Thursday is CheckOut.com's ability to 
personalize the site. Once a user indicates interest in a 
particular artist, music style or subject, the screen is filled 
with references and options for related information. The site is 
designed to ``remember'' the user's preferences by tracking icons 
that are clicked. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we have is the ultimate destination for entertainment  
data,'' said Ovitz. ``It's not all about buying. It's not like an 
Amazon.com.'' 
</P>
<P>
	CheckOut.com, scheduled to be up and running by midsummer, also  
may reflect the ultimate business partnership. 
</P>
<P>
	It combines Ovitz's powerful influence in the entertainment  
world with Wolpert's experience helping Disney create and manage 
some of the leading Internet sites, including Disney.com, The 
Disney Internet Guide and The Disney Store Online. 
</P>
<P>
	Joining Ovitz and Wolpert is former grocery store magnate Ron  
Burkle. Known in Hollywood for star-studded political fund-raisers 
at his 40-room Beverly Hills mansion, Burkle made headlines last 
October when his Yucaipa Cos. holding company sold Fred Meyer Inc. 
to Kroger Corp. for $8 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Burkle, who on Wednesday night held a reception and dinner for  
Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo, did not join Wolpert and Ovitz 
in the interview. 
</P>
<P>
	A few weeks after the Kroger deal was announced, Wolpert left  
Disney to develop online ventures for Yucaipa. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether the high-powered team can make CheckOut.com a force in  
the competitive world of electronic commerce may depend on how well 
they work together, said Ron Rappaport, an e-commerce analyst with 
Zona Research. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a nice track record on paper and certainly the  
connections are there to make something happen, but making it 
happen is the challenge that separates the ambitious from the 
successful in the Internet industry,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Personalized, one-to-one retailing has been a goal of Internet  
designers for some time, said Rappaport. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Ovitz and Wolpert are trying to surf a fairly  
significant wave that marketers have been dealing for a few 
years,'' he said. ``Kudos to this team if they can turn theory into 
reality.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Ovitz, the deal is the latest of many since the former super  
agent made a bitter break with Disney. Ovitz left after less than a 
year as Disney's No. 2 executive, reportedly because of a dispute 
over power sharing with Disney chairman and chief executive Michael 
Eisner. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, he has become a partner in Livent Inc., the troubled  
live theater company, and backed an unsuccessful bid to lure a 
National Football League franchise to Carson, Calif., where he, 
Burkle and others planned to build a new stadium. Ovitz also has 
formed Artists Management Group, which represents Robin Williams 
and other Hollywood stars. 
</P>
<P>
	Ovitz's vision for CheckOut.com includes creating a broad  
entertainment experience that will keep users' attention even if 
they don't buy on every visit. Eventually, the site probably will 
include live shows and the opportunity to download music. 
Initially, CDs, videos and games will be ordered but not delivered 
online. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
