<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Gun Vote Reflects NRA Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Campaign contributions from the National Rifle  
Association proved an accurate barometer of how individual senators 
would vote on a series of gun control measures this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty-two of the 34 senators who supported the NRA on each of  
four key votes received money for their last election from the 
organization that lobbies for gun owners' rights. Only two of the 
38 senators who opposed the NRA on the same four votes received 
contributions from the gun group. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a 51-50 vote to require background checks for firearms  
buyers at gun shows and pawn shops that clearly reflected the 
momentum toward tighter regulations in the aftermath of recent 
school shootings. Only two of the 50 senators who supported that 
amendment received NRA money. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our members support elected officials and candidates who  
believe in the Bill of Rights, the Second Amendment and the right 
of lawful Americans to own firearms,'' NRA spokesman Bill Powers 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Campaign finance experts said the correlation between votes and  
contributions is not surprising. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you want to know how a candidate is going to vote, follow  
the money that they're collecting when they're running for 
office,'' said Larry Makinson, executive director of the Center for 
Responsive Politics, a nonpartisan research group. ``It's very 
difficult for candidates to vote against their own cash 
constituents. They will do so only reluctantly and rarely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NRA opposed efforts to add gun control provisions to the  
juvenile crime bill in the wake of school shootings in Colorado and 
Georgia. The bill passed the Senate late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone knows this won't stop the crisis in our schools,''  
Executive Vice President Wayne LaPierre and chief lobbyist James 
Baker said. ``The American people want existing gun laws enforced 
and their Second Amendment freedoms protected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The five senators who received the most money from the NRA  
between 1993 and 1998 all sided with the gun lobby as it tried to 
defeat several amendments, led by GOP Sen. Rick Santorum of 
Pennsylvania, who has received $19,600 since 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Another senator who supported the NRA down the line was GOP  
Slade Gorton of Washington, who has received $11,400 from the gun 
lobby since 1993. On Saturday, while the bill was on the Senate 
floor, he held two fund-raisers in his home state featuring NRA 
President Charlton Heston. 
</P>
<P>
	Gorton told his supporters that Congress couldn't solve the  
problem of gun violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wish I could tell you the government could pass a law that  
can prevent this from happening,'' Gorton said. ``But the evil in 
Littleton is beyond the scope of the federal government.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NRA opposed two amendments by Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.,  
to require background checks on all firearms purchases at gun 
shows. The earlier Lautenberg amendment failed, 51-47, but a recast 
measure passed, 51-50, when Vice President Al Gore cast the 
deciding vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The 50 senators who voted against the second Lautenberg  
amendment received an average of $7,377 from the NRA. Only two of 
the 50 senators supporting the provision -- Democrat Kent Conrad of 
North Dakota and Republican Mike DeWine of Ohio -- received any NRA 
contributions. Conrad got $2,000; DeWine, $4,900. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are responsible checks to prevent guns from getting into  
the hands of felons, the mentally ill and kids,'' Conrad said. 
``Frankly, the NRA has become extreme. They're out of step with 
mainstream America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel that the requirement to follow the Brady gun-check law  
should apply to everyone at a gun show and that's what this 
amendment did,'' said DeWine said. ``It basically closed a loophole 
in current law; I did not find it to be an unreasonable 
requirement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sens. Mike Enzi, R-Wyo., and Thad Cochran, R-Miss., were the  
only two NRA supporters who did not receive any contributions from 
the organization. But the NRA did give $4,950 to Cochran's 
leadership political action committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
