<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soccer Violence Leaves 18 Injured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANTWERP, Belgium (AP) -- Sunday's playoff game at Royal Antwerp  
was postponed because of stadium damage after 11 policemen and 
seven spectators were injured during clashes with soccer vandals. 
</P>
<P>
	Two policemen were seriously injured late Thursday when they  
were attacked with iron bars, stones, pointed bats and even a 
scythe. Five suspects remained in detention Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The violence started when Antwerp yielded three late goals and  
lost 3-1 to Turnhout. Antwerp fans first attacked opposing fans in 
the stands, injuring seven. Afterward, they broke open an equipment 
shed and attacked police. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just getting sick of all this,'' Mayor Leona Detiege said  
after banning Sunday's game. ``It is just too much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said the club refused to make sufficient efforts to contain  
rioters following the game. 
</P>
<P>
	The city postponed the playoff against La Louviere, and the  
Belgian soccer federation has yet to reschedule the game. 
</P>
<P>
	There has been no estimate of the damage to the stadium,  
although fences were destroyed and walls were cracked in the 
mayhem. 
</P>
<P>
	Royal Antwerp, Belgium's oldest team, for years has supplied  
players for English powerhouse Manchester United. 
</P>
<P>
	It long was one of Belgium's best teams and reached the European  
Cup Winners Cup final six years ago. But it has gone downhill since 
and was relegated from the top division last year. 
</P>
<P>
	It was expected to bounce back this season, but missed out the  
Division Two title and now has only an outside chance to advance in 
the playoffs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
