<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Five Dead in Conn. Car Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MERIDEN, Conn. (AP) -- Five people were killed when a pickup  
truck slammed head-on Friday night into a car on a Connecticut 
highway. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nissan truck was traveling in the northbound lanes of  
Interstate 91 when it crossed the median and hit a Volkswagen 
Beetle, state police spokesman Lt. Ralph Carpenter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two men and two women were in the car. Three of the people died  
at the scene and a fourth victim died at a hospital/. The male 
driver of the truck was also killed. 
</P>
<P>
	All of the victims were from Connecticut, police said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 13:37:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Syria Ready for Talks With Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- Syria told Israel's new prime minister  
Friday it was ready to resume peace talks and urged him to 
negotiate simultaneously with Lebanon. 
</P>
<P>
	Official Syrian radio urged Israel's Prime Minister-elect Ehud  
Barak to deal with the Syrian and Lebanese peace talks as one since 
``the two are unified.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``A commitment from Barak's government would, no doubt, give  
Syrian-Israeli talks a fruitful start and would help to find a 
solution,'' the radio said. Syria has nearly 35,000 soldiers in 
Lebanon and is the major power broker in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	The radio added that Syria was ready to restart peace  
negotiations with Israel where they left off in early 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	At that time, the negotiating team of Israeli Prime Minister  
Shimon Peres had reportedly agreed to a full withdrawal from the 
Golan Heights, a strategic plateau that Israel captured in the 1967 
Arab-Israeli War and subsequently annexed. 
</P>
<P>
	Then in June 1996, Benjamin Netanyahu, who opposed such a  
withdrawal, took office as Israel's prime minister and refused to 
pick up talks where his predecessor had left off. Negotiations have 
been on hold since. 
</P>
<P>
	Syria is reported to have welcomed Netanyahu's defeat in this  
week's elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak, who was elected Monday, has pledged to withdraw Israeli  
troops from Lebanon within a year. Israel has occupied a zone of 
southern Lebanon since 1985 as a buffer against guerrilla attacks 
on its northern towns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 08:42:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Said Punishing Credit Suisse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's financial authorities will order Credit  
Suisse Group to suspend its Japanese operations as punishment for 
obstructing an inspection by the Financial Supervisory Agency, a 
news report said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Swiss financial group has been accused of dubious financial  
transactions intended to conceal losses at Japanese companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The FSA, Japan's financial watchdog, believes senior Credit  
Suisse officials in Japan hid and destroyed documents, Kyodo News 
reported, quoting unidentified agency officials. 
</P>
<P>
	FSA officials were not available for comment late today.  
</P>
<P>
	The report did not say how long the company's operations might  
be suspended. 
</P>
<P>
	Kyodo said the agency is also likely to punish the officials  
accused of tampering with the evidence, and will decide on final 
actions against the Swiss banking group by the end of June. 
</P>
<P>
	Credit Suisse allegedly used derivatives to hide stockholding  
losses at Japanese financial institutions, including Nippon Credit 
Bank, and other non-financial companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Friday, Credit Suisse said in Zurich, Switzerland it had  
suspended some employees and bonuses in connection with the FSA's 
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Credit Suisse said an independent probe by an international law  
firm found that ``some employees attempted to obstruct the (FSA) 
inspection during its early stages.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The law firm, Wilmer Cutler and Pickering, found that several  
managers and other staffers tried to interfere with FSA's probe in 
its initial stages by hiding and destroying documents, Credit 
Suisse said. 
</P>
<P>
	The employees allegedly sought to conceal activities that may  
have violated the strict regulatory separation of the banking and 
securities business in Japan, Credit Suisse said the lawyers' 
report found. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank said it regretted that misconduct and made an apology  
to Japan's regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	But Credit Suisse said, ``There was no evidence of efforts to  
conceal derivatives transactions, or transactions involving failed 
Japanese financial institutions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Newspaper reports have alleged that Credit Suisse's investment  
bank, Credit Suisse First Boston Corp., marketed several plans to 
help Japanese companies hide losses. 
</P>
<P>
	The law firm's report ``concludes that a few individuals in  
leadership positions failed both the company and its employees,'' 
Credit Suisse said. 
</P>
<P>
	Credit Suisse said it would make internal management and  
structural changes to ``repair the breach of the group's code of 
conduct.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
