<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Refugee Flow to Albania Resumes  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Breaking a week-long lull, a new  
tide of Kosovo refugees poured into Albania today. Many in the wave 
of 2,500 spoke of Serb security forces banging on their doors and 
ordering them to leave. Meanwhile, NATO bombed a Kosovo jail today, 
killing at least 19 people and injuring many, Yugoslavia state 
media reported. After reports of desertions by Yugoslav army 
reservists, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said troops who showed up 
in two central Serbian towns this week were just soldiers returning 
home as part of a reduction of Serb forces in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	H.S. Gunman Charged With Assault  
</P>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- The despondent boy who allegedly wounded six  
students at a suburban Atlanta high school was charged with 
aggravated assault today. Thomas Solomon Jr., 15, used a .357 
Magnum revolver and a sawed-off rifle and could have easily killed 
many Heritage High School students. But he apparently aimed at them 
below the waist so as only to wound them. Solomon was known as a 
quiet, churchgoing Boy Scout who supposedly stole the weapons from 
his stepfather's locked gun cabinet. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Signs Kosovo Spending Plan  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton signed a $15 billion  
spending bill toay to support the military operation in Yugoslavia 
and peace in the Middle East, and provide relief to Central 
American hurricane victims and Midwest farmers. In doing so, 
Clinton set aside his objections to several ``ill-advised'' items 
added to the measure in Congress. But he warned that he would 
reject future budget bills that include extraneous riders. 

</P>
<P>
	Top Dole Adviser Quits Campaign  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Consultant Kieran Mahoney left Elizabeth  
Dole's campaign today, costing her a top adviser just as her GOP 
presidential effort appeared to be gaining steam. Dole aides and 
Mahoney said the parting was amicable, although sources close to 
the candidate suggested it resulted partly from a power struggle. 
Mahoney, however, had assumed an unusual amount of control for a 
consultant. His departure leaves campaign manager Tom Daffron as 
Mrs. Dole's top adviser. 

</P>
<P>
	Kids May Fuel `Star Wars' Success  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The ``Star Wars'' prequel was poised to  
shatter its own single-day triumph and vanquish weekend box office 
records as theaters braced today for a torrent of children. 
Youngsters could be the key to the success of ``Star Wars: Episode 
1 -- The Phantom Menace.'' Analysts expect the George Lucas film to 
gross $120 million to $140 million by the end of its five-day 
opening frame. 

</P>
<P>
	Many Plan To Withdraw Cash for Y2K  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Most people in a new survey say they  
anticipate little effect from the Year 2000 computer problem on 
their bank accounts -- but that's not stopping them from setting 
aside a little extra cash in the days before New Year's. A new 
Gallup poll of 1,606 adults showed that the vast majority -- nearly 
79 percent -- said they fully expect the Y2K problem to have 
``little or no impact'' on their personal finances. But almost 
two-thirds of them said they expect to set aside extra cash in the 
days before New Year's Day. 

</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com Backs Off Book Ban  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Responding to e-mail complaints, Amazon.com says  
it will restore a book critical of the Scientology movement to its 
online catalog. The book, ``A Piece of Blue Sky,'' by British 
writer Jon Atack, was banned by a British court following a 
successful 1995 defamation lawsuit against Atack. Amazon said the 
book would be able to be shipped in a matter of days, after coding 
is put in place to make sure copies aren't shipped to British 
addresses. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Down 37.46  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices were mixed today as investors,  
worried about the effect rising interest rates might have on 
big-name stocks, moved money into small-cap issues. The Dow 
industrials ended at 10,829.28, down 37.46. On the NYSE, gainers 
led losers 1,599-1,327. The technology-heavy Nasdaq fell 22.09 to 
2,520.14. 

</P>
<P>
	Jets Up for Sale After Hess' Death  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The family of Leon Hess has hired Goldman, Sachs  
&AMP; Co. to manage the sale of the New York Jets. Goldman Sachs 
handled the sale of the Cleveland Browns for the NFL last year. The 
process took several months and had six candidates, including 
Alfred Lerner, who paid $530 million. It has been estimated the 
Jets might sell for about $500 million. 

</P>
<P>
	Boxer Tyson Granted Parole  
</P>
<P>
	ROCKVILLE, Md. (AP) -- Mike Tyson, in jail since February for  
assaulting two motorists, was granted parole today and is scheduled 
for release no later than June 4. The Maryland Parole Commission 
voted 5-1 to grant the former heavyweight champion his release, 
contingent upon approval by Indiana authorities. His jail term was 
to expire in September. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  

</P>
