<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel OKs Foster Kids' Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Legislation that would double money for  
programs to help thousands of foster children make the leap to 
adulthood cleared a House panel Thursday and drew a strong 
endorsement from President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ways and Means human resources subcommittee approved the  
bill, which would expand services to foster children ages 18 to 21 
by increasing the funding from $70 million to $140 million next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The main sponsor, Rep. Nancy Johnson, R-Conn., said the money  
would provide job training, housing assistance and other services 
for an estimated 20,000 foster children who are abruptly dropped 
from the system once they reach age 18. 
</P>
<P>
	States could also use the money for younger foster kids who are  
nearing age 18 for such things as assistance in obtaining a high 
school diploma, post-secondary education, job placement and 
training in daily living skills. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, who proposed similar legislation in his budget, said in  
a statement he would work with Congress to help the measure pass 
and ``enable these young people to live up to their God-given 
potential.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said House GOP leaders have pledged to bring the bill to  
a floor vote in June. Its next stop is the full Ways and Means 
Committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
