<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 39 File To Enter NBA Draft Early </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Duke's Elton Brand, college basketball's player  
of the year as a sophomore, and Rhode Island's Lamar Odom, the 
Atlantic 10 tournament MVP, are among 39 players who have filed as 
early entry candidates for the NBA draft. 
</P>
<P>
	The draft is June 30 at the MCI Center in Washington. Players  
who have filed for early entry can withdraw from consideration by 
notifying the NBA at least one week prior to the draft. 
</P>
<P>
	The present early entry list includes five freshmen, 11  
sophomores, 11 juniors, two high school players and 10 foreigners. 
</P>
<P>
	Brand, a 6-foot-8 forward, averaged 17.7 points, 9.8 rebounds  
and 2.21 blocked shots per game in leading Duke into the NCAA 
championship game. 
</P>
<P>
	Odom, a 6-10 sophomore forward, averaged 17.6 points, 9.4  
rebounds and 3.8 assists for Rhode Island. His 3-pointer at the 
buzzer gave the Rams a 62-59 victory over Temple in the A-10 
tournament title game. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other early entry candidates are: juniors Richard Hamilton  
of national champion Connecticut and Steve Francis of Maryland, 
sophomore Baron Davis of UCLA, and high school stars Jonathan 
Bender of Picayune (Miss.) High and Leon Smith of Chicago's Martin 
Luther King High. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, sophomore Ron Artest of St. John's, sophomore William  
Avery and freshman Corey Maggette of Duke, redshirt freshman Dion 
Glover of Georgia Tech, and junior Jamaal Magliore of Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	Glover, however, reportedly had a change of heart, and a final  
decision was expected by Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton, an All-American, helped UConn win the NCAA title after  
averaging 21.5 points and 4.8 rebounds. Francis led Maryland to the 
final 16 after averaging 17 points and 2.79 steals per game and was 
a second-team All-American. Davis, a third-team All-American, 
averaged 15.9 points, 5.1 assists, 3.6 rebounds and 2.52 steals per 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	The tallest player in the early entry list is 7-3 Aleksandr  
Radojevic of Barton County (Kan.) Community College. The only other 
7-footer is 7-1 Josko Poljak, a 21-year-old from Croatia. 
</P>
<P>
	The two high school players are among the tallest, with Bender  
at 6-11 and Smith at 6-10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
