<DOCNO> APW19990521.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 13:37:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Struggles To Maintain Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With no breakthrough in sight on the  
diplomatic or bombing fronts, the Clinton administration and its 
NATO partners struggled Friday to patch up differences over Kosovo 
while portraying Belgrade and its military as cracking after 59 
days of airstrikes. 
</P>
<P>
	In appearances with Secretary of State Madeleine, British  
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said London and Washington are in 
harmony on Kosovo strategy. And he asserted that NATO bombs are 
hitting so hard that ``I don't see any sign that the Yugoslav army 
at the present rate of attrition is going to hold out until August 
or September.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even that time frame is remarkable, considering that many in  
NATO originally believed the air campaign would be over in weeks, 
not months. 
</P>
<P>
	The calendar is influencing NATO leaders' thinking because of  
the lead time required to reach either of two outcomes in Kosovo 
before the typically harsh Balkan winter sets in -- the resettlement 
of ethnic Albanian refugees in Kosovo under a peace agreement, or 
entering Kosovo forcibly to end the conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	Army Gen. Wesley Clark, the top NATO commander, told Defense  
Secretary William Cohen and the military service chiefs in private 
meetings at the Pentagon on Thursday that the time is approaching 
when NATO decisions on ground troops must be made if a resolution 
is to be achieved before winter. 
</P>
<P>
	Kenneth Bacon, Cohen's spokesman, said Clark did not recommend a  
ground invasion or a change in NATO's strategy. He told Cohen, 
however, that because there is no guarantee that the air campaign 
will achieve all of NATO goals by autumn, ``you have to be open to 
the possibility of looking at other options.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bacon also said the Clinton administration wants an enlarged  
NATO peacekeeping force to assemble in Macedonia, on the border 
with Kosovo, ``as quickly as possible.'' He said NATO's political 
body, the North Atlantic Council, is likely to discuss a plan early 
next week for a peackeeping force of about 50,000 troops. The 
United States is likely to contribute 7,000 to 8,000 troops, 
officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	Bacon said the U.S. part of the peacekeeping force could include  
the 26th Marine Expeditionary Unit that is now afloat in the 
Adriatic with about 2,000 troops equipped with a variety of arms 
and aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO has all but ruled out a ground invasion, but it is moving  
ahead with a revised plan for a peacekeeping force that would 
secure the return of the ethnic Albanians and implement a peace 
agreement. The question bedeviling NATO now is, what if there is no 
peace deal. Can the alliance sustain an air campaign indefinitely? 
Should it plan on sending a ground force into Kosovo in late summer 
or early fall on the assumption that by then the Serb troops would 
be so battered they could not resist? 
</P>
<P>
	To that last question, Britain says yes. The Clinton  
administration says no. 
</P>
<P>
	And German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder this week restated his  
strong opposition to sending any NATO ground troops into Kosovo 
until a peace agreement is reached. 
</P>
<P>
	At NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, and in Washington on  
Friday, officials sought to portray Belgrade as on the verge of 
defeat, even though President Slobodan Milosevic has shown few 
signs of giving up. 
</P>
<P>
	``Milosevic is up against the ropes, he's in the corner, and  
that's where he's going to be kept by NATO until such time as he 
throws in the towel.'' NATO spokesman Jamie Shea told reporters in 
Brussels. 
</P>
<P>
	Cook, speaking to reporters at the British ambassador's  
residence in Washington, described Milosevic as stubborn but 
surprised that NATO has managed to keep up the airstrikes without 
unraveling. 
</P>
<P>
	In a briefing for reporters at the Pentagon, Bacon said the  
Kosovo Liberation Army is gaining strength even as the Serb forces 
are weakening. He said the KLA now has between 17,000 and 20,000 
troops, including about 15,000 in Kosovo -- more than twice as many 
as when the NATO bombing began March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Bacon said the KLA is now better trained, better equipped and  
better led than when the war began. 
</P>
<P>
	In other developments:  
</P>
<P>
	-- President Clinton signed an emergency spending measure that  
includes $12 billion for Kosovo-related operations, including 
humanitarian relief for refugees, aid to Macedonia and the other 
``front line'' states that are accepting hundreds of thousands of 
refugees, as well as funds for other U.S. military forces. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The Pentagon announced that 1,022 members of the Air National  
Guard and Air Force Reserve are being ordered to active duty for 
the Kosovo conflict. They, plus 26 KC-135 air refueling planes, are 
from units in Illinois, Kansas, Maine and New Jersey. It brings to 
about 5,000 the number of reservists activated so far. 
</P>
<P>
	-- State Department spokesman James Rubin said Milosevic is  
trying to manipulate a United Nations mission that is in Kosovo to 
assess humanitarian needs. ``It is essential that the United 
Nations not allow itself to be forced into cooperating with his 
agenda to use the U.N. humanitarian mission to generate favorable 
propaganda while denying it access to some of the most needy in the 
region,'' Rubin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 10:41:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FDA Approves New Painkiller Vioxx </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government has approved a new painkiller  
that could provide stiff competition to one of the nation's 
best-selling drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Approval of Merck &AMP; Co.'s Vioxx was announced Friday, and the  
company said the drug should be in pharmacies by mid-June. 
</P>
<P>
	The Food and Drug Administration said it approved Vioxx for  
people with osteoarthritis, for women with menstrual pain and for 
adults with other acute pain. 
</P>
<P>
	The dosage is once a day, and the cost of the prescription  
medication is expected to be between $2.38 and $2.52 per tablet. It 
will also be available in liquid form. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tests on acute pain, Merck officials said the drug was  
tested and worked well on patients following extraction of wisdom 
teeth, people who had had hip or knee replacements and women who 
suffered severe menstrual pain. 
</P>
<P>
	Vioxx is a type of drug known as a Cox-2 inhibitor and is the  
second such drug on the market. The other, Monsanto's Celebrex, 
went on sale late last year for arthritis sufferers, and more than 
two million prescription were written in the first three months of 
sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Advisers to the FDA recommended approval of Vioxx last month.  
</P>
<P>
	Cox-2 inhibitors are a new type of drug that relieves aches and  
inflammation with fewer stomach-damaging side effects. 
</P>
<P>
	Millions of people depend on aspirin, ibuprofen, naproxen and  
other pills called ``non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs,'' or 
NSAIDs, to relieve pain. 
</P>
<P>
	But NSAIDs can cause ulcers, stomach bleeding and other  
gastrointestinal side effects, especially in long-term users. They 
are blamed for causing 107,000 hospitalizations every year, and for 
killing 16,500 people. 
</P>
<P>
	NSAIDS target an enzyme called cyclo-oxegenase, which is  
responsible for much inflammation. But there are two types of this 
enzyme. Cox-2 is believed to cause inflammation, while Cox-1 
protects the stomach lining. NSAIDs attack both. 
</P>
<P>
	So scientists developed more specific drugs to target just  
Cox-2. 
</P>
<P>
	While Vioxx is the second Cox-2 inhibitor on the market it could  
prove to be a formidable competitor, especially since it was 
approved for more uses than Celebrex. 
</P>
<P>
	Vioxx will include a label note that there were rare instances  
of gastrointestinal bleeding among users during trials and urging 
physicians to watch for that possibility. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
