<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Seattle's Griffey Still Having Fun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Kirby Puckett is Ken Griffey Jr.'s favorite  
player. And not just for what Puckett did on the field. 
</P>
<P>
	The Seattle Mariners slugger remembers how Puckett became his  
mentor when he got to the majors. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I first came into the league, he treated me like I was  
somebody and not a rookie,'' Griffey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Puckett, a former star for the Minnesota Twins, now is an  
executive vice president with the team. When the Mariners are in 
Minneapolis on Monday, Griffey will go to Puckett's office to see 
his friend. 
</P>
<P>
	Back in 1989, when Griffey was a rookie, Puckett offered some  
sage advice. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said, `Smile and do what you've got to do,''' Griffey said.  
```Just play hard and have some fun.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Eleven seasons later, the charismatic Griffey is still smiling  
and having fun. He's one of the most popular players in the game 
and perhaps the best. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, it's easy to have fun when you've got 366 career  
homers, including consecutive 56-homer seasons in 1997 and 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Still believed to be approaching the prime of his career,  
Griffey is an American League MVP, a three-time AL home run 
champion, a nine-time All-Star and a nine-time Gold Glove center 
fielder. He's led the majors in voting for the All-Star game the 
past three seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	With 16 homers in 39 games this year, Griffey is off to a fast  
start, sharing the major league home run lead with Tampa Bay's Jose 
Canseco. He has homered in five of his last six games, and he has 
hit in nine consecutive games. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey isn't taking anything for granted. He saw what happened  
to Puckett. 
</P>
<P>
	Puckett led the Twins to World Series titles in 1987 and 1991,  
before being forced into early retirement in 1996 when an early 
form of glaucoma left him blind in his right eye. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey remembers Puckett's message fondly.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was towards the end of my rookie season and we were playing  
Minnesota and I didn't run out a ground ball,'' Griffey said. ``He 
said, `Show a little more effort. You ain't got to run under four 
seconds, but just do a little more. And smile.' That always 
stuck.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another baseball elder Griffey listens to is Chili Davis of the  
New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	``He always gives me calls during the season when I've done  
something wrong and when I've done something right,'' Griffey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there's the late Jackie Robinson. Griffey appreciates  
everything Robinson did for today's black players. 
</P>
<P>
	``He did everything you ask somebody to do and more,'' Griffey  
said. ``He endured the name-calling, the dirty play. If you're the 
only one, it's always hard. He's the one who did it for all of 
us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Mariners have another star in Alex Rodriguez, a three-time  
All-Star shortstop. Last season, Rodriguez joined Canseco and Barry 
Bonds in the majors' 40-40 club with 42 homers and 46 stolen bases. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey enjoys watching young players develop into stars. He  
knows Rodriguez is a special talent. Rodriguez is good enough to 
play anywhere on the field, Griffey says. 
</P>
<P>
	``Look at our shortstop,'' he said. ``He could play second base  
if he wanted. Third base. First base. The outfield positions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It doesn't matter if a player isn't a center fielder like  
Griffey. If he's got talent, Griffey likes him. He particularly 
enjoys watching Boston shortstop Nomar Garciaparra and Red Sox 
right-hander Pedro Martinez, who he thinks might be the best 
pitcher in the game today. 
</P>
<P>
	Not that he enjoys hitting against Martinez.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's the one guy who's going to come after you,'' Griffey  
said. ``He's a skinny kid who gives you everything he's got.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Added Griffey with a smile: ``I don't like pitchers.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
