<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Mixed; Dow Down 37.46 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices were mixed in a listless session  
today as investors, worried about the effect rising interest rates 
could have on big-name stocks, moved their money into small-cap 
issues. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average finished 37.46 lower at  
10,829.28, closing out an unusually quiet week on Wall Street with 
a loss of 84.04, or 0.77 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``This week has been interesting,'' said Brian Belski, chief  
investment strategist at George K. Baum &AMP; Co. in Kansas City, Mo. 
``There's been no volume, but many of the internal factors are 
fairly positive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, even as most indexes ended lower Friday, the New York  
Stock Exchange had six stocks rise for every five that fell. On the 
Nasdaq Stock Market, the ratio of advancers to decliners was 
roughly even. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq composite index fell 22.09 to 2,520.14, and the  
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was off 8.54 at 1,330.29. 
</P>
<P>
	Some prominent technology stocks fell, including Dow component  
IBM, which tumbled 2 1/2 to 230 3/8. Nasdaq's most actively traded stocks 
were a trio of high-profile computer companies: Dell, Microsoft and 
Intel all declined, with Dell slipping 15/16 to 37 5/16, Microsoft 
falling 7/8 to 77 9/16 and Intel losing 11/16 to close at 57. 
</P>
<P>
	Tony Cecin, director of institutional trading at Piper Jaffray  
in Minneapolis, said investors appeared to be edging away from the 
biggest names, seeking value in smaller companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of the money coming out of the large-cap stocks is just  
looking for a new home,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Market players continued to ponder the impact of potentially  
higher interest rates. Analysts said the low volume and modest 
shifts on Wall Street this week were due largely to the Federal 
Reserve's warning Tuesday that it may raise interest rates if 
further signs of inflation appear in the coming months. 
</P>
<P>
	Higher interest rates can crimp corporate profits as borrowing  
costs rise. Analysts say that with many stocks near record levels, 
investors may feel that large-cap stocks are simply too expensive 
if their profits start to wane. 
</P>
<P>
	There was little fresh news to affect the overall market.  
Cosmetics maker Revlon, a frequent topic of takeover speculation, 
rose 1 1/4 to 30 1/2 amid rumors it will be acquired by Coty, a fragrance 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Pharmaceutical maker Merck, counting on a boost after the Food  
and Drug Administration approved its new pain pill Vioxx, instead 
saw its shares fall 15/16 to 71 5/16. Analysts said Merck simply 
mirrored the drug sector, where most companies fell much more 
steeply. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Dow component General Motors rose 3 3/16 to 83 5/16,  
following the lead of Delphi Automotive, the auto parts unit GM 
spun off. Delphi shares rose 13/16 to 21 5/16 in heavy trading 
after Standard &AMP; Poor's said it would add the stock to its S&AMP;P 500 
index. 
</P>
<P>
	Eastman Kodak fell 2 9/16 to 73 after an analyst said it will  
keep losing market share to Fuji Photo Film Co. 
</P>
<P>
	With all the shifting fortunes of blue-chip companies, analysts  
were reluctant to draw many conclusions. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are questioning what to do with some of these premier  
leaders,'' Belski said. ``There's a lot of indecision and a lack of 
investor commitment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Friday was a ``double witching'' day, when the expiration of  
stock and index options forces traders to adjust their portfolios. 
Yet volume remained low on the NYSE. Consolidated volume totaled 
836.41 million shares, compared to 905.9 million in the previous 
session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 2.55 to 636.87, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 3.34 to 795.37. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 1.12 to 449.14,  
its fourth straight gain. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.06 percent.  
Germany's DAX index rose 0.2 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 slipped 
0.2 percent, and France's CAC-40 closed 0.5 percent lower. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
