<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Black Newspaper Finds Backer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The Chicago Defender -- a leading voice for black  
Americans through segregation and the civil rights era -- has found 
an investor who is expected to bring financial stability to the 
94-year-old newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Defender has suffered in recent years, but I think we have  
an opportunity to get back on track,'' Robert Sengstacke, 
great-nephew of the newspaper's founder, said Friday. ``There are 
reasons why the Defender is 94 years old, why it has survived; it 
still provides a service to this community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit businessman Don Barden announced an agreement in  
principle Thursday with Sengstacke Enterprises Inc., which 
publishes the Defender and three other black-oriented newspapers. 
Terms of the deal were not released. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to being a fixture in Chicago since 1905, the  
Defender was read by thousands in the South, where it was 
distributed by Pullman porters and sold by newsboys who risked 
being lynched for their actions. 
</P>
<P>
	The early Defender inflamed southern whites by encouraging  
blacks to leave the Jim Crow laws and cotton fields of the South to 
take jobs in northern factories. It also became home to black 
writers ignored by the white press, including Langston Hughes and 
W.E.B. DuBois. At its peak in the 1930s, the Defender had a 
circulation of 300,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The Defender's future was put up for grabs after John  
Sengstacke, nephew of the paper's founder Robert Abbott, died in 
1997 at 84. In 1975, he placed Sengstacke Enterprises Inc. in trust 
with instructions that it be sold upon his death; his heirs had no 
say in the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	Some feared Northern Trust Co., Sengstacke's trustee, would sell  
the newspaper and its sister papers -- the Michigan Chronicle, the 
Pittsburgh Courier and the Memphis Tri-State Defender -- without 
concern for their activist history. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, activists in the African-American community hope the  
arrangement with Barden will help the Defender stay true to its 
crusading heritage. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Defender is the only daily newspaper that tells our  
story,'' said the Rev. Al Sampson, who heads the Citizens Committee 
to Save the Chicago Defender. ``It has told our story throughout 
the black liberation movement, and we need it to keep telling that 
story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barden -- who owns the Majestic Star riverboat casino in Gary,  
Ind., five Illinois radio stations and other businesses -- said his 
goal was to maintain the company legacy as well as provide growth. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will work cooperatively to grow this medium in its existing  
and new community markets, provide all news and information needed 
and desired and work with the family of employees who have served 
this vision for so long,'' Barden said in a statement. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
