<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBC's Ventura Story Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL (AP) -- Among all the laughable inaccuracies in ``The  
Jesse Ventura Story'' airing Sunday on NBC, one jumps out. 
</P>
<P>
	Gubernatorial candidate Ventura is on the campaign trail,  
discussing why the state ought to regulate prostitution rather than 
ban it. 
</P>
<P>
	As he's getting in his car, he turns to the reporter and says,  
``Thanks a lot for your time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This never happened, and as any reporter who covers Ventura  
knows, it's not likely to ever happen. The real Ventura spends more 
time joking about running over reporters than thanking them. 
</P>
<P>
	And that's just the beginning. NBC is stretching when it says  
the account scheduled to air Sunday is ``based on the true story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But inaccuracies aren't the worst part of the movie.  
</P>
<P>
	At the end of it, the Ventura character turns to the camera as  
he's entering the Capitol and says, ``I can promise you this: It's 
not going to be boring.'' It sure isn't, in real life. 
</P>
<P>
	But the movie turns a bona fide character -- Ventura himself --  
into Casper Milquetoast. It's not only untrue to the events of last 
fall's gubernatorial campaign, it's dull -- something the real 
Ventura never is. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ventura story is a great one. The former bad-boy  
professional wrestler known as ``The Body'' runs for governor and 
scores a shock victory over the son of a state Democratic political 
legend and a Republican rising star. 
</P>
<P>
	On a shoestring campaign with few staff, Ventura built support  
by sheer force of personality. The movie doesn't show any of the 
street energy of the campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the character works out of a snazzy, well-staffed  
campaign office, something the real Ventura didn't have. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ventura campaign picked up steam when he ran some creative,  
funny ads featuring himself singing a revised version of the 
``Theme From Shaft'' and doing television commercials with his 
action figure fighting off Evil Special Interest Man. The movie 
substituted variations that failed to match the wit of the original 
commercials. 
</P>
<P>
	The movie Ventura walks door-to-door delivering campaign  
pamphlets. The real Ventura didn't do that; supporters literally 
followed him -- at fairs and across the state either in their cars 
or on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Nils Allen Stewart plays Ventura but conveys neither the  
governor's rough charm nor his distinctive voice. Stewart puts all 
the attitude of a commercial voice-over into his accompanying 
narration. 
</P>
<P>
	The real Ventura has star power. This guy doesn't.  
</P>
<P>
	The movie traces Ventura from his youth in south Minneapolis to  
his election night victory. The script conveys few of Ventura's 
numerous grammatical quirks. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the character says things you would never expect to  
hear from Ventura, such as ``I had an epiphany'' or ``I didn't know 
it, but what I was looking for was back home in Minnesota.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota viewers also may cringe at the skewed portrayals of  
Ventura's opponents in the election. 
</P>
<P>
	In the movie, GOP St. Paul Mayor Norm Coleman and former  
Attorney General Hubert Humphrey III are indistinguishable. In real 
life, Coleman is much taller than Humphrey and is a native New 
Yorker who speaks with a Brooklyn accent. 
</P>
<P>
	Humphrey is a native Minnesotan and the son of former Vice  
President Hubert Humphrey. The movie Humphrey lives in a gated 
palace; the real Humphrey lives in a modest suburban house. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura himself had nothing to do with the movie and says he  
won't watch it. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither should anyone who wants to understand how Ventura rocked  
the political establishment, because what you see in the movie 
isn't what Minnesota voters saw last fall. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Editors: Rochelle Olson covers politics in Minnesota.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ....  
</P>
<P>
	BRIAN'S SONG: ``Brian Wilson: A Beach Boy's Tale'' examines the  
talent and troubles of the pop wizard. The two-hour film, airing 8 
p.m. EDT Sunday on the Biography channel, includes interviews with 
Wilson, his family and friends, rare film footage and concert 
performances. Among those who weigh in: daughters Carnie and Wendy 
Wilson; Glen Campbell, and Beach Boys Bruce Johnston and Alan 
Jardine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
