<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mircosoft Unveiling New Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. revealed a new defense  
strategy today for its antitrust trial, suggesting future 
high-speed Internet connections for consumers will undermine the 
government's case by threatening to reduce the industry's reliance 
on Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	The insights into Microsoft's new courtroom defense came during  
testimony from Steve Case, the chairman of America Online Inc., who 
was questioned for three hours under oath at a downtown hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial judge previously agreed to allow Microsoft to ask Case  
about AOL's nearly $10 billion purchase earlier this year of 
Netscape Communications Corp., the Internet software pioneer that 
saw its business crumble after Microsoft started giving away its 
own Web browser free with the Windows operating system. 
</P>
<P>
	Case argued that Netscape's ``Netcenter'' Web site -- among the  
most popular on the Internet -- attracted AOL more than its browser 
software, which he acknowledged has suffered a ``significant 
decline'' in popularity. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did not buy Netscape because of the browser business,''  
Case said. ``We bought Netscape in some ways despite the browser 
business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Microsoft focused as much Friday on AOL's purchase as on  
future high-speed Internet access -- connecting home computers and 
other devices over cable TV or new digital telephone lines or even 
using satellite transmissions. 
</P>
<P>
	Those questions appeared to puzzle Case, who has taken an  
unusually high-profile role in recent weeks lobbying Congress and 
federal regulators to force the nation's cable companies to allow 
their subscribers to use his AOL software with cable companies' 
ultra-fast data pipelines. 
</P>
<P>
	``Am I in the right room?'' Case asked at one point.  
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft lawyer John Warden pressed Case on whether high-speed  
Internet connections will allow consumers to use software that 
isn't installed with Windows on their personal computers but housed 
instead on powerful machines elsewhere and ``served up'' to 
customers across data lines. 
</P>
<P>
	``As more people are connecting to high-speed networks, they  
will be able to do more useful things,'' Case agreed cautiously. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft's sudden emphasis on these high-speed connections and  
their implications is meant to undercut some elements of the 
government's antitrust case -- namely, that its Windows operating 
system is so dominant that no one in the industry can compete with 
its success. 
</P>
<P>
	Software that is used in such ways across high-speed networks  
can typically be used with whatever operating system a consumer has 
on their computer. Microsoft argues that, in effect, the Internet 
itself becomes a competing software platform, threatening to make 
Windows less important. 
</P>
<P>
	Those fears were illustrated by Microsoft's $5 billion  
investment in AT&AMP;T earlier this month, ensuring that AT&AMP;T will use 
Windows software in millions of cable TV boxes providing high-speed 
Internet connections. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft also argues that this ability to run programs across a  
network can ease the reluctance of programmers to write software 
for operating systems other than Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has accused Microsoft of exploiting a particular  
antitrust theory known as the ``applications barrier to entry.'' 
This reasons that potential rivals are discouraged from creating 
other operating systems because they can't persuade programmers to 
write useful applications for them. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft also contends that fast Internet connections  
eventually will allow consumers to easily retrieve even large 
software programs from remote locations, which could contradict 
government charges that Netscape was prevented from being able to 
adequately distribute its rival browser software. 
</P>
<P>
	The government on Friday did not appear interested in the  
high-speed Internet access question. During much of Warden's 
questioning, Justice Department lawyer David Boies rubbed his chin 
and glanced toward the ceiling, sometimes casually taking notes on 
a legal pad. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a sideshow, an effort to detract from what the  
real issues are,'' Boies said afterward. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
