<DOCNO> APW19990521.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 17:05:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Helicopter Rescues McKinley Climbers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- Two exhausted, frostbitten British  
mountain climbers who got trapped on Mount McKinley in a fierce 
blizzard were rescued Friday by a high-altitude helicopter. 
</P>
<P>
	Rescuers were trying to get to a third climber late Friday  
afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Nigel Vardy and Antony Hollinshead, plucked off the mountain  
just after midnight, were hospitalized with frostbite after getting 
300 feet from the mountain summit. Both said they were disappointed 
at not reaching the top, but said the weather worked against them. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were a gnat's whisker away, but it was a combination of a  
lot of things. It would have been a worse situation if we had 
continued on,'' Hollinshead said. 
</P>
<P>
	The three climbers tried to reach the top of North America's  
highest peak Wednesday, but a blizzard forced to wait as they 
battled hypothermia. 
</P>
<P>
	They decided to head down a day later. Vardy, nearly blinded by  
frostbite, stumbled, which sent him and his roped-together 
companions, Hollinshead and Steve Ball, on a 300-foot tumble. 
</P>
<P>
	In better shape than the other two, Ball, 42, descended to a  
ranger camp for help Thursday. Authorities did no know where he was 
until Friday afternoon. They reported that he was hypothermic, had 
a fractured leg and was dehydrated. 
</P>
<P>
	Vardy, 29, and Hollinshead, 33, badly frostbitten and exhausted,  
were rescued early Friday in a daring high-altitude helicopter 
rescue. 
</P>
<P>
	Their McKinley climb ended at about midnight, and after  
communicating with park rangers for hours through a radio with 
ever-weakening batteries, a break in the weather allowed a 
high-altitude helicopter pilot to make a dash for the men. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilot dropped a bag with a radio, fluids and two ``screamer  
suits,'' insulated suits specifically designed to protect them from 
the 50 mph winds and temperatures 30 below zero. 
</P>
<P>
	Dangling from a helicopter cable, the climbers were taken on a  
10-minute flight to the 72,00-foot base camp and later on to the 
hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Vardy was hospitalized in serious condition with severe  
frostbite. His nose and cheek were blackened from the damage, and 
white gloves covered his hands. He also was alert and in good 
spirits. 
</P>
<P>
	The team had the right equipment, and all three climbers had  
reach the tops of peaks higher than McKinley, Vardy said. But the 
ferocious weather and the tantalizing proximity of the summit 
conspired against them. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you climb 4,000 feet in a day, you don't want to come  
down,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hollinshead, also frostbitten and with an injured shoulder, was  
in fair condition. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did everything technically right, but we just left too big  
a chunk for the summit day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rescue was similar to one last summer in which two other  
British climbers were flown beneath the helicopter to a base camp. 
Two British military climbers were about 300 feet lower when they 
were rescued in June. 
</P>
<P>
	About 350 climbers now are on Mount McKinley. Ten people have  
reached the summit so far this spring, Park Service spokeswoman 
Jane Tranel said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 06:35:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Refugees on Both Coasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Kosovo refugees can be found from coast to coast  
as they settle in with friends, relatives and host families anxious 
to help them forget about their war-torn homeland. 
</P>
<P>
	Refugees arrived Thursday in Seattle and Los Angeles. The  
arrival of a seven-member family at Seattle-Tacoma International 
Airport marked the latest leg in an odyssey that began when Serbian 
police drove them from their home in Gjilan, about 40 miles from 
the Kosovo capital, Pristina. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thank the American government that took the initiative to  
save us from the bloody hands of the Serb regime, to save my family 
and children,'' Xhavit Korqa, the father, said through an 
interpreter. 
</P>
<P>
	The Korqas walked for two days through the mountains before  
reaching Macedonia, where they had to wait for a week at the 
border. The family spent a month at a border camp in Macedonia, 
then two weeks at Fort Dix in New Jersey before heading for 
Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	With Korqa came his wife and children -- three girls and two  
boys, ages 6 to 16. World Relief, the refugee resettlement arm of 
the National Association of Evangelicals, is sponsoring the family 
in Seattle. 
</P>
<P>
	Korqa said the first thing he wants his children to do is to go  
to school and learn English. The first thing the 45-year-old 
mechanic and bus driver wants to do is find work. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very encouraging,'' said host family member Bruce  
Kennedy, after the Korqas sat through a news conference. ``This 
means they won't have time on their hands as they have had for the 
last few months.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Korqa and his family have full refugee status, meaning they will  
be able to apply for permanent residence in the United States and 
eventually apply for green cards. 
</P>
<P>
	But Korqa said they hoped to return home ``as soon as peace  
returns to Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NATO launched air strikes against Yugoslavia on March 24 after  
President Slobodan Milosevic rejected a plan to end the fighting 
with the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army. Hundreds of thousands of 
ethnic Albanians have fled to neighboring countries. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States has agreed to accept up to 20,000 refugees.  
</P>
<P>
	More than 3,000 refugees have been flown to Fort Dix this month,  
where they are processed for relocation throughout the United 
States. At the post, Mirsade Bejiqi was saying good-bye Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	She arrived with her parents and three brothers here with the  
first planeload of refugees on May 5. The 20-year-old college 
student had to say good-bye again Thursday as her family headed to 
Boise, Idaho. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what to say. I'm too sad,'' Bejiqi sobbed. ``How  
many times do I have to say good-bye to my friends?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Arlinda Gashi, 19, stood behind a fence and cried as she watched  
her friend talk to reporters. They exchanged a tearful farewell 
before Bejiqi boarded a bus for Newark International Airport. 
</P>
<P>
	In Los Angeles, 28 ethnic Albanian refugees -- all members of the  
Vlashi family -- arrived to stay with host families. They were 
greeted by Hajrush Vlashi and his wife, Renee. The couple worked 
with the Jewish Federation to bring family members to the United 
States from Macedonia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm in shock,'' Mrs. Vlashi said by telephone from Los Angeles  
International Airport. ``They were very, very happy to see my 
husband.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The refugees will receive one month of cash assistance, which  
averages about $300 a person, and three months of services. The 
hosts have been asked to house families for as long as two weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
