<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 13:42:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soybean Oil Tested As Motor Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Researchers say they've developed an  
alternative use for soybeans -- as a motor oil. 
</P>
<P>
	A month-long road test ended Friday in Washington.  
</P>
<P>
	Researchers from Agro Management Group Inc., of Colorado  
Springs, Colo., who developed and patented the product, drove two 
trucks on an 18-day tour through 18 states. One was lubricated with 
conventional motor oil, the other with the new soybean oil. 
</P>
<P>
	The two materials performed equally, researchers said.  
</P>
<P>
	The new product, made from soybean, canola and other vegetable  
oils, operates in the same way as conventional motor oil but is 
biodegradable, nontoxic and produces fewer harmful emissions, 
researchers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whenever you drain the oil pan (now), there's always a concern  
about what you do with the oil, because it is a toxic substance,'' 
said Byron Lemoine of the United Soybean Board. ``This is not 
toxic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dollars from soybean farmers helped pay for the research  
project. 
</P>
<P>
	Motorists shouldn't expect to see the product at their local  
auto shops soon. The product will initially be offered only for 
commercial fleets in Michigan and already is being used in U.S. 
Postal Service vehicles in Grand Rapids, Mich. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 03:45:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SI's Indy Credentials Reinstated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Reversing course, Indianapolis 500 race  
officials have reinstated the credentials of a Sports Illustrated 
writer barred because the magazine ran a critical article and photo 
of fans killed at a recent race. 
</P>
<P>
	Tony George, president of the Indianapolis Motor Speedway, said  
SI's senior auto racing writer, Ed Hinton, can cover the May 30 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's quite welcome to come, but I find it distasteful to have  
to offer him a credential,'' George said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The speedway relented after a boycott of the race by other news  
organizations began to take shape. 
</P>
<P>
	Race officials were upset by a photo and an article that  
appeared in the magazine after three fans were killed May 1 at a 
race in Concord, N.C. Hinton wrote in the article, titled ``Fatal 
Attractions,'' that such accidents could be avoided. 
</P>
<P>
	The photograph, taken by The Associated Press, showed one victim  
lying on blood-covered grandstand steps with a leg protruding from 
beneath a sheet and another sheet-covered body. 
</P>
<P>
	Mai Lindstrom, a spokeswoman for the Indy Racing League, which  
is headed by George, said that some of the AP photos were ``very 
graphic,'' and ``to our knowledge, SI was the only publication that 
chose to print one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Horton, AP senior photo editor for sports, said photo  
editors were sensitive to the graphic nature of the photographs and 
edited them carefully. He said there had been no complaints from AP 
member newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
	The speedway at first offered press credentials for a Sports  
Illustrated writer other than Hinton, but the magazine declined. 
</P>
<P>
	In protest, the Chicago Tribune said earlier this week it  
wouldn't cover the race, and the Los Angeles Times also said it was 
considering a boycott. After the speedway backed down, the Tribune 
said it would cover the Indy 500. 
</P>
<P>
	Sports Illustrated said Hinton would cover the race but was  
upset by George's criticism. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're glad it's been resolved. We wish it hadn't come to  
this,'' said SI spokesman Joe Assad. 
</P>
<P>
	Hinton said he was astounded at George's comments.  
</P>
<P>
	``I thought they were at least putting it under the guise of a  
professional dispute,'' he said. ``What I've heard sounds so absurd 
and so irrational I don't know what to make of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Indy 500, which began in 1911 as ``the greatest spectacle in  
motor racing,'' has lost its prestige in the last three years. Star 
drivers like Michael Andretti and Al Unser Jr. no longer compete 
there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
