<DOCNO> APW19990521.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 02:51:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nebraska OKs Execution Moratorium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- The Nebraska Legislature has become the  
first in the nation to approve a moratorium on executions, a step 
that surprised some in a state where residents consistently say 
they support capital punishment. 
</P>
<P>
	The one-house, officially nonpartisan Legislature voted 27-21 on  
Thursday to send the measure to Gov. Mike Johanns. 
</P>
<P>
	The first-term Republican supports capital punishment and  
opposes the moratorium but did not say whether he will sign or veto 
the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would put a two-year moratorium on executions while a  
study is done to see if the death penalty is being applied fairly. 
Death sentences still could be given, but no executions would take 
place. 
</P>
<P>
	Sens. Ernie Chambers and Kermit Brashear pushed the bill through  
three rounds of debate. Chambers, an outspoken independent, has 
proposed abolishing the death penalty nearly every year since his 
election in 1970, but Brashear's support surprised even statehouse 
insiders. 
</P>
<P>
	A former Republican candidate for governor and longtime  
supporter of capital punishment, Brashear is the conservative 
chairman of the Legislature's Judiciary Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	While many as 80 percent of Nebraska's registered voters have  
indicated support for the death penalty in public opinion polls, 
Brashear said he believes most Nebraskans will support the 
moratorium during the study. 
</P>
<P>
	Brashear said state law requires the death penalty be applied  
fairly and uniformly, but many of the 155 murderers serving life 
sentences committed crimes just as heinous as those of the 10 men 
now on Nebraska's death row. 
</P>
<P>
	Other states have considered moratoriums but have not adopted  
legislation, according to the Death Penalty Information Center, a 
Washington-based group critical of how capital punishment is 
applied. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida officials stopped executions for a year after a fire  
started during a 1997 electrocution. The Illinois House recently 
passed a resolution urging the governor to impose a six-month 
moratorium. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Bar Association and the National Conference of  
Catholic Bishops have called for such moratoriums. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 07:32:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A Brief Look at Gun Control Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Senate juvenile justice bill would:  
</P>
<P>
	--Make it easier for prosecutors to charge juveniles as young as  
14 with violent crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	--Require background checks on all firearms transactions at gun  
shows and pawn shops. 
</P>
<P>
	--Revoke the right to gun ownership for anyone convicted of a gun  
crime as a juvenile. 
</P>
<P>
	--Require gun safety devices to be sold with all handguns.  
</P>
<P>
	--Limit the liability of gun owners who use the gun lock when the  
firearm is stolen and used to commit a crime. 
</P>
<P>
	--Set up a grant program of $50 million a year for state juvenile  
court judges, juvenile prosecutors, juvenile public defenders and 
other juvenile court system personnel to reduce court backlogs and 
recidivism. 
</P>
<P>
	--Provide for a study of the effects of television programming,  
movies, video games, Internet content and music lyrics on child 
development. 
</P>
<P>
	--Provide for a study of the marketing practices of the firearms  
industry with respect to children. 
</P>
<P>
	--Make Internet screening software more cheaply available.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
