<DOCNO> APW19990521.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 02:12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Shooting at Another American School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- The first bell hadn't sounded yet and the  
students in the commons area at Heritage High School were gabbing 
and munching on cinnamon rolls. It was the last day of class for 
the seniors. 
</P>
<P>
	Suddenly came a loud, startling ``pop,'' then another, another  
and still another. Some figured it was a prank -- maybe firecrackers 
-- until they heard shouts of ``he's got a gun!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then came the panic, screams, tears -- and blood.  
</P>
<P>
	On the day Heritage High seniors were looking forward to picking  
up their yearbooks, their suburban community became the new focus 
for a nation on edge after months of fear and concern about 
violence in America's schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Six students were wounded in Thursday morning's attack, none  
critically. Prosecutor Richard Read said the boy who suddenly 
attacked his classmates was carrying a .22-caliber rifle and 
.22-caliber revolver. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspect, a 15-year-old sophomore friends said was upset over  
a failed romance, dropped to his knees, pulled the gun away from 
his mouth and, witnesses said, surrendered with a tearful: ``Oh my 
God, I'm so scared!'' 
</P>
<P>
	The gunman was identified by friends as Thomas Solomon. He was  
charged with aggravated assault and other charges were being 
considered. Solomon must appear in juvenile court before he can be 
charged as an adult, something not expected before Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Classes were canceled for today, though students were expected  
to return to Heritage High on Monday. School officials said 
graduation would go on as scheduled May 28. 
</P>
<P>
	The attack was the seventh at an American high school or middle  
school since October 1997. President Clinton received word of 
Thursday's shooting before he left for Littleton, Colo., for the 
one-month anniversary of the deaths of 15 people at Columbine High 
School. 
</P>
<P>
	The news ``is deeply troubling to me, as it is to all  
Americans,'' Clinton said. As he spoke, the U.S. Senate was 
approving a proposal requiring background checks for all 
transactions at gun shows and for anyone seeking to reclaim a 
weapon at a pawn shop. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Heritage High Class of '99 was left with these  
indelible mental snapshots: 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of teens, screaming, crying, jamming through doors to  
escape. Some yanking up fallen friends, others jumping over them. 
</P>
<P>
	A girl, lying on the floor, screaming ``I'm shot!'' and begging  
for her mother. Another moaning after banging her head diving under 
a table. 
</P>
<P>
	A teacher shepherding students into a closet, and calming them  
by quoting from the Book of Psalms. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside, helicopters, sirens, milling knots of dazed students,  
panicked parents searching the groups and tearful, hugging 
reunions. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of these same students and parents had watched television  
coverage of the Littleton shooting a month ago. That horror lasted 
for hours; the assault here was over in minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``You, like, watch it on TV and it's not your school and it's  
not like this,'' said Scottie Sanders, an 11th-grader struggling to 
reconstruct the morning's events. ``It was like a blur.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Heritage, 20 miles east of Atlanta, is a mostly white, suburban  
school, like Columbine High. About 80 percent of graduates go on to 
college. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before the massacre in Colorado, Heritage had video  
surveillance cameras in the hallways and an armed sheriff's deputy 
on duty during school hours. The deputy didn't exchange fire with 
the gunman, and it was unclear where he was during the shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Dunn, a sophomore, said he had seen ``lots of guns'' at  
the suspect's home. Solomon was described as quiet, and several 
students said his grades had slipped lately and he had been heard 
making ambiguous comments about shooting someone. One said he 
didn't take Solomon seriously. 
</P>
<P>
	A day earlier, someone had brought in a paper bag filled with  
crickets and left them to hop out across Heritage High. There were 
rumors that a possum or another critter would be turned loose 
Thursday, and firecrackers had been lit as classes came to a close 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I walked into the commons area and heard the pops,'' said  
Michael Mellitto, an 18-year-old junior. ``I thought, `Ha, ha, very 
funny!' Then these girls come running past me, crying, saying, `I 
can't believe they shot him!' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Nathaniel Deeter, 15, a friend of the gunman, said Solomon was  
depressed after a girlfriend broke off their relationship this 
week. He was there as the attack began. 
</P>
<P>
	``I yelled to him, `Hey, what're you doing?' But he just kept  
shooting. And then the kid next to me got shot in the foot. Then I 
started to run,'' Deeter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Seventeen-year-old Drake Hoy tried to run, too, but realized  
something was wrong with his foot: ``I took off my boot and there 
was blood and stuff everywhere.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses said the gunman was running and shooting at no one in  
particular, firing at students below the waist. 
</P>
<P>
	``People were falling on the floor, a lot of screaming, people  
trying to help each other,'' said Joel Thomas, 14. 
</P>
<P>
	Inside a closet, teacher Carol Ingle recited Bible verses to  
calm terrified students she had gathered there. One of them, 
freshman Stephanie Edwards, said: ``She told us it would be all 
right.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 19:41:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Five Dead After Connecticut Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MERIDEN, Conn. (AP) -- Five people were killed when a pickup  
truck slammed head-on Friday night into a car on a Connecticut 
highway. 
</P>
<P>
	The truck was traveling in the northbound lanes of Interstate 91  
when it crossed the median and hit a Volkswagen Beetle, state 
police spokesman Lt. Ralph Carpenter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two men and two women were in the car. Three of the people died  
at the scene and a fourth victim died at a hospital/. The male 
driver of the truck was also killed. 
</P>
<P>
	All of the victims were from Connecticut, police said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 13:42:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kasich To Make Public Contributors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rep. John Kasich will start making public the  
names of his presidential exploratory committee's financial 
backers, a spokesman said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Press Secretary Todd Harris said the Kasich 2000 committee will  
meet Federal Election Commission campaign finance deadlines 
beginning July 15, when forms are due showing how money was raised 
and spent through the end of June. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich, R-Ohio, chairman of the House Budget Committee, has been  
unusual among the better-known presidential hopefuls in that he 
chose not to register his exploratory committee with the FEC; it is 
registered only with the Ohio secretary of state. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris emphasized that the July filing will be voluntary, and  
said the decision to file was made to avoid letting the lack of 
disclosure become a distraction. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have conducted this campaign to the letter of the law and  
when people examine the Kasich campaign we want the focus on John's 
message and what he is saying,'' Harris said. 
</P>
<P>
	No law requires an exploratory committee to register; that's  
required only after a hopeful has decided to become a candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	``Legally, they're probably on solid ground. Politically,  
they're on quicksand,'' Larry Makinson, executive director of the 
Center for Responsive Politics, said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Probably the only reason this hasn't been more of an issue is  
he isn't considered a top-tier candidate for president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Makinson's group has been preparing a report comparing the  
various committees' public disclosure performance, and The Columbus 
Dispatch reported in Friday's editions that the report would be 
critical of Kasich. 
</P>
<P>
	Kasich has told reporters he raised $1.3 million during the  
first quarter of 1999, and that he is meeting his fund-raising 
goals. 
</P>
<P>
	The FEC said federal law does not set a time limit or dollar  
limit on hopefuls while they travel, poll and talk to activists in 
the course of deciding whether to run for an office. 
</P>
<P>
	Makinson said Kasich's failure to file disclosure reports to  
date presents questions about the ethics of a person holding an 
important job in Congress maintaining secrecy about the origins of 
a large amount of money. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one in Congress, let alone the chairman of an important  
committee, should have more than a million dollars of phantom 
money,'' Makinson said. ``Maybe (Microsoft Chairman) Bill Gates 
wouldn't be influenced by a million dollars but almost anyone else 
would be.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 02:12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Shooting at Another American School </HEADLINE>
