<DOCNO> APW19990521.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 17:21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stewart Gets Shot at Indy Pole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Larry Curry had a message for driver Tony  
Stewart: ``Tell him to get on that plane and get back here. We've 
got a practice in the morning and we drew No. 2.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, who was in Concord, N.C., to qualify for Saturday  
night's NASCAR Winston Open, has only a small window of time 
earlier Saturday in which to take a shot at the pole for the May 30 
Indianapolis 500. 
</P>
<P>
	Curry, the co-owner of his team, got the first part of the  
equation right, drawing the second spot in the qualifying order for 
Stewart's primary car and No. 17 for his backup. 
</P>
<P>
	Qualifying was scheduled to begin at 11 a.m., but one possible  
glitch in Stewart's plan is a 60 percent chance of rain Saturday 
morning. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's as good as it gets,'' said Curry, who pumped his fist in  
the air after pulling the No. 2 spot. ``That's what we had to do, 
so now we've just got to hope that it doesn't rain. We really don't 
have any leeway. If it rains, it pushes back practice, qualifying 
starts late and we'll have to qualify on Sunday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pole and most of the top spots in the 33-car lineup are  
expected to be filled Saturday, with the rest of the field 
determined in further time trials on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Pole favorite Greg Ray, with no other racing on his schedule  
this weekend, will have to wait until No. 45 -- his backup -- or No. 
58 to make his four-lap, 10-mile qualifying run. 
</P>
<P>
	Two-time race winner Arie Luyendyk, also one of the favorites on  
Saturday, is 30th in line. 
</P>
<P>
	Defending race winner Eddie Cheever drew qualifying position No.  
1, followed by Stewart, Scott Sharp and rookies David Steele and 
Jaques Lazier. 
</P>
<P>
	Billy Boat, last year's pole-winner, will go 15th, while his  
teammate, Kenny Brack, the defending Pep Boys Indy Racing League 
champion, is 25th. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *THE PAYOFF:* It takes four laps around the 2 1/2-mile oval to win  
the pole for the Indianapolis 500. For the driver who accomplishes 
that feat, the payoff averages well over $25,000 a lap. 
</P>
<P>
	To begin, the pole winner on Saturday will get the traditional  
trophy and a check for $100,000 from sponsor PPG Industries. If he 
or she runs the fastest single lap in qualifying, add $5,000 to 
that. 
</P>
<P>
	Each of the 33 starters in the race, including the pole-winner,  
will get $15,000 as well as a ring from PPG. 
</P>
<P>
	The fastest qualifier will also get to drive home a 1999  
Chevrolet Camaro pace car, worth about $30,000. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *AERIAL VIEW:* Kevin Forbes, director of engineering and  
construction for the Indianapolis Motor Speedway, says the last leg 
of the infield portion of the new Formula One track will be paved 
before the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want people to be able to see the road course when there  
are pictures shot from the blimp for TV,'' Forbes said. ``We hope 
people will see how well it fits into the overall layout of the 
facility.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The speedway is spending an estimated $75 million for  
construction projects, including the track, 36 Formula One garages, 
a new control tower and media center. All of the work is expected 
to be done prior to the first F1 races at the track on Sept. 24, 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The road circuit is 2.61 miles long and traverses 13 turns. It  
uses about half of the historic 2 1/2-mile oval, including most of the 
main straightaway. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *PORTER CRITICAL:* Herb Porter, one of the most successful  
engine-builders in the history of the speedway, was in critical 
condition after being involved in a traffic accident on I-74 near 
Indianapolis on Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Porter, 84, owns Speedway Engines, located in the track's  
Gasoline Alley area. The company builds engines for Indy Racing 
League teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Porter and driving great Eddie Sachs, who was killed in a crash  
during the 1964 Indy 500, were scheduled to be inducted into the 
Indianapolis Motor Speedway Hall of Fame on Friday night during the 
annual Hall of Fame/Indianapolis Old Timers dinner. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SPECIAL VISIT:* Stan Fox, who was seriously injured in a  
spectacular crash on the first lap of the 1995 Indy 500, was back 
at the track Friday in an entirely different capacity. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox, whose racing career ended with that crash, spent the day  
escorting students from an Indianapolis middle school through the 
garage area as part of his role with the ``Friends of the Fox'' 
head injury support group. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox introduced the students to several drivers, including  
two-time Indy winner Arie Luyendyk. The former driver also took the 
youngsters for a tour of the speedway museum. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SPARK PLUGS:* Rookie Brian Tyler replaced Vincenzo Sospiri as  
Jeff Ward's ISM Racing teammate. Sospiri, who finished 17th in the 
1997 race, could not get out of a testing commitment with his 
sports car team. ... This year's Indy 500 rookie of the year will 
receive a check for $25,000 from sponsor Bank One. That's an 
increase of $15,000 from last year. 

</P>
