<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> As Knicks Win, Grunfeld Sits  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Like the rest of the New York Knicks, Ernie  
Grunfeld had the day off today. Unlike the others, he won't be back 
at Madison Square Garden when their series against the Atlanta 
Hawks resumes. 
</P>
<P>
	Grunfeld, the former general manager and team president who was  
demoted in a front office shakeup last month, has been watching 
from afar as the team he built has begun to thrive in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Led by controversial new acquisitions Latrell Sprewell and  
Marcus Camby, the Knicks have a 2-0 lead over Atlanta in the 
best-of-7 second round. The series resumes Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people criticized what I did, but I did what was in  
the best interest of the organization,'' Grunfeld said. ``I still 
feel very good about it, and now it's starting to come around and 
people are starting to see why I made the decisions I did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It has been more than a month since Grunfeld was reassigned to  
special consultant, a move made by Madison Square Garden president 
Dave Checketts while the team was floundering with a .500 record 
and in danger of missing the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The demotion all but ruined the relationship between Grunfeld  
and Checketts, who considered each other friends and whose families 
were close. 
</P>
<P>
	Refusing to call himself bitter, it's nonetheless clear Grunfeld  
feels a sense of betrayal from the organization he spent 18 years 
with as a player, broadcaster and chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was hurt,'' Grunfeld admitted in a telephone interview  
Friday after playing a round of golf. ``I was hurt by the events 
that happened and the timing of the events, but sometimes strange 
things happen in our business. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a good lesson for our family to see that things aren't  
always going to go perfect in your life, and sometimes you're going 
to have to regroup. My family grew up as a Knicks family, and the 
Knicks were a very important part of our lives. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard on them, but they're tough and were going to move  
on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The demotion of Grunfeld has remained a hot topic of debate in  
New York for the past month as the team has begun to click on a 
consistent basis. A victory over the Hawks would put New York into 
the Eastern Conference finals for the first time since 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell, acquired by Grunfeld prior to the season for John  
Starks, Terry Cummings and Chris Mills, has scored 31 points in 
each of the first two games against the Hawks and is New York's 
leading scorer in the postseason. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's on a level with Michael Jordan,'' Atlanta's Ed Gray said.  
``He's that type of player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition of Camby was the subject of much more criticism,  
including within the organization and especially with coach Jeff 
Van Gundy, because it cost the Knicks gritty veteran Charles 
Oakley. 
</P>
<P>
	But Camby has injected the team with a shot-blocking presence on  
defense and a youthful energy on offense that had been missing for 
the better part of a decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Camby's devastating dunk over Dikembe Mutombo in Game 2, a play  
on which he took off from near the foul line, was exactly the type 
of moment Oakley was simply incapable of. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel a lot of pride in the way things are coming around,''  
said Grunfeld, who has been watching the games on TV with family 
and friends. 
</P>
<P>
	``We watch and we root, I'm a Knicks fan, and I feel this is the  
team I put together and I felt could be competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew it was going to take a little longer than normal for  
this team to come together, but finally it is coming together and 
I'm really happy about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Hawks, meanwhile, stayed in Atlanta on Friday for a long  
film session and practice. They will try to become just the eighth 
team in NBA history to come back from a 2-0 deficit in a seven-game 
series. 
</P>
<P>
	Game 3 is Sunday afternoon, and Game 4 is Monday night.  
</P>
<P>
	``Oh-and-two is not a good situation to be in, but it's not  
impossible,'' Steve Smith said. ``The Garden is the one place where 
you just like to play.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
