<HEADLINE> Arrillaga Named AP Regional Writer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Pauline Arrillaga, a newswoman in Houston for  
The Associated Press, has been named Southwest regional reporter 
for the news cooperative, based in Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	Arrillaga becomes part of a team of reporters formed in 1985 to  
cover topics of regional and national interest. She will work 
closely with editors in the AP's Western Regional Service. 
</P>
<P>
	The appointment was announced Thursday by AP Managing Editor  
Jonathan Wolman. 
</P>
<P>
	Arrillaga joined the AP in Dallas in 1992 and also worked in  
Austin. In 1995 she became correspondent in Harlingen, covering 
such issues as immigration and drug trafficking in 13 counties 
along the Texas-Mexico border. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year she transferred to Houston, where she has assisted  
with coverage of the space shuttle program, including John Glenn's 
historic return to space. 
</P>
<P>
	Arrillaga, 28, is a graduate of the University of North Texas.  
She is a native of Atlanta and grew up in Virginia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
