<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Overturns FCC Phone Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal appeals court today overturned a  
decision by federal regulators that had resulted in lower 
long-distance phone bills for millions of Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia sent part  
of the 1997 decision back to the Federal Communications Commission 
for review. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said the FCC didn't adequately explain certain changes  
to a complex formula that affects ``access'' payments that 
long-distance companies pay local phone companies to connect calls. 
</P>
<P>
	These fees are typically passed on to long-distance customers  
and make up a big portion of the average long-distance bill. When 
the FCC orders these fees to be reduced, the savings are supposed 
to be passed along to long-distance customers. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997 the FCC made some adjustments that caused the access  
fees to be reduced by more than $1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Specifically, the court today disagreed with the FCC's rationale  
for making those changes to the so-called ``X Factor.'' Expressed 
as a percentage, the factor aims at ensuring that as a local phone 
company's productivity improves, the company would receive less 
from these access payments. 
</P>
<P>
	Local phone companies ``argue that the FCC did not give a  
rational explanation of that choice and we agree,'' the court said 
in its 11-page opinion. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision is a major victory for the nation's Bell companies,  
GTE and other local phone companies and a blow to the FCC and the 
long-distance companies AT&AMP;T, MCI WorldCom and Sprint. 
</P>
<P>
	The local telephone industry through the United States Telephone  
Association had contested this portion of the FCC's decision before 
the court. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T and MCI had challenged the FCC's 1997 calculations for  
opposite reasons. The long-distance companies contended the FCC 
should have adjusted its formula to result in deeper cuts in the 
access payments. 
</P>
<P>
	The court's decision is likely to affect how the FCC adjusts  
access fees later this year. The fees are still expected to be 
reduced, but now it is not clear by how much. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 16:10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Arab Woman Elected in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAIBEH, Israel (AP) -- For half a century, Arab women in Israel  
had no voice in parliament. That's changed with the victory of 
Hussnia Jabara, the first Arab woman elected to Israel's Knesset. 
</P>
<P>
	``It shouldn't have taken so long,'' said the 41-year-old  
activist, whose priorities are to improve education and fight 
unemployment in Arab communities that have suffered discrimination 
at the hands of Israeli governments for years. 
</P>
<P>
	But despite her election this week, the 120-member Knesset  
continues to be dominated by men -- only 14 of the newly elected 
legislators are women, and that's an all-time high. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Jabara's victory highlights gradual changes in Israeli  
Arab society, where women, even of her generation, were expected to 
be mothers and wives, not lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Jabara, a farmer's daughter, married a man her family chose for  
her when she was 19. ``We weren't modern then,'' she said, 
laughing. 
</P>
<P>
	But times have changed. While she gives interviews, her husband,  
Fathi, a driving teacher, helps answer the phones. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of men worked on her campaign in Taibeh, a Muslim  
community of 27,000 residents located about 20 miles northeast of 
Tel Aviv. Her mother prayed for her and neighbors flocked to her 
home every evening to show support. 
</P>
<P>
	And, Jabara said, in a sign that Arab citizens are slowly being  
integrated into the Israeli mainstream, the primarily Jewish, 
left-wing Meretz Party, on whose slate she was elected, made 
getting an Arab woman into parliament a priority. 
</P>
<P>
	Meretz was the only party competing in the elections to use a  
quota system under which four of the top 10 candidates on the slate 
had to be women. Meretz won 10 seats, with Jabara in 10th place. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the issues Jabara is pushing are longer school days so  
Arab women can work full-time if they choose and better education 
about birth control to increase women's freedom. 
</P>
<P>
	One of 15 children, Jabara believes that once education  
improves, the Arab community will become more open to expanding 
women's traditional roles. 
</P>
<P>
	While she has found a home in Meretz, the Arab political  
establishment has been slower to change. The three predominantly 
Arab parties have failed to elect a woman to a realistic slot on 
their party lists. 
</P>
<P>
	Mohammed Miari, a former lawmaker in the Arab National  
Democratic Alliance, warns that Jabara's victory should not be 
overrated. The advancement of Arab women, he said, was linked to 
that of Israel's Arab community as a whole, which, he contended, 
still faced widespread discrimination. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, there has been a slow move toward integration of Israel's  
1 million Arab citizens. 
</P>
<P>
	An Arab woman from the mixed city of Haifa was crowned Miss  
Israel this spring and an Arab legislator made a bid for prime 
minister in last week's elections. Though dominated by Jewish 
candidates, the two largest political parties, Likud and Labor, 
brought three Arab lawmakers into parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	Jabara said teaming up with Jewish parties was key because it  
gave Arab politicians a chance to sit in the government. While no 
predominantly Arab party has ever been asked to join a government, 
Meretz is expected to become a member of Prime Minister-elect Ehud 
Barak's new coalition. 
</P>
<P>
	Fellow Meretz legislator Naomi Hazan said Jabara has her work  
cut out for her. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hussnia faces a tremendous responsibility because, until now,  
nobody has dealt with the interests of Arab women,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
