<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 17:11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Disabled Golfer Says He'll Play  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) -- A local golf pro who lost his court  
battle with the U.S. Golf Association said today he'll still play 
in a local qualifier for the U.S. Open despite a judge's ruling 
barring him from using a cart. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford Olinger, who has a degenerative hip disorder that makes  
walking 18 holes nearly impossible, said he would consult with his 
doctors before playing Monday at the South Bend Country Club. 
Unless they tell him that he risks serious injury by playing, he'll 
be there. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to go out and commit suicide,'' Olinger said.  
``If everything goes well, you're going to see me at 10:10 (a.m.) 
at the South Bend Country Club. 
</P>
<P>
	``If that's what the USGA wants, that's what the USGA is going  
to get.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Olinger sued the USGA under the Americans with Disabilities Act  
seeking a permanent injunction allowing him to ride in qualifiers 
for the Open. But U.S. District Judge Robert Miller ruled such an 
accommodation would fundamentally alter the nature of the 
tournament and denied the request. 
</P>
<P>
	Olinger, a golf pro in Warsaw, successfully sued the USGA last  
year to use a cart in a local qualifier in a similar suit. Though 
he was allowed to ride, he shot a 12-over-par 83 and did not 
qualify for the sectional. 
</P>
<P>
	What remains to be seen now is whether Miller's decision will  
eventually affect Casey Martin, who has a circulatory disorder in 
his right leg that makes it painful for him to walk long distances. 
</P>
<P>
	He successfully sued the PGA to use a court on tour, and the PGA  
has appealed the decision to the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals. 
The USGA has agreed to allow him to ride while the suit is under 
appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	USGA spokesman Marty Parkes said the association hasn't analyzed  
the implications of Miller's decision yet, but he reiterated that 
Martin would be allowed to ride in this year's Open. Still, the 
association now has a trial judge's decision backing up their 
contention that carts represent an unfair advantage, and Parkes 
said the USGA's executive committee will discuss its options at its 
meeting during the U.S. Open. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing that says there's going to be a decision out  
of that meeting right away, but it certainly will be discussed,'' 
Parkes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Parkes said the USGA made the exception for Martin in deference  
to his suit against the PGA. Still, Olinger said he was frustrated 
by the USGA's decision to allow Martin to ride while fighting him 
in court on his request. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's another guy going on a cart, and it's not me,'' he  
said. ``I don't know how they justify him getting a cart and me 
not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His attorney, John Hamilton, said Olinger has 30 days to appeal  
the judge's decision, but he's unsure whether Olinger will have the 
funds to pursue an appeal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
