<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> L.L. Bean To Expand Retail Presence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FREEPORT, Maine (AP) -- Mail-order company L.L. Bean plans to  
open its first major U.S. store outside Maine, the first step 
toward expanding its domestic retail presence beyond the 24-hour 
store that Leon Leonwood Bean opened 87 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The new location, in the Tysons Corner Center mall in McLean,  
Va., is part of the company's strategy for boosting profits in an 
era of ever-increasing competition in its core mail-order business. 
</P>
<P>
	Leon Gorman, president and grandson of L.L. Bean, said the  
outdoors outfitter is up to the challenge of the suburban shopping 
mall. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody is worried about The Gap, but we've got a unique  
niche and we have a good opportunity,'' he said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, L.L. Bean plans to build at least three stores by 2001  
to test the retail waters, said Bill Shea, L.L. Bean's top retail 
executive. Those are in addition to the main store in Freeport, 10 
smaller outlet stores in four states and 16 stores in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, whose sales have hovered around $1 billion for the  
past four years, hopes the new stores will boost brand identity 
while increasing sales of camping gear, fishing gear, bicycles, 
kayaks and canoes -- all things that people might want to see or 
feel before buying. 
</P>
<P>
	The company hopes to maintain an outdoors theme similar to its  
Freeport store, so the 75,000-square-foot Tysons Corner store, 
which is expected to open by July 2000, will feature a stream, 
waterfall and indoor trout pond, Shea said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wendy Liebmann, president of WSL Strategic Retail, a marketing  
and retail consultant in New York, said it's important for L.L. 
Bean to seek new markets and introduce trendier clothing lines to 
attract new customers. But she said it's important for the company 
to move slowly. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a noble thing for them to do, but it's fraught with a lot  
of challenges for a company that isn't traditionally in the retail 
business and the fashion business,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The location was chosen because there are 1.4 million L.L. Bean  
catalog customers living in the area and because the mall attracts 
21 million visitors a year. Also, Great Falls National Park on the 
Potomac River is 10 miles away and the Appalachian Trail is 75 
miles away. 
</P>
<P>
	L.L. Bean workers will teach outdoor skills like fly casting,  
kayaking and canoeing the same way it does through its Outdoors 
Discovery Program in Freeport, Gorman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The other stores planned by L.L. Bean will be smaller -- about  
30,000 square feet -- and won't necessarily be located in malls. 
</P>
<P>
	The goal is to introduce the company to new customers as well as  
serve current customers, providing another avenue for profits in an 
era where homes are flooded with mail-order catalogs. 
</P>
<P>
	About 85 percent of L.L. Bean's revenues currently come from  
catalog sales, 10 percent from retail sales and 5 percent over the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Gorman is optimistic the retail-stores experiment will work.  
``We don't see it as a risk because we believe it will be received 
enthusiastically. We'd look silly if it flops, but it won't.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
