<HEADLINE> Feds To Study Olympics Records </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Congressional investigators examining Atlanta's  
bid for the 1996 Olympics will be in Georgia next month to go 
through many of the records of the bid committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation holds about 1,400 boxes  
of records that detail the committee's enticements to IOC members 
from 1988 to 1990, when Atlanta was awarded the 1996 Summer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The foundation has agreed to give the U.S. House Commerce  
Committee access to the records, even though the foundation is 
battling The Atlanta Journal-Constitution in court to keep them 
from being released publicly. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee Echols, a GAAF spokesman, said today the House committee has  
not determined how many of the records will be examined or how long 
the process will take. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not know what the inquiry's schedule is at this point,''  
Echols said. ``We are cooperating fully with the committee and will 
do whatever is necessary to do this review.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The committee wants to determine if the boxes of records contain  
evidence of bribery similar to the scandal that has tainted Salt 
Lake City's successful bid for the 2002 Winter Olympics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
