<HEADLINE> Deal Struck in Charlie Trie Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Presidential friend Yah Lin ``Charlie''  
Trie, the restaurateur turned political fund-raiser implicated in 
improper contributions from Chinese officials, today reached a plea 
agreement on an obstruction of justice charge against him, a 
prosecutor said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor George Vein confirmed today that a deal has been  
struck. Details were withheld pending an announcement in court. 
</P>
<P>
	Trie's trial began Monday. He was accused of obstructing justice  
by ordering an employee to destroy documents subpoenaed in 1997 by 
a federal grand jury and by the Senate Governmental Affairs 
Committee. The charges carry a penalty of up to five years in 
prison and a $250,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	He faces separate charges in Washington that he made and  
arranged illegal contributions from foreigners to the Democratic 
National Committee. Trie is accused of making the contributions to 
buy access to Clinton and other top officials for himself and the 
likes of Chinese arms dealer Wang Jun. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic National Committee has returned $640,000 that  
Trie raised. President Clinton's legal defense fund has returned 
another $460,000 raised by Trie. 
</P>
<P>
	He became friends with then-Gov. Clinton when Clinton frequented  
a Chinese restaurant Trie owned near the state Capitol. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors had expected to wrap up their case today.  
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, testimony was suspended and jurors were sent home  
while lawyers for the prosecution and the defense wrangled over 
what documents the defense should be allowed to present as 
evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyers say thousands of documents were provided to  
congressional investigators, making Trie's business and 
fund-raising activities an open book. 
</P>
<P>
	But Maria Mapili, who managed his office here, testified that  
Trie ordered her to get rid of documents that the Senate panel 
sought in its probe. She said she threw out some papers but hid 
others that were later seized or turned over to the grand jury. 
</P>
</TEXT>
