<DOCNO> APW19990521.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 15:55:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Carr Not the Show on De La Hoya Card </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Oscar De La Hoya could probably take it easy  
tomorrow night, box Oba Carr for 12 rounds and add another $5 
million to his already fat bank account. 
</P>
<P>
	With a megafight set with fellow welterweight champion Felix  
Trinidad and other big bouts ahead, it would seem the prudent thing 
to do. 
</P>
<P>
	De La Hoya, however, is in no mood to be prudent.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not boxing anymore. I'm going back to fighting, to the old  
school way,'' De La Hoya said. ``I'm going to walk through guys and 
destroy them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That could be bad news for Carr, a decent enough fighter but a  
10-1 underdog when he challenges De La Hoya for the WBC 147-pound 
title in the scheduled 12-round bout at the Mandalay Bay resort. 
</P>
<P>
	But it would please De La Hoya's fans, who may have been  
disappointed in the cautious way he fought Ike Quartey his last 
time out and the fact that four of his last eight fights have gone 
the 12-round distance. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guarantee you there is no fighter in the world who can take  
my punch and last 12 rounds,'' De La Hoya said. ``So what am I 
doing boxing people? I should be going out there and destroying 
them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	De La Hoya doesn't need to knock Carr out to guarantee a Sept.  
18 fight with Trinidad that will pay him $15 million. He simply 
needs to beat Carr for the fight, which was finalized Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	But De La Hoya says he has a reborn desire to punch people out.  
It came to him just during training camp when he woke up one 
morning about five weeks ago and decided that he should return to 
the form in which he knocked out 20 of his first 22 opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	A parade of different trainers, he said, had changed his style  
by convincing him that he was getting hit too much and should try 
to box more in the ring. 
</P>
<P>
	``I decided to listen to myself and do what I want in the  
ring,'' De La Hoya said. ``My passion is fighting and I wasn't 
happy doing the things I was doing against (Pernell) Whitaker, 
Quartey and the others. I'm not a boxer, I'm a fighter. I'm a 
slugger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	De La Hoya said his transformation from boxer back to puncher  
began the same day of his revelation in his training camp in the 
mountains of Big Bear, Calif. He went into the ring and began 
backing his sparring partners up and punishing them instead of 
looking for angles and trying to block punches. 
</P>
<P>
	The results, says trainer Roberto Alcazar, have been nothing  
short of spectacular. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's 100 percent different,'' Alcazar said. ``He's happy and  
he's hurting people in the ring. He's the old Oscar like he was 
when he first started out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	De La Hoya may be fortunate he's got a chance to test out his  
new theory of fighting against Carr instead of a ferocious puncher 
the likes of Trinidad. 
</P>
<P>
	Both fighters weighed in Friday at the class limit of 147  
pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Carr is capable enough and certainly no pushover. He's 48-2-1  
with 28 knockouts and his only two losses were to Trinidad and 
Quartey, both of whom he knocked down before being beaten. 
</P>
<P>
	But Carr has had both sides of his jaw broken in his last two  
fights, and the Detroit fighter will be getting a bigger and 
stronger opponent. Carr had his jaw wired for weeks and was on a 
liquid diet after winning a Feb. 22 elimination fight against 
Frankie Randall to qualify for the De La Hoya fight. 
</P>
<P>
	``Oba Carr is a dangerous opponent and he'll be ready to  
fight,'' said De La Hoya, 30-0 with 24 knockouts. ``When I fight an 
opponent, they lift themselves up to the sky. They all want to be 
the first to beat Oscar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fight with Carr, which will be televised by HBO beginning  
around 11:30 p.m. EDT, has been largely overshadowed by 
negotiations between rival promoters Bob Arum and Don King over a 
Sept. 18 fight between De La Hoya and Trinidad, who holds the IBF 
version of the welterweight title. 
</P>
<P>
	Promoter Bob Arum said Friday that De La Hoya will receive $15  
million and Trinidad's camp will get $10.5 million for the bout. 
</P>
<P>
	``The two fighters have to win, that's the main thing,'' Arum  
said. ``Other than that, it's a done deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carr would love nothing better than to disrupt the carefully  
laid plans of De La Hoya and his promoter. The 27-year-old, who 
will make $350,000, sees himself as part of a welterweight series 
that could include a number of fights between the likes of himself, 
De La Hoya, Quartey and Trinidad. 
</P>
<P>
	``Trinidad and Oscar is an attractive fight,'' Carr conceded.  
``People want to see that fight. But in the future they're going to 
want to see Oba Carr and Trinidad and Oba Carr and De La Hoya in a 
rematch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also on the card is a second title fight, with Floyd Mayweather  
defending his WBC super featherweight title against Justin Juuko, a 
Ugandan living in Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be the third defense of the title for Mayweather, a 1996  
Olympian who is 20-0 as a pro. He was supposed to have fought Goyo 
Vargas, but Vargas became sick in training camp and pulled out at 
the last minute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 15:55:47 </DATE_TIME>
