<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Va. Health Facility Blamed in Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Shoddy medical care and poor communication  
between nurses and doctors were to blame for the death of a patient 
at a state-run mental health institute, two confidential reports 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Skander Najar died June 8 from an inflamed, bleeding pancreas  
while he was a patient at the Northern Virginia Mental Health 
Institute. Two days earlier, he was vomiting and showing other 
symptoms, but nurses' notes show the on-call doctor who was 
notified put off seeing him until the next morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Najar, 26, didn't receive emergency treatment until his mother,  
Hanni Najar, arranged his transfer to neighboring Fairfax Hospital 
at a nurse's urging, an internal report by the institute said. The 
Associated Press obtained a copy of the report. 
</P>
<P>
	Fairfax Hospital staff fought for 24 hours to save Najar, but  
couldn't. 
</P>
<P>
	The internal investigation said Najar's death was caused by  
human error, specifically ``inadequate physical assessment, 
documentation and communication of the patient's changing clinical 
condition'' by the institute's medical staff. It said nurses 
believed they would be yelled at by on-call physicians who believed 
they were receiving too many calls. 
</P>
<P>
	A consultant for the state attorney general's office drew  
similar conclusions in a separate review. ``The information in the 
record indicates that on on-call M.D. should have ensured immediate 
medical evaluation,'' the consultant, psychiatry professor 
Catherine A. Leslie, wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Justice Department has been investigating negligence,  
abuse and deaths of patients in Virginia's public mental 
institutions since 1990, and the Northern Virginia institute is 
still under investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Half of the psychiatrists at the institute, including the  
on-call doctor, lost their jobs after Najar's death. The institute 
has adopted policies to improve basic patient care and staff 
communication that include having an on-site doctor 24 hours a day, 
seven days a week, and the state mental health system has been 
overhauled. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Najar said the reports confirmed her fears about her son's  
death. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had already come to the conclusion that there were problems  
at the institute, but I wasn't fully aware of the extent of the 
problems,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 14:44:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Eagles Sign Staley To Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Philadelphia Eagles have their franchise  
running back, and his name is not Ricky Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	The Eagles signed Duce Staley to a six-year, $16.3 million  
contract extension today, a month after picking quarterback Donovan 
McNabb instead of Williams with the No. 2 pick in the NFL draft. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal keeps Staley in Philadelphia through the 2004 season,  
and he could make an additional $2 million in incentives. He rushed 
for 1,065 yards last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's more than what I thought I was getting here, and I  
thought I was getting a lot,'' Eagles coach Andy Reid said. ``We 
are counting on Duce and we tried to show that by signing him to 
this contract.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After Ricky Watters signed with Seattle as a free agent, Staley  
won the Eagles' starting job last season from injury-plagued 
Charlie Garner, who was released last month. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Eagles secured the No. 2 draft pick with a 3-13 season,  
fans began a loud campaign for the team to choose Williams, the 
Heisman Trophy winner from Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	The City Council even voted on a resolution for the team to pick  
Williams; it was stymied by council members who realized there were 
better things to do. Mayor Edward Rendell urged fans to call the 
Eagles offices and lobby for Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	Reid and Tom Modrak, director of football operations, chose  
McNabb instead -- partly because of Staley's breakthrough season as 
a featured back. In addition to becoming a 1,000-yard rusher, 
Staley added 432 yards receiving on a team-high 57 catches and six 
touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	Staley, a third-round pick by the Eagles in 1997 from South  
Carolina, could have become a restricted free agent after this 
season. He resisted the lure of testing the market, partly because 
of what he remembered about Watters' heated contract talks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't want to go into the year thinking about money,  
thinking about myself,'' Staley said. ``I felt I would be cheating 
the team, thinking about all the money I could be chasing. I can't 
live for tomorrow. I can only live for today. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Eagles drafted me, so I feel dedicated to them like they  
are dedicated to me. They gave me my first shot so I thought it was 
only right as far as returning the favor.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 03:34:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Golden Bear Is Back  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AVONDALE, Pa. (AP) -- Jack Nicklaus took a moment to recall the  
days when he was young and greedy, a time when he felt he could do 
anything on a golf course and pushed his body to give him what he 
demanded. 
</P>
<P>
	His gait was much quicker, his hair shinier and closer to the  
color of sand in a bunker. Nicklaus felt invincible back then, and 
he believes that is part of the reason he now must step gingerly 
into a sand trap, steadying a 59-year-old body that is now partly 
supported by a ceramic left hip. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that my hip problem and the early aging resulted  
basically because of cortisone injections,'' said Nicklaus, who 
returns to competitive golf today for the first time in nearly a 
year. ``I had 25 of them in a 10-week period when I was 23 years 
old. 
</P>
<P>
	``They wouldn't do that any more, but that's what they used to  
do in those days. A lot of my back problems, I think, came from 
cortisone. By the time I was 19, I'd had my back injected in seven 
different places and some of them repeatedly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There is nothing Nicklaus can do about it now, except what he  
has always done. Play golf. 
</P>
<P>
	Warming up for his first tournament since having his left hip  
replaced in January, Nicklaus shot an even-par 72 Thursday in a 
pro-am round just four months after the experimental operation. 
Teeing off today in the Senior PGA Bell Atlantic Classic, Nicklaus 
ends a 299-day layoff -- his longest since turning professional in 
1961. He last played in the U.S. Senior Open on July 26, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Waving to the crowd and then slicing his first tee shot into the  
rough, Nicklaus tried to see beyond the moment. Even as he gets his 
golf game back into shape, Nicklaus is dreaming of one final charge 
that will cap his brilliant career. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll play a little bit this fall, just because I want to play  
next year,'' Nicklaus said. ``My goal next year is to try to play 
the four majors and try to be as competitive as I can be. Beyond 
that point, I'm not saying that's going to be the end of my playing 
major championship golf, but it'll probably be the end of my 
playing all four of them in one year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Out of habit, impatience, or a little of both, Nicklaus clutched  
a microphone as if it were a 9-iron while discussing his quick 
comeback from an operation that forced him to miss his first 
Masters in 40 years. 
</P>
<P>
	He was told he couldn't return for six months, and Nicklaus  
eagled that estimate, so to speak, beating it by two months. 
Doctors were amazed at the deterioration in Nicklaus' hip, which 
had been bone-on-bone with no cartilage for several years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never expected to be able to do things so soon,'' said  
Nicklaus, who played about 20 practice rounds at home in North Palm 
Beach, Fla., before making his comeback official. ``I certainly 
don't want to do it again, but it was no big deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If all goes well this weekend at this senior tournament in the  
Philadelphia suburbs, Nicklaus will play the Memorial Tournament on 
the course he designed in Dublin, Ohio, June 3-6. Then he plans to 
play in the U.S. Open, U.S. Senior Open and Senior Players 
Championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``I doubt that I'll go to the British this year,'' Nicklaus  
said. ``That's too many weeks in a row. I might play the PGA 
Championship and I might not. I haven't made up my mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nicklaus teed off on No. 10 in the pro-am, bogeying the first  
hole and double-bogeying the fifth. He finished with four birdies. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just don't have my strength yet,'' Nicklaus said. ``I mean,  
I'm not terrible. I surprise myself every once in while and hit one 
pretty good. But I'm 85 percent top form.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Playing to the crowd and signing autographs, Nicklaus walked  
nearly all of the hilly course. He plans to do the same in the 
tournament, even though carts are legal on the senior tour. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't think that I played great, but I played better than  
I've been playing,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicklaus made a terrific second shot on the par-3 11th, coaxing  
a short chip 3 feet from the cup before sinking the easy putt for 
par. He has come a long way since first clutching a club in his 
hands after the surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	Imagine Nicklaus, the six-time Masters champion, starting from  
scratch in the weeks after the surgery -- with half swings, 
three-quarter swings and finally full swings that drove the ball 
only 170 yards or so. He joked that he's not even a four-handicap. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm trying to get back to a four,'' Nicklaus said. ``I was a  
four when I was about 12 years old and haven't worried about it 
much since then.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Nicklaus stirred memories of his triumphant, youthful  
days when he became the oldest player to finish in the top 10 at 
the Masters, shooting a final-round, 4-under-par 68 to tie for 
sixth. 
</P>
<P>
	If his bid for one last shot at the four majors goes as planned,  
he wonders how his mind and body will respond. 
</P>
<P>
	``You find something inside you that will sort of drive you on,  
like at the Masters,'' Nicklaus said. ``I remembered how to finish 
a golf tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that will come back. I'll remember.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 21:11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 5 Boys Charged For Raping Twin Girls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Kan. (AP) -- Five boys were charged Friday in the  
alleged rape and sodomy of 6-year-old twin girls at a day-care 
center. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspects, four 13-year-old boys and one 11-year-old boy,  
sexually assaulted the girls on May 15 in the basement of a day 
care center and in a shed next door, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	The girls were apparently alone in the center and unattended by  
any adult, police said. The next day, the girls told their mother 
about the alleged assault and they were taken to the hospital for 
tests. 
</P>
<P>
	``They saw the girls were available and took advantage of  
them,'' Lt. Doug Hansen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the suspects are the sons of the woman who runs the day  
care center and lives next door to the center, police said. The 
other three are friends of her sons. 
</P>
<P>
	Each of the boys was charged in juvenile court with six counts  
of aggravated criminal sodomy. Two of them were also charged with 
two counts of rape. 
</P>
<P>
	Four of the boys were in custody Friday night and a fifth was at  
large, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The day-care center was closed by order of the state on  
Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 18:21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paralyzed Gymnast Fulfills Dream </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Chinese gymnast Sang Lan, who was  
paralyzed during the Goodwill Games last summer, fulfilled a 
longtime wish today when she visited the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Accompanied by China's U.N. Ambassador Qin Huasun and a host of  
diplomats, the 17-year-old gymnast got to see the U.N. Security 
Council chamber where she hit the president's gavel and the General 
Assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	``The U.N. symbolizes world peace,'' Sang said through an  
interpreter. 
</P>
<P>
	Sitting in a wheelchair, she also got to see Chinese sculptures  
and other gifts to the United Nations from her government. 
</P>
<P>
	Sang, a member of the Chinese national team, was severely  
injured during a warmup exercise at the Goodwill Games last summer 
in Uniondale, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	She was paralyzed from the neck down, but has regained some  
strength in her shoulders, elbows and wrists, and can raise her 
arms. 
</P>
<P>
	China's U.N. Mission said the U.N. visit was her last public  
appearance in the United States before returning home Sunday via 
Detroit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
