<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Labonte Wins Winston Pole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- Bobby Labonte has finished second in each  
of the last two all-star races for NASCAR's Winston Cup series. 
He's in prime position to improve on that this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Labonte won the pole for the 15th annual running of The Winston  
by destroying the qualifying record Friday night by more than 3.5 
mph. 
</P>
<P>
	In a format that requires drivers to make three laps around  
Lowe's Motor Speedway at Charlotte and stop to change two tires, 
Labonte capitalized on a pit stop that took just 9.8 seconds. The 
result was an average speed of 146.830 mph, easily eclipsing the 
143.273 set by Bill Elliott two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're awfully excited,'' said Labonte, who would win a minimum  
of $200,000 for a victory in Saturday night's 70-lap race. ``The 
guys did a great job on the pit stop and I got in and out of the 
pits really well and didn't spin the tires too bad. That's the name 
of the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was Labonte's first pole in five appearances at The Winston,  
which has a purse of more than $1.3 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting alongside him will be defending Winston Cup champion  
Jeff Gordon, who had a pit stop of 8.9 seconds but wasn't as fast 
as Labonte on the track and wound up with a 144.814. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Martin, who won The Winston last year when Gordon ran out  
of gas taking the white flag, also broke the qualifying record 
Friday night with a 143.862 and will start third. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty drivers were guaranteed entry in The Winston, with the  
remainder of the field being filled by the winner of the Winston 
Open, a 50-lap race held for non-qualifiers before Saturday night's 
main event. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be the first racing activity at the track since May 1,  
when three spectators were killed and eight more were injured by 
debris that flew into the stands following a crash during an Indy 
Racing League event. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday night's activities drew a crowd of about 35,000,  
including many who sat in the fourth-turn grandstands where the 
debris from the IRL wreck landed. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd saw a number of problems in addition to Labonte's  
impressive qualifying run. 
</P>
<P>
	Darrell Waltrip, winner of the first Winston in 1985 and one of  
three drivers to compete in every all-star race, was penalized 
three seconds because an air gun was thrown back over the pit-road 
wall after his stop. Waltrip will start 17th. 
</P>
<P>
	Winston Cup points leader Jeff Burton had just the 16th-fastest  
speed after crew chief Frankie Stoddard, changing the right-front 
tire, couldn't get the lug nuts tightened on the first try. 
</P>
<P>
	The worst pit stop of the session, however, went to Ricky Rudd,  
who in his haste to get back on the track for his third lap did a 
360-degree spin near the exit of pit road. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were going for it,'' said Rudd, who will start 19th. ``I  
feel bad for the guys. We had a good pit stop, and I let them down 
a little bit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At least Rudd made it in to get two tires changed before he  
messed up his stop. Ward Burton came charging down pit road so fast 
that he couldn't get stopped in time, and he slid right past his 
stall. 
</P>
<P>
	Car owner Bill Davis, watching from just behind the pit-road  
wall, epitomized the good-natured spirit of the all-star weekend by 
smiling and giving a friendly wave to Burton as he skidded past in 
a cloud of gray tire smoke. 
</P>
<P>
	Burton will start 20th.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
