<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ray, Stewart in Pole Battle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The rivalry is heating up between Greg Ray  
and Tony Stewart, the man he replaced at Team Menard. 
</P>
<P>
	Those two are considered the drivers to beat on Saturday in pole  
qualifying for the Indianapolis 500 on May 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, a former Indy Racing League champion who has moved on  
to become the hottest rookie in NASCAR's Winston Cup series, left 
Team Menard at the end of the 1998 season. 
</P>
<P>
	His seat was filled by Ray, a fast but unproven driver who IRL  
officials hope develops into a star, much as they hoped Stewart 
would become their main man before he chose to concentrate on stock 
cars. 
</P>
<P>
	When practice began last Saturday at the Indianapolis Motor  
Speedway, it was Ray who set the pace for the first few days. 
</P>
<P>
	Then Stewart emerged, driving for a new team of which he is a  
co-owner. He turned it up Wednesday, running the fast lap of the 
week at 226.683 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked about Ray, Stewart said, ``I haven't paid much  
attention to those guys, but he's got all of my old setups, so they 
ought to be going fast.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ray answered on Thursday, retaking the top spot on the speed  
chart with a lap of 227.192. 
</P>
<P>
	``It feels nice to be this consistently quick,'' Ray said. ``We  
regard our competition very highly. We're not taking anything for 
granted. From here, we want to try to go even faster but, above 
all, keep it off the wall.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart wasn't able to keep his car off the wall.  
</P>
<P>
	Shaking down his primary car, he got too high in turn 3 on the  
2 1/2-mile oval and bounced twice off the concrete wall before 
stopping on the main straightaway. 
</P>
<P>
	``I needed about 12 more inches of racetrack,'' Stewart said.  
``Unfortunately, I just ran out of racetrack and hit the wall.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The car was not badly damaged, but Stewart was upset.  
</P>
<P>
	``I just made a stupid mistake,'' he said. ``I'm disgusted with  
myself. They pay me to drive a race car, and I take these things to 
heart. Thankfully, it wasn't too bad. 
</P>
<P>
	``Knock on wood, we haven't had an engine problem of any kind  
yet, and I've had more fun so far this week, and the most relaxing 
week leading up to qualifying that I've ever had at Indy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ray is having fun, too, except when he is asked about replacing  
Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm tired of hearing his name,'' Ray said earlier in the week.  
``I have a lot of respect for Tony's ability, but I just don't want 
to answer any more questions about him. He's Tony Stewart and I'm 
Greg Ray, and I want to concentrate on my team and my effort.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The only problem is the head-to-head duel on Saturday could be  
short-circuited if Stewart gets a late draw in the qualifying order 
or if the weather turns wet. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because Stewart is committed to drive Saturday night in  
The Winston, a NASCAR all-star event at Lowe's Motor Speedway in 
Concord, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	To make it in time, Stewart must leave Indianapolis no later  
than 1:30 p.m., local time. Concord's time is an hour later. 
</P>
<P>
	Qualifying is scheduled to begin here at 11 a.m., but the early  
weather forecast is calling for possible morning rain. 
</P>
<P>
	``That would mean we'd have to qualify on Sunday, but the most  
important thing is to make the race. I've won the pole,'' said 
Stewart, who has started first, second and fourth in his three 
previous Indy races. ``I want to win the race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Race day will be a long haul for Stewart, who is scheduled to  
fly to Concord immediately after the 500 to race in NASCAR's 
Coca-Cola 600. The only other driver to pull off that double is 
current Winston Cup regular John Andretti, who finished 10th in the 
1994 Indy 500 and then crashed out of the 600. 
</P>
<P>
	In Thursday's practice, Robby Unser, last year's top Indy  
rookie, jumped to fourth overall at 225.079. 
</P>
<P>
	Other fast drivers on Thursday included two-time Indianapolis  
champion Arie Luyendyk, retiring following the May 30 race, at 
225.073; Stephan Gregoire at 224.792, 1996 Indy winner Buddy Lazier 
at 224.361 and defending champion Eddie Cheever Jr. at 224.193. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnny Unser, Robby's cousin, also crashed in practice Thursday,  
spinning in turn 3 and hitting the wall twice. He also escaped 
injury. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
