<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GM Plant To Be in Baltimore County </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WHITE MARSH, Md. (AP) -- General Motors announced Thursday it  
chose a site in Baltimore County for its new $250 million 
transmissions plant. 
</P>
<P>
	Allison Transmission, a subsidiary of the world's largest  
automaker, plans to build the 400,000 square foot plant on the 
65-acre site of a former gravel quarry here. 
</P>
<P>
	``This location is especially good for us since it is near a  
good work force, a major highway and a port,'' said Allison 
President Dan Hancock. 
</P>
<P>
	Construction could begin this summer but won't be completed for  
about a year, said Richard C. Mike Lewin, Maryland's secretary of 
business and economic development. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant initially will employ about 300 workers now employed  
at GM's Broening Highway plant in Baltimore City, Lewin said. 
Though no new jobs will be created, the new plant will ensure that 
500 autoworkers remain in the area. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think our strong suit is our workers,'' Lewin said. ``They  
could have taken this plant anywhere in the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland sweetened the deal by extending financial incentives to  
Allison. State officials declined to release details, but WBAL-TV 
reported that GM will receive over $1 million in tax credits during 
the next five years. 
</P>
<P>
	The state also will plug $8 million to $10 million into local  
highways used to access the plant. The state would be willing to 
help with extensive improvements to the plant's infrastructure to 
keep it open, Lewin said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the first heavy manufacturing plant to be built in  
Maryland in 30 years,'' Gov. Parris Glendening said, standing on 
the future site of the plant. 
</P>
<P>
	GM, based in Detroit, has said it needs a new plant to meet the  
demand for the 1000 series Allison automatic transmissions, which 
are sold to makers of full-size pickup trucks. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
