<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Rules for Souvenir Baseballs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Worried about ``wild scrambles'' in the stands,  
Major League Baseball is asking its players to be a little more 
careful with its souvenirs. 
</P>
<P>
	Players, coaches and managers have been reminded this year not  
to toss balls into the stands. Instead, they have been told simply 
to hand the souvenir to fans. 
</P>
<P>
	The policy is not new, said baseball spokesman Pat Courtney.  
Although a memo has been sent to all 30 ballclubs, a notice has 
been posted in clubhouses about the policy for at least 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball decided to reiterate the policy after watching fans  
climb over each other trying to get one of slugger Mark McGwire's 
home run balls last year during his record-breaking season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a safety thing,'' Courtney said. ``We just don't want any  
wild scrambles or melees up in the stands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many players routinely toss baseballs into the stands after the  
final out of an inning or after chasing down a foul. Officials can 
do nothing about the scramble for balls into the stands after home 
runs or fouls, but it is trying to maintain control at other times. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want to discourage players from giving away balls,''  
Courtney said. ``It's fine if they want to do that. Just go hand it 
to someone, instead of throwing it into the stands.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
