<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FEC May Allow Credit-Card Donations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Presidential campaigns that use the Internet  
to raise funds got a big lift when the Federal Election Commission 
took the first step toward approving federal matching dollars for 
credit card donations to candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	All the major presidential campaigns have Web sites that include  
fund-raising sections. The easiest way for donors to contribute is 
via credit card, but existing FEC regulations expressly forbid 
candidates from collecting federal matching funds on those 
donations. 
</P>
<P>
	The FEC tentatively approved a plan Thursday that would allow  
presidential campaigns to begin collecting credit card donations in 
anticipation of receiving matching funds for them on Jan. 1, 2000, 
the same time that they will get federal dollars for other eligible 
donations. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the commission -- which is made up of six members split  
evenly along party lines -- did not vote, members indicated that as 
soon as some details regarding the security and documentation of 
donations are resolved, the regulations would be changed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The FEC is going to take the legal steps to make these funds  
matchable,'' said Scott Thomas, the commission chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission acted in response to a formal request made by  
Democratic presidential hopeful Bill Bradley's campaign in March. 
</P>
<P>
	All five of the commission members at the meeting indicated that  
they would vote to pass the regulation in some form, but they left 
the decision to a written vote by each of the six commission 
members within the next 72 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	``The clear indication is that the commission wants to do  
this,'' said David Mason, a Republican FEC member. ``It's just the 
details that need to be worked out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barring disapproval from the Congress or the president, the new  
regulations would take effect in a few months. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan calls for the campaigns to maintain security procedures  
-- the details of which are still to be worked out -- to avoid 
illegal donations via corporate credit cards or from foreigners. 
</P>
<P>
	Many members of the commission stressed, however, that it would  
be unfair to place more restrictions on credit card donations than 
more traditional forms like checks or money orders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
