<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thomson To Lead International Golf  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- Five months ago in Australia, Peter  
Thomson held up the Presidents Cup trophy as captain of the 
International team and called it the crowning achievement of a 
career that includes five British Open titles. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, he agreed to return as captain in 2000 for a chance  
to beat the Americans on their own turf. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm looking forward to this, I'm thrilled,'' Thomson told The  
Associated Press from Malaysia. ``It will be huge if we win. It 
means the International team will be the top dog, bigger than 
Europe -- and bigger than the U.S.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Royal Melbourne Golf Club in December, Thomson brought  
together 12 players from seven countries under one fabricated flag 
and handed the Americans their worst loss ever in match play, 
20 1/2-11 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	``The United States players will be determined to erase the  
disappointment of Royal Melbourne,'' he said. ``However equally, 
the International team vividly remembers the joy of victory and 
would dearly cherish a successful defense on the Americans' soil.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Presidents Cup, patterned after the Ryder Cup to give  
foreign players born outside Europe a chance to compete, began in 
1994 and resulted in two U.S. victories at the Robert Trent Jones 
Golf Club in Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	After the U.S. failure in Australia, the 2000 matches return to  
Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said the Melbourne event was the highlight of my career,''  
Thomson said. ``This will be a test for the team. If the team can 
win in the U.S., we're on top of the pile.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The PGA Tour announced last week that Ken Venturi, the CBS  
Sports golf analyst and 1964 U.S. Open champion, would be the 
American captain. 
</P>
<P>
	``I applaud that,'' Thomson said. ``The U.S. could not have  
picked a better man.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jack Nicklaus was the U.S. captain at Melbourne and had what  
Thomson called during opening ceremonies the ``greatest collection 
of golfers in the world,'' from young stars such as David Duval and 
Tiger Woods to the experience of Fred Couples and Davis Love III. 
</P>
<P>
	But the International team, inspired by an emotional team  
meeting led by Thomson after its 1996 loss in Virginia, rolled to 
such a huge lead that it only needed to win two of the 12 singles 
matches on Sunday to take the cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Already this year, five players from that team have won on the  
PGA Tour -- Steve Elkington, Vijay Singh, Stuart Appleby, Ernie Els 
and Carlos Franco. 
</P>
<P>
	``They got a lift of confidence,'' Thomson said. ``I'm not  
surprised because they're all good players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The International team is determined by the world rankings,  
although Thomson said he expects the same core of his winning team 
in 2000 -- Elkington, Greg Norman, Els and Nick Price. 
</P>
<P>
	That he will be captain is a small surprise. Thomson suggested  
during the beer-spraying celebration at Royal Melbourne that it was 
time to give someone else a chance. 
</P>
<P>
	PGA Tour commissioner Tim Finchem has spent the past few weeks  
polling international players, and Thomson was the choice. Gary 
Player also was considered, and he is likely to be the leading 
candidate should the Presidents Cup move to South Africa in 2002, 
as expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``I certainly didn't plan on this,'' Thomson said. ``But I said  
that if the team wanted me, then I would.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
