<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Top Banks Report Big Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's top banks reported heavy losses for the  
latest fiscal year due largely to writing off problem loans to 
comply with new, more stringent rules for classifying loans. 
</P>
<P>
	The major commercial lenders indicated Friday they would earn a  
profit by the end of the current business year. 
</P>
<P>
	Top-ranked Tokyo-Mitsubishi Bank Ltd., the only major commercial  
bank which has not taken part in a taxpayer-financed bailout of the 
industry, posted a consolidated net loss of 86.90 billion yen, or 
$701 million, for the fiscal year ended March 31 compared with a 
net loss of 524.36 billion yen a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	It said its parent company problem loans total 2.16 trillion  
yen, or $17.42 billion -- up from 1.86 trillion yen last September. 
</P>
<P>
	The higher figure was due in part to revamped disclosure  
standards prompted by the banking sector's recent woes. Problem 
loans include those extended to bankrupt borrowers, companies in 
danger of failing and loans on which payments have been missed or 
which have been restructured. 
</P>
<P>
	Under previous accounting standards, Tokyo-Mitsubishi's problem  
loans would have totaled 2.08 trillion yen. It wrote off 843.9 
billion yen worth of these loans in the past fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	It forecast a group net profit of 140 billion yen for the  
current fiscal year, which ends in March 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd. posted a consolidated net loss of  
445.29 billion yen, or $3.59 billion, compared with a loss of 72.02 
billion yen the previous year. It expects a group net profit of 130 
billion yen this fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	It reported problem loans at its parent company amounting to  
2.25 trillion yen, or $18.15 billion, under the new accounting 
rules, up from 1.47 trillion yen a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank disposed of 856.48 billion yen in problem loans with  
the roughly 900 billion yen in public funds it received as part of 
25 trillion yen the government earmarked to prop up the banking 
industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Asahi Bank Ltd., Fuji Bank Ltd., Sanwa Bank Ltd., Sakura Bank  
Ltd., Sumitomo Bank Ltd. and Tokai Bank Ltd. also all reported 
large group net losses for fiscal 1998, reflecting their stepped up 
efforts to write off bad loans using government funds. 
</P>
<P>
	But each of the banks projected posting a net profit this fiscal  
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's banks have been struggling to deal with loans which have  
soured amid the country's worst recession since World War II. Many 
of these loans were extended in the late 1980s to finance 
speculative land deals before a collapse in real estate prices at 
the outset of this decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Parliament approved a scheme in October to inject new capital  
into banks to cover bad loan write-offs. Two major banks which had 
become insolvent largely as a result of problem loans were 
nationalized late last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
