<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> INS Rule Helps Central Americans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Immigration procedures will be eased for more  
than a quarter-million Salvadorans and Guatemalans seeking legal 
U.S. residency after entering the nation illegally. 
</P>
<P>
	Such individuals, most of whom came to the United States after  
fleeing civil wars in their homelands during the 1980s, will be 
allowed to apply for relief from deportation through a simplified 
procedure. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a new rule announced Thursday by the Immigration and  
Naturalization Service, the immigrants will be exempt from having 
to prove they would suffer ``extreme hardships'' if they were sent 
back to their homelands -- a key test of eligibility. They also will 
have their cases overseen by INS asylum officers, rather than 
immigration judges. 
</P>
<P>
	About 10,000 Eastern Europeans also will be affected by the  
procedure. 
</P>
<P>
	``Consistent with the commitment President Clinton made when he  
visited Central America in March, the new program is the 
culmination of the administration's efforts to create as accessible 
and straightforward a process as the law permits,'' INS 
Commissioner Doris Meissner said. 
</P>
<P>
	The rule is expected to affect 290,000 Central Americans,  
including 240,000 Salvadorans and Guatemalans. It is to take effect 
June 21 after a public comment period. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, Congress passed a law that granted amnesty to some  
Nicaraguans and Cubans in the United States and allowed them to 
apply for status as legal permanent residents. 
</P>
<P>
	The law was intended to help the thousands of Central Americans  
who illegally entered the United States after fleeing civil wars in 
their homelands during the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the law, Guatemalans and Salvadorans who qualify would be  
considered for a suspension of deportation under the less stringent 
rules that existed before the 1996 immigration legislation, but on 
a case-by-case basis, requiring them to prove ``extreme hardship'' 
if they were returned to their home countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, chairman of the House Judiciary  
subcommittee on immigration and claims, criticized the rule change, 
saying it was ``not what Congress intended.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Amnesty rewards those who break the law and encourages more  
illegal immigration. It is a slap in the face to all those who 
patiently waited their turn to come to the U.S.,'' Smith said in a 
statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
