<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Team Finds Kosovo Quiet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UROSEVAC, Yugoslavia (AP) -- At first glance, the village, once  
home to about 1,000 ethnic Albanians, seemed normal. Chickens 
wandered around intact houses, cows grazed in the fields. But the 
houses were abandoned, the workshops and barns deserted -- the 
village was empty and looted. 
</P>
<P>
	For the visiting U.N. team, this was ``silent confirmation'' of  
the ethnic conflict that has driven about 800,000 Kosovo Albanians 
into exile in neighboring countries. 
</P>
<P>
	The team found the village, Muhadzeri Babuc, almost by chance as  
it traveled the road to Urosevac. The team was on its first full 
day Friday touring Kosovo to assess the humanitarian needs of the 
province, where refugees have said Serb forces waged a brutal 
campaign to expel the ethnic Albanian majority. 
</P>
<P>
	The tour provides the United Nations with the first  
on-the-ground look at Kosovo since international observers and 
virtually all foreign aid workers fled the province shortly before 
NATO launched its air campaign March 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Several times during the day, U.N. mission head Sergio de Mello  
tried to visit villages off the main roads. His Yugoslav hosts 
refused. It was unsafe to stray off the road, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, de Mello insisted. He stopped the convoy and  
proceeded into the settlement to see it for himself. 
</P>
<P>
	The houses, he found, were abandoned. Workshops and barns  
deserted. Floors of the brick homes were littered with clothes, 
bedding and household items. 
</P>
<P>
	``Silent confirmation,'' de Mello muttered.  
</P>
<P>
	Much of Kosovo appears empty. Those still there only reinforce  
the picture of a mass exodus by ethnic Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	At the mosque in Kacanik, the team found three elderly brothers  
who stayed behind when their family fled from the chaos in Kosovo, 
heading for the nearby Macedonian border. 
</P>
<P>
	Imer Caca said he could have gone -- but at the same time he  
couldn't. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were afraid,'' he said of his family. ``There was  
shooting day and night. I would have left -- but I have to take care 
of my brothers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His brothers Rufki and Nuhi are diabetic. Rufki's right leg was  
amputated several years ago; Nuhi has lost both of his. They 
couldn't have survived alone. 
</P>
<P>
	The brothers, along with an elderly neighbor, found refuge in  
Kacanik, where townspeople laid mattresses in the mosque for them 
and bring them food. 
</P>
<P>
	It's better than their empty village. But many of Kacanik's  
people have fled, too. 
</P>
<P>
	In an abandoned, looted apartment, a pot of tea still stands on  
a table, testament to the haste with which its inhabitants left. 
</P>
<P>
	The floors are strewn with the debris of a family's life:  
clothes, dishes, toys, a photo album. 
</P>
<P>
	A look inside shows what that life was once like: new babies,  
family outings, a village wedding, a vacation abroad. Now they have 
all gone -- somewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Macedonian border town of Djeneral Jankovic, the team saw  
hundreds of tractors and wagons abandoned by fleeing ethnic 
Albanians. The wagons were packed with blankets, mattresses, 
cradles, rugs and household goods and covered in plastic sheeting. 
A lonely donkey brayed wildly among the abandoned vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Several thousand Kosovo Albanians were trapped there for several  
days when Macedonia closed its border. And when the border 
reopened, the refugees had to cross on foot, leaving their 
belongings behind, parked at a huge cement plant near the border 
post. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials assured the U.N. team that the vehicles were being  
protected so their owners could reclaim them when they return. 
</P>
<P>
	In Urosevac, the liveliest town visited by the team, the  
delegation found Kosovo Albanians who had tried to leave for 
Macedonia but had been turned back at the train station by Serb 
police. 
</P>
<P>
	``They said: 'Go back!' I don't know why,'' said one young man  
who spoke a little English. Asked why he wanted to leave Kosovo, he 
said he was afraid of the army and police. 
</P>
<P>
	In Urosevac, an ethnically mixed city, the scene was one of  
seeming normalcy amid signs of tension. 
</P>
<P>
	Old men in dark berets lined up to collect their pensions from  
government offices. Young people thronged the streets. Shops were 
open, but not well-stocked. 
</P>
<P>
	On the edge of town, however, burned homes and shops spoke  
silently of the violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
