<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Publisher Pulls Hit Man Guide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Two families who claimed a hit man followed a  
how-to manual published by Paladin Press in the killings of their 
loved ones are getting millions of dollars and a promise to stop 
selling the book, their lawyer said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boulder, Colo., publisher agreed Friday to stop selling  
``Hit Man: A Technical Manual for Independent Contractors,'' said 
lawyer John Marshall. The book has sold more than 13,000 copies 
since it was first published in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal lawsuit, scheduled to go to trial next week, was  
filed by the family of Mildred Horn and her 8-year-old son Trevor, 
and the family of nurse Janice Saunders. It accused Paladin Press 
of providing James Perry with a 130-page blueprint for murder. 
</P>
<P>
	Perry was convicted of killing the Silver Spring mother, her  
quadriplegic son and Ms. Saunders in 1993, a year after ordering 
the book. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a multi-million dollar settlement in which Paladin has  
agreed, in addition, to make donations to two charities,'' said 
Marshall. ``They have agreed to remove `Hit Man' from their 
catalogue and to cease publication.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides agreed not to disclose the exact amount of the  
settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	Paladin lawyer Lee Levine said concerns over school violence  
stemming from last month's murders in Littleton, Colo. and this 
week's shootings in Conyers, Ga., could have made it harder to get 
the jury to listen to their side. 
</P>
<P>
	``This case is about whether or not there is a clear and  
convincing case that this book in any sense known to our law caused 
these murders,'' or substantially helped Perry to commit them, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hit Man'' offers tips for deadly effectiveness, such as  
shooting victims in the head. Ms. Horn and Ms. Saunders were shot 
in the eye. Trevor's breathing tube was disconnected. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawrence Horn, Ms. Horn's ex-husband, was convicted of hiring  
Perry so he could inherit the $1.7 million estate his son won from 
a medical malpractice suit. 
</P>
<P>
	At Perry's trial in 1995, prosecutors listed 22 connections  
between Perry's actions and the book's instructions. Paladin 
countered that there were few similarities and that Perry learned 
what he knew from growing up in a tough Detroit neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	The 13,500-member Society of Professional Journalists filed a  
court brief in support of Paladin Press, saying the suit threatens 
the right of free speech, said President Wendy S. Myers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately, the timing for the suit is difficult given our  
recent experience with the Littleton, Colo., shooting,'' she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
