<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Moment of Truth for Indy 500 Pole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Greg Ray wants to leave Indianapolis Motor  
Speedway tomorrow as the pole winner for the Indianapolis 500. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what we've been here working on all week,'' said Ray,  
who has been the fastest driver on the 2 1/2-mile oval all but one day 
since practice opened last Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	His fastest lap so far, 227.192 mph, came Thursday during the  
final hour, often referred to as ``Happy Hour'' because weather 
conditions are generally conducive to speed with cooling 
temperatures and winds often dying down. 
</P>
<P>
	But Ray backed it up Friday with a lap of 227.175 mph shortly  
after the track opened for practice at 11 a.m. -- the same time that 
the first of two days of time trials was scheduled to begin on 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The qualifying on Saturday and Sunday will determine the 33-car  
starting lineup for the 83rd Indy on May 30. 
</P>
<P>
	``It really hasn't mattered what time of day we go out,'' Ray  
said. ``These guys at Team Menard have given me a fast car in just 
about any condition. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no guarantees, but we're feeling pretty good right  
now,'' he said. ``I'll be disappointed if we don't get the job 
done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, Ray can't take anything for granted -- not with  
challengers like Tony Stewart, the driver he replaced at Team 
Menard, and Arie Luyendyk close enough to get his attention. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, who had to miss all of Friday's final full day of  
practice to practice and qualify for Saturday night's NASCAR 
Winston Open in Concord, N.C., was the only driver to beat Ray for 
the day's best speed on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The hottest of the current Winston Cup rookies, driving for Joe  
Gibbs Racing, turned a lap of 226.683 mph to top that day's speed 
chart. 
</P>
<P>
	Not even an embarrassing brush with the speedway wall late in  
Thursday's practice could stifle his enthusiasm. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just need to get a break with the draw and the weather,''  
Stewart said. ``If we get the chance to run on Saturday, we'll be 
right there. If not, we'll qualify Sunday. Either way, the main 
thing is to win the race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The forecast for Saturday was calling for a 60 percent chance of  
morning rain, with afternoon clearing. A delay would cause big 
problems for Stewart, who must leave Indy by 1:30 p.m. to get to 
Concord for the stock car race. 
</P>
<P>
	The other part of the equation was the draw for positions in the  
qualifying line, which was to be conducted following the end of 
practice Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Curry, co-owner of the team, pumped his fist in the air  
after drawing position No. 2 for the team's primary car and No. 17 
for Stewart's backup. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now we just need the weather to cooperate,'' Curry said.  
</P>
<P>
	Luyendyk, who won Indy poles in 1993 and 1997 and won the  
500-mile race in 1990 and '97, has been just close enough to Ray 
and Stewart to be optimistic about his chances of winning another 
pole. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Greg Ray has to be the favorite,'' said Luyendyk, who  
will retire from the cockpit following the race. ``He's been able 
to run 226 on his own. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been able to run 225 on my own,'' added Luyendyk,  
referring to running without the help of the draft from other cars 
on the track. ``The key is going to be the conditions when you go 
out. This place is tougher than anywhere to gauge because even a 
small temperature change or wind change can make a huge 
difference.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Luyendyk was right behind Ray in Friday's practice, turning his  
fast lap of the week at 226.131 -- the third fastest overall. Next 
was Luyendyk's Treadway Racing teammate Sam Schmidt at 225.468, 
followed by Scott Sharp at 224.792, defending Indy Racing League 
champion Kenny Brack at 224.087 and A.J. Foyt Racing teammate and 
last year's pole-winner Billy Boat at 223.847. 
</P>
<P>
	Two more crashes on Friday brought the total since practice  
began to 11. 
</P>
<P>
	Rookie Mike Borkowski, who also crashed Monday, and John Paul  
Jr. both hit the wall. Borkowski escaped injury, but Paul was 
admitted to Methodist Hospital with a severe back contusion and a 
back sprain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
