<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 11:31:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Police: Teen Brought Guns From Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- The teen-age suspect accused of opening fire  
on classmates, wounding six of them, got his guns from a locked 
cabinet in his home and concealed the rifle he took to school in a 
pants leg, the sheriff said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Rockdale County Sheriff Jeff Wigington also said that  
investigators seized a videotape from a surveillance camera in the 
area where the shootings happened. They had not watched it as of 
this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	On the day Heritage High seniors were looking forward to picking  
up their yearbooks, their suburban community became the new focus 
for a nation on edge after months of fear and concern about 
violence in America's schools. 
</P>
<P>
	Six students were wounded in Thursday morning's attack, none  
critically. Two of the six were treated at a hospital and released 
Thursday. Two others were released today -- including a boy who said 
the shooter laughed during the attack -- while the other two, both 
girls, remained hospitalized. 
</P>
<P>
	The attack was the sixth mass shooting at an American high  
school or middle school since October 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspect, a 15-year-old sophomore friends said was upset over  
a failed romance, dropped to his knees and pointed the gun at his 
mouth after the shootings, witnesses said. A short time later, he 
aimed the gun at an assistant principal, then surrendered with a 
tearful: ``Oh, my God, I'm so scared!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wigington said today that the suspect broke into a locked gun  
cabinet in his family's basement to get the two weapons, a rifle 
and a .357 Magnum. He wouldn't say how the cabinet was broken in to 
but said it wasn't just unlocked. Wigington said he didn't know 
whether the boy's parents were aware the guns had been taken. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspect fired 14 shots, 11 of them from the rifle and three  
from the Magnum revolver, according to a preliminary investigation. 
No bullets from the revolver hit anyone, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wigington said the boy concealed the rifle in the leg of his  
jeans and the revolver in a book bag. He gave no details. 
</P>
<P>
	``Apparently he was shooting at the hip. Basically, he was not  
aiming the rifle at one particular person,'' Wigington said. 
</P>
<P>
	Friends identified the gunman as Thomas Solomon Jr., nicknamed  
T.J. He was charged with aggravated assault, and other charges were 
being considered. Solomon must appear in juvenile court before he 
can be charged as an adult, something not expected before Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was in there laughing, jumping up and down,'' student Jason  
Cheek, who was wounded in the leg, said today as he left the 
hospital. ``He kind of had a natural high, pulling the trigger ... 
like it was some kind of game to him. He didn't seem like anybody 
that was angry to me. He just, he looked like he was just having a 
good time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the shooting, Assistant Principal Cecil Brinkley followed  
the student outside toward the football field and asked the suspect 
to hand over the handgun, which at that point was raised at 
Brinkley. 
</P>
<P>
	``I stepped back a couple of steps and I turned to him again and  
I said, 'Give me the gun,' and I said again, 'Give me the gun,''' 
Brinkley said today. ``I saw him lower the barrel of the gun and I 
kept getting closer and closer to him. Then I held out my hands and 
he laid the gun in my hands. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then he gave me a real big bear hug and he said, 'I'm scared,  
I'm scared,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Classes were canceled today, though students were expected to  
return to Heritage High on Monday. School officials said graduation 
would go on as scheduled next Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	This morning, students streamed into Heritage Hills Baptist  
Church near the school to meet with counselors and ministers. Some 
teens hugged in the parking lot before going inside. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're just all trying to get our lives back,'' said  
senior Brian Skelton, 18, on his way in. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton received word of Thursday's shooting before he  
left for Littleton, Colo., for the one-month anniversary of the 
deaths of 15 people at Columbine High School. 
</P>
<P>
	The news ``is deeply troubling to me, as it is to all  
Americans,'' Clinton said. As he spoke, the U.S. Senate was 
approving a proposal requiring background checks for all 
transactions at gun shows and for anyone seeking to reclaim a 
weapon at a pawn shop. 
</P>
<P>
	The shootings came before the first bell sounded, when students  
in the commons area were gabbing and munching breakfast. It was the 
last day of class for the seniors. 
</P>
<P>
	When the loud pops sounded out, some figured it was a prank --  
maybe firecrackers -- until they heard shouts of ``he's got a gun!'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I walked into the commons area and heard the pops,'' said  
Michael Mellitto, an 18-year-old junior. ``I thought, `Ha, ha, very 
funny!' Then these girls come running past me, crying, saying, `I 
can't believe they shot him!' '' 
</P>
<P>
	In their panic, hundreds of crying teens jammed through doors to  
escape, some yanking up fallen friends, others jumping over them. 
One girl, lying on the floor, screamed ``I'm shot!'' and begged for 
her mother. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of these same students and parents had watched television  
coverage of the Littleton shooting a month ago. That horror lasted 
for hours; the assault here was over in minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``You, like, watch it on TV and it's not your school and it's  
not like this,'' said Scottie Sanders, an 11th-grader struggling to 
reconstruct the morning's events. ``It was like a blur.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Heritage, 20 miles east of Atlanta, is a mostly white, suburban  
school, like Columbine High. About 80 percent of graduates go on to 
college. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before the massacre in Colorado, Heritage had an armed  
sheriff's deputy on duty during school hours. Wigington said the 
attack happened before the deputy had arrived. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Dunn, a sophomore, said he had seen ``lots of guns'' at  
the suspect's home. Solomon was described as quiet, and several 
students said his grades had slipped lately and he had been heard 
making ambiguous comments about shooting someone. One said he 
didn't take Solomon seriously. 
</P>
<P>
	Nathaniel Deeter, 15, a friend of the gunman, said Solomon was  
depressed after a girlfriend broke off their relationship this 
week. He was there as the attack began. 
</P>
<P>
	``I yelled to him, `Hey, what're you doing?' But he just kept  
shooting. And then the kid next to me got shot in the foot. Then I 
started to run,'' Deeter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Seventeen-year-old Drake Hoy tried to run, too, but realized  
something was wrong with his foot: ``I took off my boot and there 
was blood and stuff everywhere.'' He was treated for minor wounds 
and released Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Inside a closet, teacher Carol Ingle recited Bible verses to  
calm terrified students she had gathered there. One of them, 
freshman Stephanie Edwards, said: ``She told us it would be all 
right.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
