<DOCNO> APW19990521.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 12:32:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cyclists Protest Renewed Blood Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FOGGIA, Italy (AP) -- Some of cycling's top riders on Friday  
threatened to withdraw from the Tour of Italy if further drug tests 
are demanded by Italian sports authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	Blood tests were performed on three teams by Italy's Olympic  
Committee before the start of Friday's seventh stage. The 
International Cycling Union conducted tests at the start of the 
race May 16. 
</P>
<P>
	Defending Giro champion Marco Pantani, Giro leader Laurent  
Jalabert and world road champion Oscar Camenzind contend the tests 
are unnecessary. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was an evident lack of respect for the cyclists. ... The  
next time we are ready to stop the race and return home ... most 
cyclists are ready to join the protest,'' Pantani said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pantani won the Giro and Tour of France last year.  
</P>
<P>
	``We are not criminals ... we already undergo antidoping urine  
tests every morning,'' he said. ``It looks like a political move in 
occasion of Italy's most prestigious race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pantani and other cyclists said they do not oppose the drug  
tests by their governing organization, but they object to the 
duplicate tests. 
</P>
<P>
	Directors of the teams Mobilvetta, Ballan and Cantine Tollo,  
whose cyclists were tested Friday, also lamented the method used by 
doctors hours before the stage from Foggia to Lanciano. 
</P>
<P>
	Two unheralded cyclists, Nicola Loda and Javier Ochoa Palacios,  
were banned from the Giro and did not start last Saturday because 
their tests showed unusually high levels of red blood cells. 
</P>
<P>
	High red blood cell count can be a sign of use of EPO, a banned  
substance. But the high count can also occur naturally. 
</P>
<P>
	Pasquale Bellotti, secretary of Olympic panel, said he could not  
understand the protests by the cyclists. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today's tests were part of the campaign to safeguard the  
cyclists' health,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 16:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Gandhi's Party Set For Split </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- A former Congress party politician who  
was thrown out of the party for challenging Sonia Gandhi right to 
run for prime minister said Friday he would form a rival party to 
contest India's upcoming elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharad Pawar, a party boss from the western state of  
Maharashtra, and two others were expelled after demanding a 
constitutional amendment to bar foreign-born citizens from becoming 
prime minister. The Italian-born Mrs. Gandhi resigned as party 
president after the proposal was made, creating chaos in the 
Congress leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	Once India's dominant party, Congress led India for 45 of its 52  
years as an independent nation, and was just beginning to recover 
from defeats in the previous two elections, in 1996 and 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Pawar said he would found a new party after a meeting Saturday  
with the other two expelled party members, Purno Sangma and Tariq 
Anwar. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will take a decision on a viable alternate platform within  
the next couple of days,'' Pawar told The Associated Press in a 
telephone interview from Pune, 100 miles south of Bombay, India's 
financial hub and his base. 
</P>
<P>
	``This alternative will be based on the ideology of the Congress  
party,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pawar and his allies will likely court defectors from the  
Congress and ally with other regional groups that could play a 
crucial role in the formation of the next government, expected to 
be another coalition since no single party is expected to dominate 
the parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gandhi maintained her public silence, refusing to respond  
to party leaders and hundreds of supporters who have camped outside 
her New Delhi home, pleading with her to reconsider her 
resignation. 
</P>
<P>
	She canceled all public engagements Friday, the eighth  
anniversary of the assassination of her husband and former Prime 
Minister Rajiv Gandhi, including two rallies that had been planned 
to kick off the party's election campaign. She did attend a private 
morning prayer meeting at her husband's memorial, where she and her 
two children spread handfuls of jasmine petals on the tomb. 
</P>
<P>
	India's Parliament was dissolved last month after Prime Minister  
Atal Bihari Vajpayee's government was dislodged in a no-confidence 
vote and opposition groups failed to put together a new ruling 
coalition. Elections are set for September-October. 
</P>
<P>
	A split, just four months before national elections, would set  
back Congress' hopes to return to power. But the Congress shrugged 
off the political costs of the expulsions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think Pawar is getting much response,'' Congress  
spokesman Ajit Jogi said in New Delhi. ``Some people will break 
away, but you can't call it a split.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 16:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
