<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fed Money Going To Magnetic Trains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Proposals for high-speed magnetic levitation  
trains from Baltimore, Pittsburgh and Atlanta will be among the 
seven projects sharing $12 million for further studies, an official 
said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcements will be made by Transportation Secretary  
Rodney Slater in Baltimore on Monday. Following the studies, one of 
the seven ``maglev'' projects will be picked for development and 
construction. 
</P>
<P>
	Maglev systems, already being tested in Germany and Japan, use  
electromagnets to lift the train above ground and free it of 
speed-reducing friction. Such trains can travel up to 310 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	A Federal Railroad Administration official, speaking on  
condition of anonymity, identified three of the selected projects: 
</P>
<P>
	--A 40-mile system linking Baltimore and its airport with the  
main train station in Washington, D.C. The trip could take 16 
minutes, compared with 40 to 50 minutes by conventional rail. 
</P>
<P>
	--A 45-mile system linking Pittsburgh's airport in suburban  
Coraopolis with the city of Pittsburgh and its eastern suburbs. 
Proponents eventually want to extend the system to Philadelphia, 
creating a two-hour Pittsburgh-Philadelphia trip that now takes 
eight hours on Amtrak. 
</P>
<P>
	--A 40-mile portion of the 110-mile Interstate 75 corridor  
between Atlanta and Chattanooga, Tenn. The system was proposed by 
Atlanta officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 02:51:29 </DATE_TIME>
