<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bad Weather Hampers McKinley Rescue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- Low on supplies and lashed by strong  
winds, three British mountaineers were stranded near the top of 
North America's highest peak early today as foul weather hampered 
efforts to rescue them. 
</P>
<P>
	The trio had hoped to make quick dash to the summit of Mount  
McKinley, but that gamble failed. 
</P>
<P>
	The three men, one of them too injured to travel, were pinned  
down at 19,000 feet on McKinley's challenging West Rib route. 
</P>
<P>
	Rescuers have had limited radio contact with the climbers,  
either because of transmission problems or dying batteries, 
National Park Service spokeswoman Jane Tranel said. They radioed 
for help early Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The names of the men were not released.  
</P>
<P>
	Tranel said they were traveling with little gear, apparently to  
make a quick trip to the 20,320-foot summit and back down to a camp 
at 15,700 feet. 
</P>
<P>
	The men were low on food and other supplies in an area without  
much protection from McKinley's notorious winds, which Tranel said 
were blowing up to 50 mph. The temperature was expected to dip to 
minus-30 degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	Poor visibility has made rescue by helicopter untenable so far,  
Tranel said, but a high-altitude helicopter was ready to fly if 
visibility improved near the summit. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Weather Service was forecasting partly cloudy  
conditions today, Tranel said, so an aerial rescue attempt was 
considered possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
