<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 12:32:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate OKs Local TV for Satellites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Local television news, weather and sports  
broadcasts would be available on satellite TV systems just as they 
are on cable under bills passed by the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	The two bills, approved by voice votes Thursday evening, would  
let DirecTV, EchoStar and other companies beam local broadcast 
signals to customers who use either pizza-sized satellite dishes or 
big ``backyard'' dishes no matter where they live. Under existing 
law, companies are barred from doing this. 
</P>
<P>
	A final bill could be enacted before June 30, Sen. Patrick  
Leahy, D-Vt., who helped write one of the Senate-passed measures, 
said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Some satellite customers who are illegally receiving distant  
network affiliates via satellite are supposed to be cut off from 
ABC, CBS, NBC and Fox signals on June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Both bills, however, would delay those cutoffs for customers who  
live on the fringes of their local stations' coverage areas. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'd like to have'' the final bill ``done before then so we  
don't have the `Perils of Pauline' aspect,'' said Leahy, the Senate 
Judiciary Committee's top Democrat. 
</P>
<P>
	The bills -- one originating in the Senate, the other passed by  
the House last month -- are slightly different and will be 
reconciled in a conference of House and Senate lawmakers. Each 
chamber will then vote on the product of that conference and, if it 
passes, send it to the president. 
</P>
<P>
	The measures are intended to resolve a dispute between satellite  
companies and broadcasters over conditions under which viewers who 
get their television from satellite can watch broadcast TV 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the bills, satellite TV customers wouldn't be forced to  
use rooftop antennas or subscribe to cable TV to receive local 
broadcast signals. They would be able to get them directly from a 
satellite company, probably for a small monthly fee. Eventually, 
the companies would have to carry all local broadcast stations in a 
given market. 
</P>
<P>
	The satellite and broadcast industries generally support the  
legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Both bills also would permit eligible satellite customers to  
continue receiving broadcast network programs from ``distant'' 
network affiliates as long as they satisfy certain conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Existing law lets satellite companies provide customers with  
``distant'' network signals, those from other broadcast areas, only 
if those customers cannot receive local stations using rooftop 
antennas. The current law doesn't take into account quality of 
local reception. 
</P>
<P>
	The satellite and broadcasting industries have been at odds for  
years over how to interpret the arcane legal test that determines 
when a satellite customer can't get a local signal and thus is 
eligible to receive network programs by satellite. The bills would 
make some changes aimed at making it easier for satellite customers 
who get a poor local TV signal to be able to receive network 
signals on their satellite systems. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bills are H.R. 1554 and S 247.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 14:52:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
