<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Struggles To Maintain Unity  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration and its NATO  
partners struggled today to patch up differences over Kosovo while 
portraying Belgrade and its military as cracking after 59 days of 
airstrikes. British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said London and 
Washington are in harmony on Kosovo strategy. The calendar is 
influencing NATO leaders' thinking because of the lead time 
required to reach either of two outcomes in Kosovo before the 
typically harsh Balkan winter sets in -- the resettlement of ethnic 
Albanian refugees in Kosovo under a peace agreement, or entering 
Kosovo forcibly to end the conflict. 

</P>
<P>
	Teen's Home Part of Shooting Probe  
</P>
<P>
	CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- The parents' home is again playing a part in  
an investigation into the latest shooting rampage by a teen-ager at 
an American high school. The locked gun-cabinet of a teen's 
stepfather provided the weaponry used in the shooting at a suburban 
Atlanta high school in which six students were injured, police 
said. Thomas Solomon Jr., 15, allegedly used a .357 Magnum revolver 
and a sawed-off rifle in the attack at Heritage High School. None 
of the injuries were considered serious. It was the sixth mass 
shooting at an American high school or middle school since October 
1997. 

</P>
<P>
	Soap Star Lucci Finally Wins Emmy  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- After 18 nominations and 18 losses, soap star  
Susan Lucci won the Daytime Emmy award for best actress tonight. 
Lucci plays the villainous Erica Kane on ``All My Children.'' She 
sobbed as she received a standing ovation. ``Thank you very much. I 
truly never believed that this would happen,'' she said. 

</P>
<P>
	First Lady Visits New Mexico  
</P>
<P>
	ACOMA PUEBLO, N.M. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton toured an  
ancient Indian village atop a sandstone mesa today to promote the 
preservation of America's past, including a 360-year-old mission 
church. ``When we talk about saving America's treasures, we have to 
begin by saving the first Americans' treasures,'' Mrs. Clinton said 
at the Acoma Pueblo. Mrs. Clinton visited Acoma, Santa Fe and 
Albuquerque today on a tour of the Southwest. She is headed to Mesa 
Verde National Park in Colorado for a tour of Cliff Palace 
tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	FDA Approves New Painkiller Vioxx  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government has approved a new painkiller  
that could provide stiff competition to one of the nation's 
best-selling drugs. Merck &AMP; Co.'s Vioxx was approved today, and the 
company said the prescription drug should be in pharmacies by 
mid-June. The Food and Drug Administration said it approved Vioxx 
for people with osteoarthritis, for women with menstrual pain and 
for adults with other acute pain. Vioxx is a type of drug known as 
a Cox-2 inhibitor and is the second such drug on the market, 
following Monsanto's Celebrex. 

</P>
<P>
	FAA Clears New National Airlines  
</P>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- National Airlines -- a new airline with an old  
name -- has been cleared for takeoff. The Las Vegas-based carrier 
has been authorized by the Federal Aviation Administration to begin 
passenger service next week. National will launch service Thursday 
with daily flights to Chicago's Midway Airport and Los Angeles. 
Service to New York and San Francisco is scheduled to begin June 14 
and June 24, respectively. 

</P>
<P>
	Sanders Marries New York Model  
</P>
<P>
	CARROLLTON, Texas (AP) -- Dallas Cowboys star cornerback Deion  
Sanders was married today to New York actress and model Pilar 
Biggers. Sanders, 31, and Biggers, 25, were wed in a small private 
ceremony on Nassau's Paradise Island in the Bahamas, according to a 
release from Bishop T.D. Jakes. The bride, represented by the Ford 
Agency, has done editorial, catalog and runway modeling for 
designers Tommy Hilfiger, Guess and Richard Tyler. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Down 37.46  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors worried about the effect rising  
interest rates might have on big-name stocks today moved money into 
small-cap issues. The Dow industrials ended at 10,829.28, down 
37.46. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 1,599-1,327. The 
technology-heavy Nasdaq fell 22.09 to 2,520.14. 

</P>
<P>
	Pacers Bury 76ers 97-86  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- With 29 points from Reggie Miller and a  
meticulous attack befitting their playoff experience, the Pacers 
moved one game away from sweeping the Philadelphia 76ers with a 
97-86 victory in the Eastern Conference semifinals Friday night. 
The Pacers, who survived late runs by the Sixers in Games 1 and 2, 
did the same for the final three quarters of Game 3. This time, 
they never gave up the lead and can sweep Philadelphia with a 
victory in Game 4 on Sunday. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  

</P>
</TEXT>
