<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Leetch Nears Deal With Rangers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Rangers have all but wrapped up a  
new contract with all-star defenseman Brian Leetch. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to say 100 percent, but barring something  
unforseen, the deal should be completed shortly,'' Rangers 
spokesman John Rosasco said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosasco said that an announcement on Leetch's signing was  
``imminent.'' The Rangers and (Leetch's agent) ``Jay Grossman have 
been working hard the last 10 days. It just came together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rosasco would not confirm that Leetch had agreed to a four-year  
contract worth $35 million, as had been reported in the Daily News, 
or that a news conference would be scheduled Monday to announce the 
signing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to say ... until Brian signs a contract,''  
Rosasco said. Leetch is currently on vacation and expected back 
after the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Grossman was not immediately available for comment.  
</P>
<P>
	With the retirement of Wayne Gretzky, and the Rangers missing  
the playoffs for a second year in a row, it became imperative for 
them to sign Leetch, their captain and highest profile player along 
with goaltender Mike Richter. Richter is currently under a 
long-term contract signed last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Leetch wants to stay with the team he has played with since  
coming to New York following the 1988 Olympics. In re-signing with 
the Rangers, he will miss an opportunity to test the free-agent 
market and become perhaps the first $10 million player in hockey. 
</P>
<P>
	The News said the agreement to the record-setting contract was  
reached Wednesday night. Leetch's $8.75 million annual salary would 
be the highest in team history and the highest among NHL 
defenseman. 
</P>
<P>
	There were many teams interested in Leetch, who has won the  
Norris Trophy as the NHL's top defenseman two times and generally 
regarded as one of the best players in the game for 12 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Leetch totaled 55 points -- fifth among defenseman -- this season.  
He is third on the Rangers' career scoring list with 177 goals and 
578 assists for 755 points -- leading all defensemen in the team's 
history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 08:52:48 </DATE_TIME>
