<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Orchestra Gives Concert in Hanoi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HANOI, Vietnam (AP) -- Young communists in red scarves, girls in  
frilly party dresses and a whole lot of grown-ups flocked to 
Hanoi's opera house today for a children's concert given by the 
Philadelphia Orchestra. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, the first U.S. symphony orchestra to visit Vietnam,  
decided to give the free concert as a gift to the children of Hanoi 
ahead of a regular performance Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``Music is the only language in the world everyone can  
understand,'' conductor Wolfgang Sawallisch said before the 
hourlong performance. 
</P>
<P>
	Sponsored by Coca-Cola, whose sign hung prominently over the  
stage of the gilded French colonial rococo opera house, the concert 
began with the American and Vietnamese national anthems. 
</P>
<P>
	The program included easy-to-listen-to classics such as Dvorak's  
``Carnival Overture'' and Beethoven's ``Symphony No. 2'' before 
wrapping up with a rousing rendition of D'Souza's ``Liberty Bell 
March.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 600 people attended the concert and applauded the  
conductor as he introduced each piece. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the concert began, 16-year-old Ngo Thu Trang said she  
hoped it would pave the way for more visits by American groups, but 
preferably rock bands -- ``like the Backstreet Boys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But at the end, Vietnamese concertgoers said they thoroughly  
enjoyed their first live classical concert. 
</P>
<P>
	Tickets were meant to be free for the public, but several  
concertgoers got theirs through friends working in the government 
or at local companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside, women sold the supposedly free tickets for $10 -- more  
than a week's salary for an average Vietnamese factory worker. 
</P>
<P>
	The orchestra also will perform in Ho Chi Minh City before  
moving on for concerts in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, and Taipei, 
Taiwan. It already has performed in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The Philadelphia Orchestra, which will have its 100th  
anniversary season next year, also was the first U.S. orchestra to 
go to China, in 1973. 
</P>
<P>
	It is accompanying Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge's trade and  
culture mission to Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
