<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bay Area Baseball Competing Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Baseball in the Bay Area was an afterthought during the  
multimillion-dollar spending spree in the offseason. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Brown went to Los Angeles for $105 million. Anaheim signed  
Mo Vaughn for $80 million. Randy Johnson got $52.4 million to go 
Arizona. Texas brought back Rafael Palmeiro for $45 million. 
</P>
<P>
	While their division rivals were signing the most expensive free  
agents, Oakland and San Francisco were hunting the bargain racks 
for overlooked veterans and minor league free agents. 
</P>
<P>
	Their most expensive additions? Tony Phillips, who signed for  
$700,000 with the Athletics, and Scott Servais, who got $500,000 
from the Giants. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite being last in their divisions in payroll, the teams are  
doing well so far this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't concern ourselves with how much money we spend,''  
Giants first baseman J.T. Snow said. 
</P>
<P>
	San Francisco, which entered the weekend a half-game behind  
Arizona in the NL West, has been in first or second place all but 
11 days since April 12, 1997. Oakland was second in the AL West 
going into the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Good young pitchers have helped the Giants, who lost their only  
star, Barry Bonds, to an elbow injury last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Russ Ortiz has a good fastball, a durable arm and is 5-2 with a  
2.53 ERA. Chris Brock, discarded by the Braves, is 4-3 with a 4.01 
ERA, and Joe Nathan, a converted shortstop who gave up baseball for 
a year, has shown a lively arm and is 2-0 with a 2.42 ERA. 
</P>
<P>
	``On paper, we don't look as good as other teams, but when we're  
on the field, we can play together and that's the key,'' San 
Francisco's Stan Javier said. ``It never bothered us that we were 
picked to finish last. It's better that people take us lightly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After winning the NL West in 1997 and losing a one-game  
wild-card playoff to the Cubs last season, Dusty Baker's Giants 
probably can't be called a big surprise. 
</P>
<P>
	But no one expected Oakland to contend. The A's finished last in  
1998, put ace Kenny Rogers on the trading block in spring training 
and have a skimpy $22.8 million payroll. 
</P>
<P>
	However, an odd mix of old and new -- the opening day roster had  
five players younger than 25 and five older than 37 -- has worked 
despite slow starts by Rogers, Tom Candiotti and Rookie of the Year 
Ben Grieve, who is hitting .144. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thing is we are winning and we still haven't swung the  
bats all that well,'' Mike MacFarlane said of the A's, who are last 
in the AL in batting average. ``We're kind of waiting for all that 
to jell and come together. When that happens, we'll get on a good 
roll again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips, who has improved nearly every team he has gone to with  
his patience at the plate and aggressiveness everywhere else, was 
baseball's best free-agent bargain. 
</P>
<P>
	The 40-year-old Phillips seems to get better with age. He has a  
.389 on-base percentage, 33 runs and a surprising nine homers. But 
it's his influence on the young players that might be most 
important. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's one of those guys; you hate playing against him but you  
love playing with him,'' MacFarlane said. ``He's a leader on the 
team and an example. You can't find a better one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The A's have also gotten surprise production out of John Jaha  
(.343, 8, 27), who nearly retired because of foot injuries, and 
Olmedo Saenz (.300, 2, 15), signed as a minor league free agent 
from the White Sox. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody is surprised at how well we're going but me,''  
Phillips said. ``Every spring training, you go into the season with 
the attitude that you want to win your division and go to the 
playoffs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While that still seems improbable, the A's do have one advantage  
over their rivals in the AL West, who must try to trade for 
pitching down the stretch. Oakland has last year's No. 1 pick Mark 
Mulder (2-2, 3.73) and Tim Hudson (2-0, 2.83) waiting at Triple-A 
Vancouver. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *PINS AND NEEDLES:* After two major operations in the last three  
years and thousands of pitches by his right arm, David Cone was 
supposed to be in the twilight of his career, not at the peak. 
</P>
<P>
	But a new offseason plan has given the 36-year-old pitcher a  
little extra life on his fastball and more command on the mound. 
For the first time, Cone didn't pick up a baseball at all this 
offseason, and he began acupuncture treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	It seems to have paid off. Through the first six weeks of the  
season, Cone is 4-2 and leads the majors with a 1.69 ERA for the 
Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just don't get as sore for whatever reason,'' said Cone, who  
is able to throw between starts again, something he rarely did last 
year. ``I want to be in this for the long haul. The real test comes 
in September, but I just know I'm better this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cone gives a lot of the credit to acupuncture. He has even flown  
up from Florida the husband-and-wife team that worked on him this 
winter for some in-season treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	``They had never been to New York before, it was kind of cute,''  
Cone said. `'I took them to Chinatown.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *NO EXCUSES:* Expos manager Felipe Alou doesn't want to hear his  
players gripe anymore about the small crowds in Montreal. 
</P>
<P>
	Dustin Hermanson and other players have complained about the  
lack of crowd support. The Expos have averaged only 9,630 fans in 
their first 22 home games amid rumors they will relocate after the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to hear players criticizing the crowd or our  
situation here -- it's not fair,'' Alou said. ``The question I would 
ask myself is: What am I doing for the cause? 
</P>
<P>
	``If I go 3-for-15 or bat .180, I don't want to say to my club  
that the only reason I didn't win was because there were no people 
there. That record will be there forever. There will be no 
asterisk. It won't say how many people were watching.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At least one of Alou's players agrees.  
</P>
<P>
	``We have no excuses,'' Michael Barrett said. ``We go on the  
road and there's big crowds and our road record is no better.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BASE HITS:* Three top left-handed pitching prospects,  
baseball's rarest commodity, got promoted this week. Atlanta called 
up Bruce Chen (3-2, 2.30 in Triple-A) to the majors Friday. St. 
Louis' Rick Ankiel (6-0, 0.91 in Double-A) was promoted to Triple-A 
Memphis and Baltimore moved Matt Riley to Double-A Bowie after he 
posted an 0.57 ERA in his last four starts at Class A. ... Not only 
did Don Zimmer keep the Yankees in first place for Joe Torre, he 
added 21 wins to Torre's career record. According to the Elias 
Sports Bureau, the Yankees 21-15 record under Zimmer will count 
officially for Torre. Stat of the week: Pudge Rodriguez has stolen 
11 bases while allowing only three while he is behind the plate for 
Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	 *End Adv weekend editions May 22-23    	
</P>
