<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that have been moving substantially or  
trading heavily today on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq 
Stock Market. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	
</P>
<P>
	Merck, down 15/16 to 71 5/16  
</P>
<P>
	The nation's biggest pharmaceutical maker, based in Whitehouse  
Station, N.J., won Food and Drug Administration approval for its 
new pain pill Vioxx. The drug will compete Monsanto's and Pfizer's 
arthritis drug Celebrex. 

</P>
<P>
	Fresh Del Monte Produce, down 7/8 to 13 5/8  
</P>
<P>
	The Coral Gables, Fla., produce company said weak banana sales  
caused it to lower its second-quarter earnings estimate.The company 
expects to report earnings between 55 cents and 75 cents a share 
for the second quarter. Analysts were predicting 83 cents a share. 

</P>
<P>
	Keebler Foods, up 15/16 to 33 3/16  
</P>
<P>
	The Elmhurst, Ill., cookie maker reported better-than-expected  
profits in its fiscal first-quarter ended April 24. The company's 
earnings per share was 37 cents, beating analysts' estimates by two 
cents. Sales in the company's Specialty unit, which manufactures 
Girl Scout cookies, rose 99 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Chock Full O'Nuts, up 3/16 to 10 9/16  
</P>
<P>
	The New York-based coffee maker recommended shareholders reject  
an offer by Sara Lee Corp. to acquire the company for $10.50 a 
share. The board said Sara Lee offer did not meet the potential 
value of the company. 

</P>
<P>
	Boston Scientific, down 2 to 41 1/4  
</P>
<P>
	The Natick, Mass., medical-device maker said its new coronary  
stent, which props open clogged arteries, was approved by the U.S. 
Food and Drug Administration. 

</P>
<P>
                            	 *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
	Hauppauge Digital Inc., up 10 19/32 to 23 3/32  
</P>
<P>
	The No. 1 maker of video cards for personal computers, based in  
New York, will announce a joint venture soon with a large Internet 
company that broadcasts streaming-media programming, Business Week 
reported Thursday. 

</P>
<P>
	Priceline.com, up 6 1/8 to 140 1/2  
</P>
<P>
	The Stamford, Conn.-based travel Internet company signed a  
one-year contract to provide travel services to Major League 
Soccer. The deal puts Priceline.com's logo and promotional 
information on various league media. The value of the deal was not 
disclosed. 


</P>
</TEXT>
