<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Prison Staffer Probed in Escape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- A former prison psychologist who allegedly sent  
a convicted robber revealing photos of herself is under 
investigation on suspicion of helping him and another inmate make 
their getaway after an escape. 
</P>
<P>
	State police are investigating Elizabeth Feil, 43, in connection  
with the escape Tuesday night of Byron Lester Smoot and Gregory Lee 
Lawrence, said Ms. Feil's lawyer, Isaac Dixon. Both inmates were 
recaptured two days later. 
</P>
<P>
	Dixon would not provide details regarding Ms. Feil or disclose  
her whereabouts. Police said the inmates had at least one 
accomplice, but they wouldn't confirm whether Ms. Feil was thought 
to have been involved. 
</P>
<P>
	Glenn Bosshard, Ms. Feil's husband, said two state police  
officers came to his Annapolis home early Wednesday morning and 
told him his wife was a suspect. The police cited photographs of 
Ms. Feil, dressed in black lingerie and a garter belt, found in 
Smoot's cell, Bosshard said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bosshard said he took the photographs of his wife 11 years ago  
while they were vacationing. He said that based on the photographs, 
he believes his wife had an affair with Smoot while he was behind 
bars. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are estranged as of two days ago,'' he said Friday. ``Up  
until that point, I thought we were deeply in love. You have no 
idea how devastated I am by this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lawrence, 39, was serving a life sentence for murder after  
shooting a man and stealing his shoes in 1978. Smoot, 38, was 
imprisoned for a rash of armed robberies and was sentenced to 29 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoot and Lawrence escaped Tuesday night when they walked past  
an unmanned guard tower next to the front gate at the Maryland 
Correctional Institute, a medium-security prison in Jessup. They 
scaled two fences, one topped with razor wire, where police found 
blood. 
</P>
<P>
	A bloodhound picked up a scent that led to a phone booth about  
two miles away, where police suspect one or both inmates got a 
ride. 
</P>
<P>
	Both were recaptured Thursday afternoon in Baltimore, where they  
lived before going to prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Bosshard said his wife agreed to help police find the two  
prisoners if she would be free from prosecution. It was not known 
if such a deal was made. 
</P>
<P>
	Bosshard said his wife worked for the Patuxent Institution, a  
maximum-security prison in Jessup, but was fired last year. It was 
not known if she currently has a job. 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland correctional officials would not comment on Ms. Feil's  
employment. 
</P>
<P>
	``She told me she had been fired because she was trying to  
institute a program for better inmate conditions. I'm not sure of 
anything she told me now,'' Bosshard said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
