<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fugitives May Have Jumped Wyo. Train </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RAWLINS, Wyo. (AP) -- Authorities feared today that two  
survivalists suspected of killing a Colorado policeman last year 
jumped a train to elude capture this week in Wyoming. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're pretty confident we did a pretty good job of covering  
what we could, given the darkness and all,'' said Carbon County 
Sheriff Jerry Colson. ``We were all over the county.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Deputies continued searching today for Alan Pilon and Jason  
McVean. Authorities suspect they robbed a restaurant bar Wednesday 
near South Pass City, a ghost town that has been restored as 
tourist attraction in the mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	Colson said he feared that Pilon and McVean hopped an eastbound  
train late Wednesday. Deputies were checking transients and 
passengers on Union Pacific trains. 
</P>
<P>
	Pilon and McVean are accused of killing Dale Claxton in Cortez,  
Colo., on May 29, 1998. The officer was slain with automatic 
gunfire during a traffic stop before he could unbuckle his seat 
belt. In an ensuing chase and shootout, two sheriff's deputies were 
wounded. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of officers couldn't find the men after they  
disappeared into the rugged terrain of the Four Corners region, 
where New Mexico, Colorado, Utah and Arizona meet. An alleged 
accomplice was found a few days later, dead from a self-inflicted 
gunshot wound. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspects in the Wyoming robbery wore military boots and ski  
masks and took about $500. No one was hurt. They escaped in a 
stolen white truck and abandoned the vehicle at a gas refinery 
before fleeing on foot, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Colson said a caretaker at the plant identified the suspects as  
Pilon and McVean based on photographs. Authorities were awaiting 
the results of tests on fingerprints from the truck to verify the 
suspects' identity. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
