<DOCNO> APW19990521.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 15:55:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Stars-Avalanche Set To Face Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Ed Belfour of the Dallas Stars is intent on  
shaking his reputation as a goaltender who can't win the big one. 
</P>
<P>
	There would be no better way to do it than by outdueling  
Colorado's Patrick Roy in the Western Conference finals. 
</P>
<P>
	When the series begins Saturday, Belfour and Roy will be going  
head-to-head in the playoffs for the first time since a 1996 
second-round series between Colorado and Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Belfour and the Blackhawks won the first game. Then he  
contracted food poisoning and missed Game 2. When he returned, 
Belfour played great, but Roy was even better as the Avalanche went 
on to win the Stanley Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	That title further cemented Roy's status as the gold standard of  
goalies. It was the third time his name went on the trophy and it 
came under the pressure of having been acquired at midseason 
specifically for that type of postseason leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	Roy did it again last round as Colorado went from being down 2-0  
as the series shifted to Detroit, then winning four straight to 
eliminate the two-time defending champions. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no better playoff performer than Patrick,'' Avalanche  
coach Bob Harley said. ``He feels that pressure. He lives for that 
pressure. He can handle that pressure while raising his own game 
and force the guys around him to raise their own game. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is what a true leader will do for a hockey club.''  
</P>
<P>
	Dallas gave Belfour a three-year, $10 million contract last  
season to be that kind of leader. He lived up to the challenge as 
the Stars rode their hot goalie to the conference finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, with the series 1-1, Belfour made mental blunders in  
consecutive games that led directly to Detroit goals. The Red Wings 
won the series in six games and back came the talk that the 
ultra-intense Belfour couldn't put a team over the top. 
</P>
<P>
	Belfour's pattern of grand success followed by failure began in  
1992 when he helped Chicago win 11 straight playoff games, then was 
swept by Pittsburgh in the finals. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, Belfour became just the fifth goalie with multiple  
40-win seasons, then lost four straight in the playoffs. Another 
one-round exit followed in '94. Chicago reached the finals again in 
1995, but Detroit won three overtime games to advance. 
</P>
<P>
	So far this postseason, Belfour has been superb. His 1.68  
goals-against average is best among the four remaining playoff 
goalies and he and Roy are tied for the best save percentage at 
.929. 
</P>
<P>
	``Little things aren't bothering him,'' said Mike Keane, who was  
traded to Colorado with Roy in 1995 and joined Dallas last season. 
``Some teams have tried to get under Eddie's skin, but he's not 
really worried about stuff like he was last year. He won't take a 
whack at a guy or start chirping at them. He's just stopping pucks. 
That's what we need from Eddie Belfour.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said Belfour won't be spooked by  
having Roy in the opposite net, but also said he doesn't expect his 
goalie to be motivated by Roy's presence. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Eddie's gone a long ways past that now,'' Hitchcock  
said. ``Eddie's more into the light at the end of the tunnel. I 
think his own personal challenges are within, and they're all 
structured around our team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just see him more focused on his job and not on the  
peripheral stuff that comes with this business. I watch his 
routine. He wastes no extra energy on any other area that is not 
relevant to winning hockey games. I think being able to do that is 
what makes special athletes special.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 15:55:47 </DATE_TIME>
