<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Janis Joplin Did Not Live There </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A drug rehab center in the city's  
Haight-Ashbury district isn't in Janis Joplin's old house after 
all. 
</P>
<P>
	The Golden Gate Community rehab center, tapping local legend,  
said in a news release earlier this week that it is operating out 
of a Victorian home where the singer who died of a heroin overdose 
in 1970 once lived. 
</P>
<P>
	But her '60s cohorts soon turned up to set the record straight:  
She lived next door. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, Ms. Joplin's California driver's license listed her  
address as 122 Lyon. The center is at 124 Lyon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 23:51:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Record Tax Surplus Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Alas, there was no April budget surprise this  
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury Department reported Friday that the federal  
government ran a large surplus last month of $113.5 billion. But 
unlike in the past two years, that was right in line with 
expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997 and 1998, huge surpluses far surpassing forecasts were  
recorded for April, including a record $124.6 billion surplus for 
April 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	That unforeseen revenue, which came is as millions of taxpayers  
filed income tax returns, helped congressional and White House 
negotiators reach agreement in 1997 on a five-year plan to balance 
the budget, then to actually accomplish the feat ahead of schedule 
in 1998, when the government recorded a $64.9 billion surplus, the 
first time that had occurred in 29 years. 
</P>
<P>
	But the $113.4 billion surplus for April this year was slightly  
lower than many private economists had forecasted, and it was 8.9 
percent below last year's record. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, private economists said the federal government is likely  
to achieve an even bigger annual surplus this year, projected by 
the Clinton administration to reach $79 billion for the fiscal 
year, which ends on Sept. 30. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first seven months of the fiscal year, through April,  
the surplus totaled $64.7 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are on track to reach the largest annual budget surplus  
ever,'' President Clinton said in a statement Friday after the 
April budget figures were released. But he added, ``Despite the 
good news, this is not a time for complacency.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the new figures dashed hopes that extra revenue  
would make it easier to provide tax cuts or shore up Social 
Security. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anybody who was hoping for a sudden boost, a much bigger  
surplus that would provide them a little room to do something, it's 
just not going to be there,'' said Stanley Collender, senior vice 
president of the consulting firm Fleishman Hillard. 
</P>
<P>
	One reason for the lower April surplus this year as compared to  
last April was an increase in tax refunds of almost 59 percent, to 
$36.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	That reflects the new $400 per child credit and new credits for  
higher education as well as the increasing popularity of electronic 
filing and direct deposit, which offer speedier refunds than paper 
tax returns and paper checks. 
</P>
<P>
	Year to date, tax refunds are up nearly 33 percent compared to  
the corresponding period in fiscal 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 03:34:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Leetch Said To Resign With Rangers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Rangers and captain Brian Leetch  
have agreed to a four-year, $35 million contract, the Daily News 
reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement to the record-setting contract was reached  
Wednesday night, but won't be formally signed or announced until a 
press conference at Madison Square Garden on Monday, the newspaper 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Leetch's $8.75 million annual salary would be the highest in  
team history and the highest among all NHL defenseman. 
</P>
<P>
	The 31-year-old Leetch scored 55 points -- fifth among defenseman  
-- this season. He is third on the Rangers' career scoring list with 
755 points -- leading all defenseman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
