<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Details of Gun-Control Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Some questions from polls released this week on gun control and  
school violence. When results don't total 100 percent, the 
remainder did not know or refused to answer. 

</P>
<P>
	--What do you think is more important -- to protect the right of  
Americans to own guns, or to control gun ownership? (Pew Research 
Center) 
</P>
<P>
	Protect rights to own guns, 30 percent; control gun ownership,  
65 percent. The number who want to give priority to controlling gun 
ownership rose 8 percentage points since a poll in December 1993. 

</P>
<P>
	--Do you favor or oppose stricter gun control laws in this  
country? (ABC-Washington Post) 
</P>
<P>
	Favor -- 67 percent; oppose, 31 percent. That's about the same  
level of support as when that question was asked in March 1993. 

</P>
<P>
	--Would you favor or oppose a law that banned the sale of  
handguns? (Pew Research Center) 
</P>
<P>
	Favor, 44 percent; oppose 50 percent. That level of opposition  
is the same as in a December 1993 poll. 

</P>
<P>
	--Do you think that TV news is too full of violence, or not? (Pew  
Research Center) 
</P>
<P>
	TV news too full of violence, 63 percent; News not too full of  
violence, 33 percent. The 63 percent is an 11-point increase from 
1993 in the number of people concerned about TV news violence. 

</P>
<P>
	--Are there any groups at your school who you think are violent  
or capable of violence based on what they do, what they say, or 
what they claim they will do? (Gallup poll of teens.) 
</P>
<P>
	Yes, 46 percent; no, 54 percent.  

</P>
<P>
	--Which political party, the Democrats or the Republicans, do you  
trust to do a better job of handling the issue of gun control? (ABC 
News) 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats, 39 percent; Republicans, 31 percent.  

</P>
<P>
	The Gallup telephone poll of 403 teens, ages 13-17, was  
conducted May 5 to May 17. It has a margin of error of plus or 
minus 5 percentage points. The Pew telephone poll of 1,179 adults 
was taken May 12-16 and has an error margin of plus or minus 3.5 
percentage points. The ABC-Washington Post telephone poll of 761 
adults was taken Sunday and has an error margin of plus or minus 
3.5 percentage points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
