<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Climbers Recuperate After Rescue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- Three British climbers were plucked off  
North America's highest peak after a blizzard forced them to 
retreat just 300 feet from the summit. 
</P>
<P>
	Helicopters on Friday ferried the three to a hospital to  
recuperate after battling hypothermia since the storm hit Mount 
McKinley on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	As the group tried to retreat from the blizzard, Nigel Vardy,  
nearly blinded by frostbite, stumbled. That sent him and his 
roped-together companions, Antony Hollinshead and Steve Ball, on a 
300-foot tumble. 
</P>
<P>
	They called for help. While they waited for rescue, temperatures  
dipped to 30 degrees below zero, with 50 mph winds. The men had 
taken no sleeping bags or shelter on their final push for the 
summit. 
</P>
<P>
	Badly frostbitten and exhausted, Vardy, 29, and Hollinshead, 33,  
were picked up from the mountain early Friday in a daring 
high-altitude helicopter rescue. 
</P>
<P>
	Ball, in better shape, had tried to descend to a ranger camp  
Thursday afternoon for help. But he didn't make it and was found 
Friday afternoon at the 17,500-foot level, severely hypothermic, 
dehydrated and with a broken left leg, said Jane Tranel, a Park 
Service spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
	Ball, 42, was in critical condition Friday night, a nursing  
supervisor said, and doctors were still trying to determine the 
extent of his injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Vardy was in serious condition Friday with severe frostbite.  
Hollinshead, also frostbitten and with an injured shoulder, was in 
fair condition. 
</P>
<P>
	About 350 climbers now are on Mount McKinley. Ten people have  
reached the summit so far this spring, said Tranel of the Park 
Service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
