<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 07:32:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Breaking Senate Ties Is Gore's Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore's tie-breaking vote on  
gun control legislation Thursday was his fourth such vote in more 
than six years in office, according to research by his office and 
the Senate Library. 
</P>
<P>
	The job of breaking ties in the Senate is set out in Article I  
of the Constitution. Vice presidents have cast deciding votes 235 
times since John Adams performed that duty for the first time on 
July 18, 1789. 
</P>
<P>
	Statistics compiled by the chamber's foremost historian, Sen.  
Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., show Adams, with 29 tie-breaking votes, 
holds the record for the most deciding votes cast by any vice 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	Before his vote Thursday, Gore broke two tied votes in 1993 on  
President Clinton's deficit reduction package. In 1994, he cast the 
deciding vote on a spending bill for veterans, housing and 
environmental programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
