<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Bombs exploded in a working-class  
neighborhood, wounding 21 people and damaging 14 houses, officials 
said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The blasts occurred Thursday in Florencia, 325 miles southwest  
of Bogota and capital of Caqueta state. Police defused a third bomb 
that failed to explode. 
</P>
<P>
	Florencia is 55 miles from a region cleared of government troops  
in November as a concession to the Revolutionary Armed Forces of 
Colombia, or FARC, the country's oldest and largest rebel band. 
</P>
<P>
	Peace talks aimed at ending Colombia's 35-year civil war were  
launched in January. 
</P>
<P>
	A local military commander blamed FARC guerrillas for the bomb  
attack, but no group had claimed responsibility. Right-wing 
paramilitary leaders have repeatedly threatened to attack the 
region, a longtime rebel stronghold. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- A military helicopter ferrying  
veterans to the 50th anniversary celebration of their military 
school crashed Friday, killing three. 
</P>
<P>
	The helicopter, coming from Sao Paulo, was trying to land when  
it hit a tree and exploded on the grounds of the Air Force Cadet 
Training School in Barbacena, 124 miles northwest of Rio de 
Janeiro, the air force press office said. 
</P>
<P>
	Three others aboard the aircraft survived and were hospitalized  
in serious condition. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Argentina's labor minister  
abruptly resigned Friday, the second cabinet minister in a month to 
leave the administration of President Carlos Menem. 
</P>
<P>
	Calls for Antonio Erman Gonzalez to step down arose after local  
newspapers reported that he began collecting a monthly pension 
worth $8,000 in March on top of his regular salary. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez denied the accusations. However, he said Menem accepted  
the resignation ``because the retirement issue was represented to 
the public as something incorrect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez is the second minister to resign from Menem's cabinet  
this month, following the departure of Education Minister Susana 
Decibe. She stepped down in opposition to $1 billion in 
controversial budget cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexico's interior minister resigned the  
nation's second-highest office Friday to campaign for the ruling 
party's presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Under party rules approved last week, Francisco Labastida --  
widely viewed as President Ernesto Zedillo's favorite for the 
nomination of the Institutional Revolutionary Party -- was required 
to resign before the primary campaign officially opens Aug. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	His post as Cabinet secretary in charge of domestic political  
and security affairs will be filled by Diodoro Carrasco, 45, who 
until late last year was governor of the southern state Oaxaca, one 
of Mexico's poorest. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Despite the steepest quarterly drop in  
production in more than 20 years, Colombia's economy will still 
grow in 1999, a top economic official said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Planning Minister Jaime Ruiz said the country's gross domestic  
product fell 4.8 percent in first three months of the year, 
compared to the same period in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-month decline was the fourth consecutive quarter of  
recession in a country which has traditionally had one of Latin 
America's most stable and vibrant economies. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the drop, Ruiz said the government is standing by its  
forecast of at least 1.3 percent growth for the year. He predicted 
a turnaround based on rising exports and strengthening prices for 
Colombia's main legal exports, oil and coffee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
