<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Agent Says Lewis Was Entering Prime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Had the late Celtics star Reggie Lewis lived and  
played basketball into his late 30s, he might have earned more than 
$117 million in contracts and endorsements, a sports agent 
testified today. 
</P>
<P>
	The testimony came during the trial of a malpractice suit  
brought by Lewis' widow, Donna Harris-Lewis, against Drs. Gilbert 
Mudge, Mark Creager and Peter Friedman. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis collapsed and died in 1993 at 27 while shooting baskets,  
and Harris-Lewis claims the doctors misdiagnosed and mistreated his 
heart condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Los Angeles-based agent Arn Tellem told the Suffolk County jury  
that Lewis was ``entering the prime of his career'' and might have 
earned $113.5 million from his playing and product endorsements. 
</P>
<P>
	Tellem also estimated that Lewis could have earned an additional  
$5 million from working as a sports commentator, bringing his 
potential earnings to more than $117 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Reggie Lewis had a brilliant career ahead of him as a  
basketball player,'' said Tellem, who also represents Indiana 
Pacers star Reggie Miller. ``There was no reason to believe 
(Lewis') career wouldn't have gone on for a long time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But defense attorney William Dailey questioned Tellem's figures,  
pointing out that between 1987 and 1993 Lewis had earned only 
$15,000 in endorsements from autograph shows and clinics. 
</P>
<P>
	Dailey also questioned whether Lewis could have earned millions  
as a color commentator, saying only a few such jobs are available 
and salaries are not always so high. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, Dailey said, former Celtics star Cedric Maxwell  
makes only $75,000 annually for doing commentary for the Celtics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
