<DOCNO> APW19990521.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 14:22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unknown Soldiers May Be Identified </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon for the first time will attempt  
to use DNA technology to identify remains of U.S. troops killed in 
the Korean War and buried as ``unknowns'' at the National Memorial 
Cemetery in Hawaii. 
</P>
<P>
	About 70 sets of remains are candidates to be disinterred at the  
cemetery, commonly called the Punchbowl, where 864 remains of 
unidentified soldiers from the Korean War are buried. They were 
turned over to the United States by North Korea after a cease-fire 
ended the conflict in 1953, but the remains could not be 
identified. 
</P>
<P>
	Only the 70 are considered candidates because the records  
associated with them, such as military unit or recovery location, 
suggest a name, Pentagon spokesman Larry Greer said. Name 
associations are vital because the DNA technique for positive 
identification requires a comparison blood sample from the maternal 
bloodline. 
</P>
<P>
	The names were not released. Greer said not all of the families  
had been contacted. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Dunton of the Korean War/Cold War Association of the Missing  
said her organization and others have lobbied the Pentagon for 
years to use DNA testing more aggressively on Korean War remains. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an excellent thing,'' she said in an interview. ``It  
needs to be done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's announcement follows the successful identification last  
year of Air Force 1st Lt. Michael Blassie, the former Vietnam War 
unknown from the Tomb of the Unknowns at Arlington National 
Cemetery. The same mitochondrial DNA technology used in the Blassie 
case will be used in the Korean War cases. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blassie case stirred emotional debates about whether the  
Tomb of the Unknowns should be disturbed, whether a replacement set 
of unknown remains from Vietnam should be put in, and, later, 
whether the Defense Department should set a policy of disinterring 
potentially identifiable remains at war cemeteries. 
</P>
<P>
	The work will be done by forensics experts at the military's  
Central Identification Laboratory in Hawaii. The Pentagon certified 
the use of mitochondrial DNA testing as a reliable forensic tool in 
1995 and has used the technique to identify some Korean War remains 
turned over by North Korea in the early 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	Greer said no firm timetable had been set for beginning the  
disinterments at the Punchbowl cemetery. 
</P>
<P>
	``The records associated with each of the unknown remains in the  
Punchbowl cemetery will undergo rigorous evaluation before a 
decision is made to disinter,'' the Pentagon said in its 
announcement. 
</P>
<P>
	The 864 sets of remains at the Punchbowl are among the  
approximately 8,200 men listed as unaccounted for from the Korean 
War. Most of the rest are in North Korea, and the Pentagon has been 
working with the North Korean government in recent years to recover 
remains at former battle sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Eventually the Pentagon may disinter remains from World War II  
cemeteries, Greer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990521.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-21 13:21:59 </DATE_TIME>
