<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Bomb Threats at Kmart in Michigan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TROY, Mich. (AP) -- Kmart Corp. closed its suburban Detroit  
headquarters and sent 3,500 employees home early on Friday 
afternoon after receiving two bomb threats, the nation's No. 3 
retailer said. 
</P>
<P>
	The first threat came in about 7:30 a.m. and the second shortly  
after noon EDT, company spokesman Stephen Pagnani said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We did evacuate the building and are sending people home for  
the day,'' Pagnani said. 
</P>
<P>
	The first caller said a bomb would explode at 9 a.m., the  
spokesman said. The employees were evacuated at 8:30 a.m., police 
swept the building and failed to find any bomb, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Employees remained outside for about an hour, Pagnani said. But  
Kmart got a second threat shortly after noon and decided to send 
the employees home early, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he had no idea why the caller or callers may have made  
the threats. However, Kmart has received more than 200 angry calls 
this week from National Rifle Association supporters following talk 
show host Rosie O'Donnell's verbal tussle with actor Tom Selleck on 
her show Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Kmart said it had no plans to fire O'Donnell from her position  
as a celebrity spokeswoman for the company. Selleck recently filmed 
an ad for the NRA. 
</P>
<P>
	Troy police did not immediately respond to calls seeking  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Kmart is the nation's third-largest retailer, behind Wal-Mart  
Corp. and Sears Roebuck and Co. Kmart has 2,162 stores in all 50 
states, Puerto Rico, Guam and the Virgin Islands. 

</P>
</TEXT>
